{"type":"text","timestamp":1782532211330,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"id":"prt_f0732b89c001u3iNhs5LKzMPQt","messageID":"msg_f073297d6001A3dxut5pYElRvw","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","type":"text","text":"Discovery found the actual skill path as `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator`, not `.opencode/skills/sk-design/md-generator`. IвҖҷll treat that as the target md-generator skill surface and use the explicitly named corpus paths where they exist.","time":{"start":1782532192412,"end":1782532211326},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0e76213ab5cc5f56016a3f486068c08191aa89f2cf4a81579f","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532211370,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_7VqR1ftZM8GTp4xAB0UwViA5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/guides/quick_reference.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/guides/quick_reference.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Deep Research Quick Reference\n3: description: One-page cheat sheet for the autonomous deep research loop.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"deep research quick reference\"\n6:   - \"research loop cheat sheet\"\n7:   - \"research iteration checklist\"\n8:   - \"research loop troubleshooting\"\n9:   - \"research tuning guide\"\n10:   - \"research progress visualization\"\n11: importance_tier: normal\n12: contextType: general\n13: version: 1.14.0.26\n14: ---\n15: \n16: # Deep Research Quick Reference\n17: \n18: One-page operator cheat sheet for the autonomous deep research loop.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n23: \n24: Lookup surface during runs covering when to invoke the loop, what each phase produces, how convergence is computed, and where live state lives on disk. Defer to the full protocol and convergence references for deep reasoning.\n25: \n26: Operator contract source of truth for this page:\n27: - command syntax: `.opencode/commands/deep/research.md`\n28: - convergence stop contract: `references/convergence/convergence.md`, `references/convergence/convergence_signals.md`, and the deep-research YAML workflow\n29: - state packet contract: `references/state/state_format.md`, `references/state/state_jsonl.md`, `references/state/state_outputs.md`, and `references/state/state_reducer_registry.md`\n30: \n31: ---\n32: \n33: ## 2. COMMANDS\n34: \n35: | Command | Description |\n36: |---------|-------------|\n37: | `/deep:research:auto \"topic\"` | Run autonomous deep research (no approval gates) |\n38: | `/deep:research:confirm \"topic\"` | Run with approval gates at each iteration |\n39: | `/deep:research \"topic\"` | Ask which mode to use |\n40: \n41: ### Parameters\n42: \n43: | Parameter | Default | Description |\n44: |-----------|---------|-------------|\n45: | `--max-iterations` | 10 | Maximum loop iterations |\n46: | `--convergence` | 0.05 | Stop when avg newInfoRatio below this |\n47: | `--spec-folder` | auto | Target spec folder path |\n48: | `progressiveSynthesis` | true | Allow incremental `research/research.md` updates before final synthesis |\n49: \n50: ---\n51: \n52: ## 3. WHEN TO USE\n53: \n54: | Scenario | Use |\n55: |----------|-----|\n56: | Deep unknown topic, multi-round needed | `/deep:research` |\n57: | Simple question, 1-2 sources | Direct search with `@context` |\n58: | Check prior work only | `memory_context()` |\n59: | Exhaustive critical research | `/deep:research --max-iterations 15 --convergence 0.02` |\n60: \n61: ---\n62: \n63: ## 4. ARCHITECTURE\n64: \n65: ```text\n66: /deep:research  -->  YAML workflow  -->  @deep-research agent (LEAF)\n67:     |                    |                      |\n68:     |                    |                      +-- Read state\n69:     |                    |                      +-- Research (3-5 actions)\n70:     |                    |                      +-- Write findings\n71:     |                    |                      +-- Update state\n72:     |                    |\n73:     |                    +-- Init (config, strategy, state)\n74:     |                    +-- Loop (dispatch, evaluate, decide)\n75:     |                    +-- Synthesize (final research/research.md)\n76:     |                    +-- Save (memory context)\n77: ```\n78: \n79: ---\n80: \n81: ## 5. STATE FILES\n82: \n83: | File | Location | Format | Purpose |\n84: |------|----------|--------|---------|\n85: | Config | `research/deep-research-config.json` | JSON | Loop parameters |\n86: | State | `research/deep-research-state.jsonl` | JSONL | Iteration log (append-only) |\n87: | Strategy | `research/deep-research-strategy.md` | Markdown | What worked/failed, next focus |\n88: | Registry | `research/findings-registry.json` | JSON | Reducer-owned open/resolved questions and key findings |\n89: | Dashboard | `research/deep-research-dashboard.md` | Markdown | Reducer-owned lifecycle and convergence summary |\n90: | Iterations | `research/iterations/iteration-NNN.md` | Markdown | Per-iteration findings |\n91: | Output | `research/research.md` | Markdown | Workflow-owned progressive synthesis output |\n92: \n93: > **Live lifecycle branches:** `resume`, `restart`. (`fork` and `completed-continue` are deferred and not runtime-wired.) `progressiveSynthesis` defaults to `true`, so `research/research.md` is updated during the loop and finalized at synthesis.\n94: \n95: > **Path contract:** root-spec runs write directly to `{spec_folder}/research/`; child-phase and sub-phase first runs use the local `{spec_folder}/research/` directory directly, with `{ownerSlug}-pt-NN` allocated only when prior non-matching content already exists.\n96: \n97: > **Canonical pause sentinel:** `research/.deep-research-pause`\n98: \n99: > **Runtime capability matrix:** `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/guides/capability_matrix.md` and `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/assets/runtime_capabilities.json`\n100: \n101: ---\n102: \n103: ## 6. ITERATION STATUS LEGEND\n104: \n105: | Status | Meaning |\n106: |--------|---------|\n107: | `complete` | Normal iteration with findings |\n108: | `timeout` | Exceeded time/tool budget |\n109: | `error` | Failed to produce outputs |\n110: | `stuck` | No new information found |\n111: | `insight` | Low ratio but conceptual breakthrough |\n112: | `thought` | Analytical-only, no evidence |\n113: \n114: ---\n115: \n116: ## 7. CONVERGENCE DECISION TREE\n117: \n118: ```text\n119: Max iterations reached?\n120:   Yes --> STOP\n121: \n122: All questions answered?\n123:   Yes --> STOP\n124: \n125: stuckThreshold consecutive no-progress?\n126:   Yes --> STUCK_RECOVERY\n127:     Recovery works? --> CONTINUE\n128:     Recovery fails? --> STOP (with gaps)\n129: \n130: Composite convergence (3-signal weighted > 0.60)?\n131:   Yes --> STOP (converged)\n132: \n133: Otherwise --> CONTINUE\n134: ```\n135: \n136: ### 3-Signal Convergence Model\n137: \n138: | Signal | Weight | Min Iterations | Votes STOP When |\n139: |--------|--------|---------------|-----------------|\n140: | Rolling Average | 0.30 | 3 | avg(last 3 newInfoRatios) < convergenceThreshold |\n141: | MAD Noise Floor | 0.35 | 4 | latest ratio <= MAD * 1.4826 |\n142: | Question Entropy | 0.35 | 1 | answered / total questions >= 0.85 |\n143: \n144: **Composite stop threshold:** 0.60 -- weighted stop score must exceed this before quality guards are evaluated.\n145: \n146: Quality guards (source diversity, focus alignment, no single-weak-source) must pass before STOP.\n147: \n148: ---\n149: \n150: ## 8. AGENT ITERATION CHECKLIST\n151: \n152: Each @deep-research iteration:\n153: 1. Read `deep-research-state.jsonl` and `deep-research-strategy.md`\n154: 2. Determine focus from reducer-owned strategy \"Next Focus\"\n155: 3. Execute 3-5 research actions (WebFetch, Grep, Read, memory_search)\n156: 4. Write `research/iterations/iteration-NNN.md` with findings\n157: 5. Append iteration record to `deep-research-state.jsonl`\n158: 6. Let the workflow reducer update `deep-research-strategy.md`, `findings-registry.json`, and `deep-research-dashboard.md`\n159: 7. Optionally update machine-owned sections in `research/research.md` when progressive synthesis is enabled\n160: \n161: ---\n162: \n163: ## 9. TUNING GUIDE\n164: \n165: | Goal | Adjustment |\n166: |------|------------|\n167: | Deeper research | Lower convergence (0.02), raise max iterations (15) |\n168: | Faster completion | Raise convergence (0.10), lower max iterations (5) |\n169: | Broader coverage | Start with broad topic, let iterations narrow |\n170: | Specific answer | Start with specific question, lower max iterations (5) |\n171: \n172: ---\n173: \n174: ## 10. TROUBLESHOOTING\n175: \n176: | Problem | Fix |\n177: |---------|-----|\n178: | Stops too early | Lower `--convergence` from 0.05 to 0.02 |\n179: | Repeats same research | Check strategy.md \"Exhausted Approaches\" is being read |\n180: | Agent ignores state | Verify file paths in dispatch prompt |\n181: | State file corrupt | Validate JSONL: `cat research/deep-research-state.jsonl \\| jq .` |\n182: | Loop runs too long | Set lower `--max-iterations` or higher `--convergence` |\n183: \n184: ---\n185: \n186: ## 11. PROGRESS VISUALIZATION\n187: \n188: After each iteration, the orchestrator can display a text-based convergence summary:\n189: \n190: ### Format\n191: \n192: | Element | Format | Example |\n193: |---------|--------|---------|\n194: | newInfoRatio trend | ASCII sparkline | `[0.9 0.7 0.5 0.3 0.1]` |\n195: | Question coverage | Progress bar | `[=======>...] 7/10 (70%)` |\n196: | Composite score | Threshold bar | `[####----] 0.42 / 0.60` |\n197: | Noise floor | Comparison | `ratio: 0.12 > floor: 0.08` |\n198: \n199: ### Example Output\n200: \n201: ```text\n202: ITERATION 5 PROGRESS\n203: в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ\n204: newInfoRatio: 0.9 -> 0.7 -> 0.5 -> 0.3 -> 0.1  trending down\n205: Questions:   [========>..] 8/10 answered (80%)\n206: Composite:   [######--] 0.48 / 0.60 threshold\n207: Noise floor: 0.08 (ratio 0.10 ABOVE floor)\n208: Stuck count: 0 | Segment: 1 | Recovery: none\n209: Signals: RollingAvg=STOP MAD=CONTINUE Entropy=CONTINUE\n210: ```\n211: \n212: ### When to Display\n213: \n214: - After each iteration evaluation (Step 4)\n215: - In the convergence report (synthesis phase)\n216: - In confirm mode approval gates\n217: \n218: ---\n219: \n220: ## 12. RELATED\n\n(Showing lines 1-220 of 235. Use offset=221 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Deep Research Quick Reference\ndescription: One-page cheat sheet for the autonomous deep research loop.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"deep research quick reference\"\n  - \"research loop cheat sheet\"\n  - \"research iteration checklist\"\n  - \"research loop troubleshooting\"\n  - \"research tuning guide\"\n  - \"research progress visualization\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.14.0.26\n---\n\n# Deep Research Quick Reference\n\nOne-page operator cheat sheet for the autonomous deep research loop.\n\n---","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/guides/quick_reference.md","text":"---\ntitle: Deep Research Quick Reference\ndescription: One-page cheat sheet for the autonomous deep research loop.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"deep research quick reference\"\n  - \"research loop cheat sheet\"\n  - \"research iteration checklist\"\n  - \"research loop troubleshooting\"\n  - \"research tuning guide\"\n  - \"research progress visualization\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.14.0.26\n---\n\n# Deep Research Quick Reference\n\nOne-page operator cheat sheet for the autonomous deep research loop.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nLookup surface during runs covering when to invoke the loop, what each phase produces, how convergence is computed, and where live state lives on disk. Defer to the full protocol and convergence references for deep reasoning.\n\nOperator contract source of truth for this page:\n- command syntax: `.opencode/commands/deep/research.md`\n- convergence stop contract: `references/convergence/convergence.md`, `references/convergence/convergence_signals.md`, and the deep-research YAML workflow\n- state packet contract: `references/state/state_format.md`, `references/state/state_jsonl.md`, `references/state/state_outputs.md`, and `references/state/state_reducer_registry.md`\n\n---\n\n## 2. COMMANDS\n\n| Command | Description |\n|---------|-------------|\n| `/deep:research:auto \"topic\"` | Run autonomous deep research (no approval gates) |\n| `/deep:research:confirm \"topic\"` | Run with approval gates at each iteration |\n| `/deep:research \"topic\"` | Ask which mode to use |\n\n### Parameters\n\n| Parameter | Default | Description |\n|-----------|---------|-------------|\n| `--max-iterations` | 10 | Maximum loop iterations |\n| `--convergence` | 0.05 | Stop when avg newInfoRatio below this |\n| `--spec-folder` | auto | Target spec folder path |\n| `progressiveSynthesis` | true | Allow incremental `research/research.md` updates before final synthesis |\n\n---\n\n## 3. WHEN TO USE\n\n| Scenario | Use |\n|----------|-----|\n| Deep unknown topic, multi-round needed | `/deep:research` |\n| Simple question, 1-2 sources | Direct search with `@context` |\n| Check prior work only | `memory_context()` |\n| Exhaustive critical research | `/deep:research --max-iterations 15 --convergence 0.02` |\n\n---\n\n## 4. ARCHITECTURE\n\n```text\n/deep:research  -->  YAML workflow  -->  @deep-research agent (LEAF)\n    |                    |                      |\n    |                    |                      +-- Read state\n    |                    |                      +-- Research (3-5 actions)\n    |                    |                      +-- Write findings\n    |                    |                      +-- Update state\n    |                    |\n    |                    +-- Init (config, strategy, state)\n    |                    +-- Loop (dispatch, evaluate, decide)\n    |                    +-- Synthesize (final research/research.md)\n    |                    +-- Save (memory context)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. STATE FILES\n\n| File | Location | Format | Purpose |\n|------|----------|--------|---------|\n| Config | `research/deep-research-config.json` | JSON | Loop parameters |\n| State | `research/deep-research-state.jsonl` | JSONL | Iteration log (append-only) |\n| Strategy | `research/deep-research-strategy.md` | Markdown | What worked/failed, next focus |\n| Registry | `research/findings-registry.json` | JSON | Reducer-owned open/resolved questions and key findings |\n| Dashboard | `research/deep-research-dashboard.md` | Markdown | Reducer-owned lifecycle and convergence summary |\n| Iterations | `research/iterations/iteration-NNN.md` | Markdown | Per-iteration findings |\n| Output | `research/research.md` | Markdown | Workflow-owned progressive synthesis output |\n\n> **Live lifecycle branches:** `resume`, `restart`. (`fork` and `completed-continue` are deferred and not runtime-wired.) `progressiveSynthesis` defaults to `true`, so `research/research.md` is updated during the loop and finalized at synthesis.\n\n> **Path contract:** root-spec runs write directly to `{spec_folder}/research/`; child-phase and sub-phase first runs use the local `{spec_folder}/research/` directory directly, with `{ownerSlug}-pt-NN` allocated only when prior non-matching content already exists.\n\n> **Canonical pause sentinel:** `research/.deep-research-pause`\n\n> **Runtime capability matrix:** `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/guides/capability_matrix.md` and `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/assets/runtime_capabilities.json`\n\n---\n\n## 6. ITERATION STATUS LEGEND\n\n| Status | Meaning |\n|--------|---------|\n| `complete` | Normal iteration with findings |\n| `timeout` | Exceeded time/tool budget |\n| `error` | Failed to produce outputs |\n| `stuck` | No new information found |\n| `insight` | Low ratio but conceptual breakthrough |\n| `thought` | Analytical-only, no evidence |\n\n---\n\n## 7. CONVERGENCE DECISION TREE\n\n```text\nMax iterations reached?\n  Yes --> STOP\n\nAll questions answered?\n  Yes --> STOP\n\nstuckThreshold consecutive no-progress?\n  Yes --> STUCK_RECOVERY\n    Recovery works? --> CONTINUE\n    Recovery fails? --> STOP (with gaps)\n\nComposite convergence (3-signal weighted > 0.60)?\n  Yes --> STOP (converged)\n\nOtherwise --> CONTINUE\n```\n\n### 3-Signal Convergence Model\n\n| Signal | Weight | Min Iterations | Votes STOP When |\n|--------|--------|---------------|-----------------|\n| Rolling Average | 0.30 | 3 | avg(last 3 newInfoRatios) < convergenceThreshold |\n| MAD Noise Floor | 0.35 | 4 | latest ratio <= MAD * 1.4826 |\n| Question Entropy | 0.35 | 1 | answered / total questions >= 0.85 |\n\n**Composite stop threshold:** 0.60 -- weighted stop score must exceed this before quality guards are evaluated.\n\nQuality guards (source diversity, focus alignment, no single-weak-source) must pass before STOP.\n\n---\n\n## 8. AGENT ITERATION CHECKLIST\n\nEach @deep-research iteration:\n1. Read `deep-research-state.jsonl` and `deep-research-strategy.md`\n2. Determine focus from reducer-owned strategy \"Next Focus\"\n3. Execute 3-5 research actions (WebFetch, Grep, Read, memory_search)\n4. Write `research/iterations/iteration-NNN.md` with findings\n5. Append iteration record to `deep-research-state.jsonl`\n6. Let the workflow reducer update `deep-research-strategy.md`, `findings-registry.json`, and `deep-research-dashboard.md`\n7. Optionally update machine-owned sections in `research/research.md` when progressive synthesis is enabled\n\n---\n\n## 9. TUNING GUIDE\n\n| Goal | Adjustment |\n|------|------------|\n| Deeper research | Lower convergence (0.02), raise max iterations (15) |\n| Faster completion | Raise convergence (0.10), lower max iterations (5) |\n| Broader coverage | Start with broad topic, let iterations narrow |\n| Specific answer | Start with specific question, lower max iterations (5) |\n\n---\n\n## 10. TROUBLESHOOTING\n\n| Problem | Fix |\n|---------|-----|\n| Stops too early | Lower `--convergence` from 0.05 to 0.02 |\n| Repeats same research | Check strategy.md \"Exhausted Approaches\" is being read |\n| Agent ignores state | Verify file paths in dispatch prompt |\n| State file corrupt | Validate JSONL: `cat research/deep-research-state.jsonl \\| jq .` |\n| Loop runs too long | Set lower `--max-iterations` or higher `--convergence` |\n\n---\n\n## 11. PROGRESS VISUALIZATION\n\nAfter each iteration, the orchestrator can display a text-based convergence summary:\n\n### Format\n\n| Element | Format | Example |\n|---------|--------|---------|\n| newInfoRatio trend | ASCII sparkline | `[0.9 0.7 0.5 0.3 0.1]` |\n| Question coverage | Progress bar | `[=======>...] 7/10 (70%)` |\n| Composite score | Threshold bar | `[####----] 0.42 / 0.60` |\n| Noise floor | Comparison | `ratio: 0.12 > floor: 0.08` |\n\n### Example Output\n\n```text\nITERATION 5 PROGRESS\nв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ\nnewInfoRatio: 0.9 -> 0.7 -> 0.5 -> 0.3 -> 0.1  trending down\nQuestions:   [========>..] 8/10 answered (80%)\nComposite:   [######--] 0.48 / 0.60 threshold\nNoise floor: 0.08 (ratio 0.10 ABOVE floor)\nStuck count: 0 | Segment: 1 | Recovery: none\nSignals: RollingAvg=STOP MAD=CONTINUE Entropy=CONTINUE\n```\n\n### When to Display\n\n- After each iteration evaluation (Step 4)\n- In the convergence report (synthesis phase)\n- In confirm mode approval gates\n\n---\n\n## 12. RELATED","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":220,"totalLines":235,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/guides/quick_reference.md","time":{"start":1782532211354,"end":1782532211369}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e76213ab5cc5f56016a3f48734bb4819196b68566120fd975"}},"id":"prt_f07330281001vxm5TNVw25uVfC","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","messageID":"msg_f073297d6001A3dxut5pYElRvw"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532211373,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_AyhETlVWJ04HkqMDpTzo41PD","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Loop Protocol Reference\n3: description: Canonical specification for the deep research loop lifecycle with 4 phases, reference-only wave orchestration, and error handling.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"research loop protocol\"\n6:   - \"research loop lifecycle\"\n7:   - \"research loop initialization\"\n8:   - \"research auto resume protocol\"\n9:   - \"research pause sentinel\"\n10:   - \"research synthesis phase\"\n11: importance_tier: important\n12: contextType: implementation\n13: version: 1.14.0.29\n14: ---\n15: \n16: # Loop Protocol Reference\n17: \n18: Canonical specification for the deep research loop lifecycle. Use it as the lifecycle map for initialization, iteration, synthesis, save, and recovery.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n23: \n24: ### Purpose\n25: \n26: Define the lifecycle contract for deep-research initialization, iteration, synthesis, save, reference-only dispatch concepts, and error handling.\n27: \n28: ### When to Use\n29: \n30: Load this reference when running or validating the research loop lifecycle. Use `../convergence/convergence.md` for STOP decisions and `../state/state_format.md` for packet file schemas.\n31: \n32: ### Core Principle\n33: \n34: The YAML workflow owns lifecycle orchestration, `@deep-research` executes LEAF iterations, and the reducer synchronizes packet state after each iteration and lifecycle transition.\n35: \n36: ### Phase Model\n37: \n38: The deep research loop has 4 phases: initialization, iteration (repeated), synthesis, and save.\n39: \n40: Runtime capability matrix references for parity-sensitive loop behavior:\n41: - Human-readable matrix: `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/guides/capability_matrix.md`\n42: - Machine-readable matrix: `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/assets/runtime_capabilities.json`\n43: \n44: ```text\n45: в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ     в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ     в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ     в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ\n46: в”Ӯ  INIT    в”Ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ>в”Ӯ  LOOP                    в”Ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ>в”Ӯ  SYNTHESIS            в”Ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ>в”Ӯ  SAVE    в”Ӯ\n47: в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ                       в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ\n48: в”Ӯ Config    в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ Read State         в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ Final                 в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ Memory   в”Ӯ\n49: в”Ӯ Strategy в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ Check Convergence  в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ research/research.md  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ Context  в”Ӯ\n50: в”Ӯ State    в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ Dispatch Agent     в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ compilation           в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ Save     в”Ӯ\n51: в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ Evaluate Results   в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ                       в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ\n52: в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ Loop Decision      в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ                       в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ\n53: в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ                       в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ\n54: в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ           в”Ӯ repeat       в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ                       в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ\n55: в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ     в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ     в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ     в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ\n56: ```\n57: \n58: ---\n59: \n60: ## 2. PHASE: INITIALIZATION\n61: \n62: ### Purpose\n63: Set up all state files for a new research session.\n64: \n65: ### Steps\n66: \n67: 1. **Classify session state before writing**:\n68:    - `fresh`: no config/state/strategy files exist\n69:    - `resume`: config + state + strategy all exist and agree\n70:    - `completed-session`: consistent prior state with `config.status == \"complete\"`\n71:    - `invalid-state`: partial or contradictory artifacts\n72: 2. **Resolve canonical artifact names**:\n73:    - Read legacy aliases during the migration window if needed\n74:    - Write only canonical `deep-research-*` names\n75:    - Emit a `migration` event for every legacy alias consumed\n76: 3. **Resolve local artifact owner**: `artifact_dir = resolveArtifactRoot(specFolder, 'research').artifactDir`, then `mkdir -p {artifact_dir}/iterations`\n77: 4. **Write config**: `research/deep-research-config.json` from template + user parameters\n78: 5. **Initialize state log**: First line of `research/deep-research-state.jsonl` with config record\n79: 6. **Initialize strategy**: `research/deep-research-strategy.md` from template with:\n80:    - Topic from user input\n81:    - Initial key questions (3-5, from topic analysis)\n82:    - Known context from `memory_context()` results (if any), injected only after the strategy file exists\n83:    - Research boundaries from config\n84: 6a. **Detect resource-map integration state**:\n85:    - Check `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md` once during init\n86:    - If present: set `resource_map_present = true` in `deep-research-config.json`\n87:    - Summarize the map into `deep-research-strategy.md` `Known Context`\n88:    - The summary MUST include per-section entry counts for `READMEs`, `Documents`, `Commands`, `Agents`, `Skills`, `Specs`, `Scripts`, `Tests`, `Config`, and `Meta`\n89:    - The summary MUST also include a one-line theme summary for each resource-map section\n90:    - If absent: set `resource_map_present = false` and append `resource-map.md not present; skipping coverage gate` to `Known Context`\n91: 7. **Initialize findings registry**: `research/findings-registry.json` with empty `openQuestions`, `resolvedQuestions`, `keyFindings`, and `ruledOutDirections`\n92: 7a. **Validate Research Charter**:\n93:    - Verify strategy.md contains a \"Non-Goals\" section (may be empty but must exist)\n94:    - Verify strategy.md contains a \"Stop Conditions\" section (may be empty but must exist)\n95:    - If either section is missing, append it as an empty placeholder before proceeding\n96:    - In **confirm mode**: present the charter (topic, key questions, non-goals, stop conditions) for user review before proceeding\n97:    - In **auto mode**: accept the charter automatically and continue\n98: 8. **Resume only if config, JSONL, and strategy agree**; otherwise halt for repair instead of guessing\n99: \n100: ### Outputs\n101: - `research/deep-research-config.json`\n102: - `research/deep-research-state.jsonl` (1 line)\n103: - `research/deep-research-strategy.md`\n104: \n105: ### Auto-Resume Protocol\n106: If state files already exist from a prior session:\n107: 1. Verify config, JSONL, and strategy all exist and agree on topic/spec folder\n108: 2. Read JSONL, count iteration records\n109: 3. Read strategy.md for current state\n110: 4. Set iteration counter to last completed + 1\n111: 5. Append the canonical resume event to `deep-research-state.jsonl` (all fields below are required by the reducer):\n112: \n113: ```json\n114: {\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"resumed\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"rsr-2026-03-18T10-00-00Z\",\"parentSessionId\":\"rsr-2026-03-18T10-00-00Z\",\"lineageMode\":\"resume\",\"continuedFromRun\":4,\"generation\":1,\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-18T14:05:00Z\"}\n115: ```\n116: \n117: 6. Continue loop from `step_read_state`.\n118: \n119: ### Lifecycle Branch Contract (current release)\n120: \n121: The runtime supports three lineage modes today. `fork` and `completed-continue` were described in earlier drafts but have no workflow wiring in this release, so they MUST NOT be exposed to operators. If the long-form lineage feature is picked up later it will arrive with first-class event emission, reducer ancestry handling, and replay fixtures; until then treat the contract below as canonical.\n122: \n123: | Mode | Session id | Generation | Archive | JSONL event | When to pick |\n124: |------|-----------|-----------|---------|-------------|--------------|\n125: | `new` | fresh | 1 | n/a | implicit (config record) | no existing state |\n126: | `resume` | same | same | none | `resumed` (see example above) | operator wants to continue the current lineage boundary |\n127: | `restart` | fresh | `prior + 1` | prior `research/` tree moved under `research_archive/{timestamp}/` | `restarted` (same field set plus `archivedPath`) | operator wants to clear the workspace and replay with a new angle |\n128: \n129: **Contract for every persisted lifecycle event**:\n130: \n131: ```json\n132: {\n133:   \"type\": \"event\",\n134:   \"event\": \"resumed | restarted\",\n135:   \"mode\": \"research\",\n136:   \"sessionId\": \"<session id of the new or continuing lineage>\",\n137:   \"parentSessionId\": \"<session id of the prior lineage (equals sessionId on resume)>\",\n138:   \"lineageMode\": \"resume | restart\",\n139:   \"generation\": <number>,\n140:   \"continuedFromRun\": <number or null>,\n141:   \"archivedPath\": \"<path or null>\",\n142:   \"timestamp\": \"<ISO 8601>\"\n143: }\n144: ```\n145: \n146: Every field in the contract MUST be present on every persisted lifecycle event. `archivedPath` is null for `resumed` and set to the archive destination for `restarted`. `continuedFromRun` is the number of completed iteration records before the lifecycle boundary. Reducer parity tests ensure the dashboard `Lifecycle` section reads exactly those fields.\n147: \n148: ---\n149: \n150: ## 3. PHASE: ITERATION LOOP\n151: \n152: ### Loop Steps (repeated until convergence)\n153: \n154: #### Step 1: Read State\n155: - Read `deep-research-state.jsonl` -- count iterations, get last newInfoRatio\n156: - Read `deep-research-strategy.md` -- get next focus, remaining questions\n157: \n158: #### Step 2: Check Convergence\n159: Run the convergence algorithm (see convergence.md):\n160: - Max iterations reached? STOP\n161: - Stuck count >= threshold? STUCK_RECOVERY\n162: - Average newInfoRatio < threshold? STOP\n163: - All questions answered? STOP\n164: - Otherwise: CONTINUE\n165: \n166: #### Step 2c: Quality Guard Check\n167: \n168: When the convergence algorithm returns STOP:\n169: 1. Run quality guard checks (see convergence.md В§2.4)\n170: 2. Verify minimum coverage, source diversity, and question resolution thresholds\n171: 3. If **all guards pass**: proceed with STOP, exit to synthesis\n172: 4. If **any guard fails**: override decision to CONTINUE\n173:    - Log each violation: `{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"guard_violation\",\"guard\":\"<name>\",\"iteration\":N,\"detail\":\"<reason>\"}`\n174:    - Persist the blocked legal-stop outcome: `{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"blocked_stop\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"run\":N,\"blockedBy\":[\"<gate>\"],\"gateResults\":{\"convergence\":{\"pass\":true,\"score\":0.0},\"keyQuestionCoverage\":{\"pass\":false,\"answered\":X,\"total\":Y},\"evidenceDensity\":{\"pass\":false,\"sources\":N},\"hotspotSaturation\":{\"pass\":true}},\"recoveryStrategy\":\"<one-line hint>\",\"timestamp\":\"<ISO8601>\",\"sessionId\":\"<sid>\",\"generation\":G}`\n175:    - Append failed guard details to strategy.md \"Active Risks\" section\n176: 5. The loop continues until BOTH convergence AND quality guards pass simultaneously\n177: 6. Guard checks apply only to STOP decisions - CONTINUE and STUCK_RECOVERY bypass this step\n178: \n179: If the legal-stop decision tree returns `blocked`, the workflow MUST append the `blocked_stop` JSONL event before continuing. Reducers and dashboards consume the persisted event; they must not infer blocked-stop state solely from prose logs.\n180: \n181: #### Step 2a: Check Pause Sentinel\n182: \n183: Before dispatching, check for a pause sentinel file:\n184: \n185: 1. Check if `research/.deep-research-pause` exists\n186: 2. If present:\n187:    - Log event to JSONL: `{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"userPaused\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"run\":N,\"stopReason\":\"userPaused\",\"sentinelPath\":\"{artifact_dir}/.deep-research-pause\",\"timestamp\":\"<ISO8601>\",\"sessionId\":\"<sid>\",\"generation\":G}`\n188:    - Halt the loop with message:\n189:      ```text\n190:      Research paused. Delete research/.deep-research-pause to resume.\n191:      Current state: Iteration {N}, {remaining} questions remaining.\n192:      ```\n193:    - Do NOT exit to synthesis -- the loop is suspended, not stopped\n194: 3. On resume (file deleted and loop restarted):\n195:    - Log event: `{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"resumed\",\"fromIteration\":N}`\n196:    - Continue from step_read_state\n197: \n198: Pause and recovery events use the frozen stop-reason enum on the live path. Raw `paused` and `stuck_recovery` labels are legacy aliases and MUST be normalized to `userPaused` and `stuckRecovery` at emission time.\n199: \n200: **Use case**: In autonomous mode, this provides the only graceful intervention mechanism short of killing the process. Users can create the sentinel file at any time to pause research between iterations.\n201: \n202: #### Step 2b: Generate State Summary\n203: \n204: Generate a compact state summary (~200 tokens) for injection into the dispatch prompt:\n205: \n206: ```text\n207: STATE SUMMARY (auto-generated):\n208: Segment: {current_segment} | Iteration: {N} of {max}\n209: Questions: {answered}/{total} answered | Last focus: {last_focus}\n210: Last 2 ratios: {ratio_N-1} -> {ratio_N} | Stuck count: {stuck_count}\n211: Recovery: {active_recovery_strategy or \"none\"}\n212: Next focus: {strategy.nextFocus}\n213: ```\n214: \n215: This summary is prepended to the dispatch context (Step 3) to ensure the agent has baseline context even if detailed strategy.md reading fails or is incomplete. It serves as a redundant context channel.\n216: \n217: #### Step 3: Dispatch Agent\n218: Dispatch `@deep-research` with explicit context:\n219: ```text\n220: {state_summary}  // Auto-generated (Step 2b)\n221: \n222: Research Topic: {config.topic}\n223: Iteration: {N} of {maxIterations}\n224: Focus Area: {strategy.nextFocus}\n225: Remaining Questions: {strategy.remainingQuestions}\n226: Last 3 Iterations Summary: {brief summaries}\n227: Resource Map: if `config.resource_map_present == true`, prior-inventoried files are listed in `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md`; treat them as the exclusion set when hunting for net-new files; flag only missed-from-map candidates as gaps.\n228: State Files:\n229:   - Config: {artifact_dir}/deep-research-config.json\n230:   - State: {artifact_dir}/deep-research-state.jsonl\n231:   - Strategy: {artifact_dir}/deep-research-strategy.md\n232: Output: Write findings to {artifact_dir}/iterations/iteration-{NNN}.md\n233: CONSTRAINT: LEAF agent -- do NOT dispatch sub-agents\n234: ```\n235: \n236: #### Executor Resolution (spec 018 + 019)\n237: \n238: Before dispatching, the YAML resolves the executor via `parseExecutorConfig` from `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/deep-loop/executor-config.ts`. The resolved `config.executor.kind` selects the dispatch branch:\n239: \n240: - `native` (spec 018): dispatch `@deep-research` agent with model Opus.\n241: - `cli-codex` (spec 018): pipe rendered prompt via stdin to `codex exec --model X -c model_reasoning_effort=Y -c service_tier=Z -c approval_policy=never --sandbox workspace-write`.\n242: - `cli-claude-code` (spec 019): `claude -p \"$(cat prompt)\" --model X --permission-mode acceptEdits --output-format text` with optional `--effort Y`. Default permission-mode is `plan` (read-only); we override to `acceptEdits` so iteration writes succeed.\n243: \n244: All branches share:\n245: 1. Pre-dispatch prompt rendering via `renderPromptPack` (writes to `{artifact_dir}/prompts/iteration-{n}.md`).\n246: 2. Post-dispatch validation via `validateIterationOutputs` (asserts iteration file + JSONL delta + required fields).\n247: 3. Executor audit append via `appendExecutorAuditToLastRecord` (skipped when kind=='native').\n248: \n249: Per-kind flag-compatibility is enforced at config parse time by `EXECUTOR_KIND_FLAG_SUPPORT` in `executor-config.ts`. Setting a flag that the chosen kind does not support throws `ExecutorConfigError` before dispatch.\n250: \n251: Cross-CLI delegation (a running executor invoking other CLIs via its shell) is documented design intent. Runtime recursion detection is out of scope; see the SKILL.md Cross-CLI Delegation subsection.\n252: \n253: Failure handling remains unchanged from spec 018: `schema_mismatch` вҶ’ conflict event вҶ’ 3 consecutive failures вҶ’ `stuck_recovery`.\n254: \n255: The dispatch context may include a suggested `focusTrack` label (e.g., `\"focusTrack\": \"performance\"`, `\"focusTrack\": \"security\"`). Agents may tag their iteration with this track label for post-hoc grouping and analysis. Track labels are metadata only - the orchestrator does not use them for loop decisions.\n256: \n257: #### Step 3a: Per-Iteration Budget\n258: \n259: After dispatch, the orchestrator monitors the running iteration against budget limits:\n260: - **Tool call count**: tracked against `config.maxToolCallsPerIteration` (default: 12)\n\n(Showing lines 1-260 of 617. Use offset=261 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Loop Protocol Reference\ndescription: Canonical specification for the deep research loop lifecycle with 4 phases, reference-only wave orchestration, and error handling.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"research loop protocol\"\n  - \"research loop lifecycle\"\n  - \"research loop initialization\"\n  - \"research auto resume protocol\"\n  - \"research pause sentinel\"\n  - \"research synthesis phase\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.14.0.29\n---\n\n# Loop Protocol Reference\n\nCanonical specification for the deep research loop lifecycle. Use it as the lifecycle map for initialization, iteration, synthesis, save, and recovery.\n\n---","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md","text":"---\ntitle: Loop Protocol Reference\ndescription: Canonical specification for the deep research loop lifecycle with 4 phases, reference-only wave orchestration, and error handling.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"research loop protocol\"\n  - \"research loop lifecycle\"\n  - \"research loop initialization\"\n  - \"research auto resume protocol\"\n  - \"research pause sentinel\"\n  - \"research synthesis phase\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.14.0.29\n---\n\n# Loop Protocol Reference\n\nCanonical specification for the deep research loop lifecycle. Use it as the lifecycle map for initialization, iteration, synthesis, save, and recovery.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDefine the lifecycle contract for deep-research initialization, iteration, synthesis, save, reference-only dispatch concepts, and error handling.\n\n### When to Use\n\nLoad this reference when running or validating the research loop lifecycle. Use `../convergence/convergence.md` for STOP decisions and `../state/state_format.md` for packet file schemas.\n\n### Core Principle\n\nThe YAML workflow owns lifecycle orchestration, `@deep-research` executes LEAF iterations, and the reducer synchronizes packet state after each iteration and lifecycle transition.\n\n### Phase Model\n\nThe deep research loop has 4 phases: initialization, iteration (repeated), synthesis, and save.\n\nRuntime capability matrix references for parity-sensitive loop behavior:\n- Human-readable matrix: `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/guides/capability_matrix.md`\n- Machine-readable matrix: `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/assets/runtime_capabilities.json`\n\n```text\nв”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ     в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ     в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ     в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ\nв”Ӯ  INIT    в”Ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ>в”Ӯ  LOOP                    в”Ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ>в”Ӯ  SYNTHESIS            в”Ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ>в”Ӯ  SAVE    в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ          в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ                       в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ Config    в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ Read State         в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ Final                 в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ Memory   в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ Strategy в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ Check Convergence  в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ research/research.md  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ Context  в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ State    в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ Dispatch Agent     в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ compilation           в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ Save     в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ          в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ Evaluate Results   в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ                       в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ          в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ Loop Decision      в”Ӯ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ                       в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ          в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ  в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ  в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ                       в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ          в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ           в”Ӯ repeat       в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ                       в”Ӯ     в”Ӯ          в”Ӯ\nв””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ     в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ     в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ     в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2. PHASE: INITIALIZATION\n\n### Purpose\nSet up all state files for a new research session.\n\n### Steps\n\n1. **Classify session state before writing**:\n   - `fresh`: no config/state/strategy files exist\n   - `resume`: config + state + strategy all exist and agree\n   - `completed-session`: consistent prior state with `config.status == \"complete\"`\n   - `invalid-state`: partial or contradictory artifacts\n2. **Resolve canonical artifact names**:\n   - Read legacy aliases during the migration window if needed\n   - Write only canonical `deep-research-*` names\n   - Emit a `migration` event for every legacy alias consumed\n3. **Resolve local artifact owner**: `artifact_dir = resolveArtifactRoot(specFolder, 'research').artifactDir`, then `mkdir -p {artifact_dir}/iterations`\n4. **Write config**: `research/deep-research-config.json` from template + user parameters\n5. **Initialize state log**: First line of `research/deep-research-state.jsonl` with config record\n6. **Initialize strategy**: `research/deep-research-strategy.md` from template with:\n   - Topic from user input\n   - Initial key questions (3-5, from topic analysis)\n   - Known context from `memory_context()` results (if any), injected only after the strategy file exists\n   - Research boundaries from config\n6a. **Detect resource-map integration state**:\n   - Check `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md` once during init\n   - If present: set `resource_map_present = true` in `deep-research-config.json`\n   - Summarize the map into `deep-research-strategy.md` `Known Context`\n   - The summary MUST include per-section entry counts for `READMEs`, `Documents`, `Commands`, `Agents`, `Skills`, `Specs`, `Scripts`, `Tests`, `Config`, and `Meta`\n   - The summary MUST also include a one-line theme summary for each resource-map section\n   - If absent: set `resource_map_present = false` and append `resource-map.md not present; skipping coverage gate` to `Known Context`\n7. **Initialize findings registry**: `research/findings-registry.json` with empty `openQuestions`, `resolvedQuestions`, `keyFindings`, and `ruledOutDirections`\n7a. **Validate Research Charter**:\n   - Verify strategy.md contains a \"Non-Goals\" section (may be empty but must exist)\n   - Verify strategy.md contains a \"Stop Conditions\" section (may be empty but must exist)\n   - If either section is missing, append it as an empty placeholder before proceeding\n   - In **confirm mode**: present the charter (topic, key questions, non-goals, stop conditions) for user review before proceeding\n   - In **auto mode**: accept the charter automatically and continue\n8. **Resume only if config, JSONL, and strategy agree**; otherwise halt for repair instead of guessing\n\n### Outputs\n- `research/deep-research-config.json`\n- `research/deep-research-state.jsonl` (1 line)\n- `research/deep-research-strategy.md`\n\n### Auto-Resume Protocol\nIf state files already exist from a prior session:\n1. Verify config, JSONL, and strategy all exist and agree on topic/spec folder\n2. Read JSONL, count iteration records\n3. Read strategy.md for current state\n4. Set iteration counter to last completed + 1\n5. Append the canonical resume event to `deep-research-state.jsonl` (all fields below are required by the reducer):\n\n```json\n{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"resumed\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"rsr-2026-03-18T10-00-00Z\",\"parentSessionId\":\"rsr-2026-03-18T10-00-00Z\",\"lineageMode\":\"resume\",\"continuedFromRun\":4,\"generation\":1,\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-18T14:05:00Z\"}\n```\n\n6. Continue loop from `step_read_state`.\n\n### Lifecycle Branch Contract (current release)\n\nThe runtime supports three lineage modes today. `fork` and `completed-continue` were described in earlier drafts but have no workflow wiring in this release, so they MUST NOT be exposed to operators. If the long-form lineage feature is picked up later it will arrive with first-class event emission, reducer ancestry handling, and replay fixtures; until then treat the contract below as canonical.\n\n| Mode | Session id | Generation | Archive | JSONL event | When to pick |\n|------|-----------|-----------|---------|-------------|--------------|\n| `new` | fresh | 1 | n/a | implicit (config record) | no existing state |\n| `resume` | same | same | none | `resumed` (see example above) | operator wants to continue the current lineage boundary |\n| `restart` | fresh | `prior + 1` | prior `research/` tree moved under `research_archive/{timestamp}/` | `restarted` (same field set plus `archivedPath`) | operator wants to clear the workspace and replay with a new angle |\n\n**Contract for every persisted lifecycle event**:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"event\",\n  \"event\": \"resumed | restarted\",\n  \"mode\": \"research\",\n  \"sessionId\": \"<session id of the new or continuing lineage>\",\n  \"parentSessionId\": \"<session id of the prior lineage (equals sessionId on resume)>\",\n  \"lineageMode\": \"resume | restart\",\n  \"generation\": <number>,\n  \"continuedFromRun\": <number or null>,\n  \"archivedPath\": \"<path or null>\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"<ISO 8601>\"\n}\n```\n\nEvery field in the contract MUST be present on every persisted lifecycle event. `archivedPath` is null for `resumed` and set to the archive destination for `restarted`. `continuedFromRun` is the number of completed iteration records before the lifecycle boundary. Reducer parity tests ensure the dashboard `Lifecycle` section reads exactly those fields.\n\n---\n\n## 3. PHASE: ITERATION LOOP\n\n### Loop Steps (repeated until convergence)\n\n#### Step 1: Read State\n- Read `deep-research-state.jsonl` -- count iterations, get last newInfoRatio\n- Read `deep-research-strategy.md` -- get next focus, remaining questions\n\n#### Step 2: Check Convergence\nRun the convergence algorithm (see convergence.md):\n- Max iterations reached? STOP\n- Stuck count >= threshold? STUCK_RECOVERY\n- Average newInfoRatio < threshold? STOP\n- All questions answered? STOP\n- Otherwise: CONTINUE\n\n#### Step 2c: Quality Guard Check\n\nWhen the convergence algorithm returns STOP:\n1. Run quality guard checks (see convergence.md В§2.4)\n2. Verify minimum coverage, source diversity, and question resolution thresholds\n3. If **all guards pass**: proceed with STOP, exit to synthesis\n4. If **any guard fails**: override decision to CONTINUE\n   - Log each violation: `{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"guard_violation\",\"guard\":\"<name>\",\"iteration\":N,\"detail\":\"<reason>\"}`\n   - Persist the blocked legal-stop outcome: `{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"blocked_stop\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"run\":N,\"blockedBy\":[\"<gate>\"],\"gateResults\":{\"convergence\":{\"pass\":true,\"score\":0.0},\"keyQuestionCoverage\":{\"pass\":false,\"answered\":X,\"total\":Y},\"evidenceDensity\":{\"pass\":false,\"sources\":N},\"hotspotSaturation\":{\"pass\":true}},\"recoveryStrategy\":\"<one-line hint>\",\"timestamp\":\"<ISO8601>\",\"sessionId\":\"<sid>\",\"generation\":G}`\n   - Append failed guard details to strategy.md \"Active Risks\" section\n5. The loop continues until BOTH convergence AND quality guards pass simultaneously\n6. Guard checks apply only to STOP decisions - CONTINUE and STUCK_RECOVERY bypass this step\n\nIf the legal-stop decision tree returns `blocked`, the workflow MUST append the `blocked_stop` JSONL event before continuing. Reducers and dashboards consume the persisted event; they must not infer blocked-stop state solely from prose logs.\n\n#### Step 2a: Check Pause Sentinel\n\nBefore dispatching, check for a pause sentinel file:\n\n1. Check if `research/.deep-research-pause` exists\n2. If present:\n   - Log event to JSONL: `{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"userPaused\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"run\":N,\"stopReason\":\"userPaused\",\"sentinelPath\":\"{artifact_dir}/.deep-research-pause\",\"timestamp\":\"<ISO8601>\",\"sessionId\":\"<sid>\",\"generation\":G}`\n   - Halt the loop with message:\n     ```text\n     Research paused. Delete research/.deep-research-pause to resume.\n     Current state: Iteration {N}, {remaining} questions remaining.\n     ```\n   - Do NOT exit to synthesis -- the loop is suspended, not stopped\n3. On resume (file deleted and loop restarted):\n   - Log event: `{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"resumed\",\"fromIteration\":N}`\n   - Continue from step_read_state\n\nPause and recovery events use the frozen stop-reason enum on the live path. Raw `paused` and `stuck_recovery` labels are legacy aliases and MUST be normalized to `userPaused` and `stuckRecovery` at emission time.\n\n**Use case**: In autonomous mode, this provides the only graceful intervention mechanism short of killing the process. Users can create the sentinel file at any time to pause research between iterations.\n\n#### Step 2b: Generate State Summary\n\nGenerate a compact state summary (~200 tokens) for injection into the dispatch prompt:\n\n```text\nSTATE SUMMARY (auto-generated):\nSegment: {current_segment} | Iteration: {N} of {max}\nQuestions: {answered}/{total} answered | Last focus: {last_focus}\nLast 2 ratios: {ratio_N-1} -> {ratio_N} | Stuck count: {stuck_count}\nRecovery: {active_recovery_strategy or \"none\"}\nNext focus: {strategy.nextFocus}\n```\n\nThis summary is prepended to the dispatch context (Step 3) to ensure the agent has baseline context even if detailed strategy.md reading fails or is incomplete. It serves as a redundant context channel.\n\n#### Step 3: Dispatch Agent\nDispatch `@deep-research` with explicit context:\n```text\n{state_summary}  // Auto-generated (Step 2b)\n\nResearch Topic: {config.topic}\nIteration: {N} of {maxIterations}\nFocus Area: {strategy.nextFocus}\nRemaining Questions: {strategy.remainingQuestions}\nLast 3 Iterations Summary: {brief summaries}\nResource Map: if `config.resource_map_present == true`, prior-inventoried files are listed in `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md`; treat them as the exclusion set when hunting for net-new files; flag only missed-from-map candidates as gaps.\nState Files:\n  - Config: {artifact_dir}/deep-research-config.json\n  - State: {artifact_dir}/deep-research-state.jsonl\n  - Strategy: {artifact_dir}/deep-research-strategy.md\nOutput: Write findings to {artifact_dir}/iterations/iteration-{NNN}.md\nCONSTRAINT: LEAF agent -- do NOT dispatch sub-agents\n```\n\n#### Executor Resolution (spec 018 + 019)\n\nBefore dispatching, the YAML resolves the executor via `parseExecutorConfig` from `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/deep-loop/executor-config.ts`. The resolved `config.executor.kind` selects the dispatch branch:\n\n- `native` (spec 018): dispatch `@deep-research` agent with model Opus.\n- `cli-codex` (spec 018): pipe rendered prompt via stdin to `codex exec --model X -c model_reasoning_effort=Y -c service_tier=Z -c approval_policy=never --sandbox workspace-write`.\n- `cli-claude-code` (spec 019): `claude -p \"$(cat prompt)\" --model X --permission-mode acceptEdits --output-format text` with optional `--effort Y`. Default permission-mode is `plan` (read-only); we override to `acceptEdits` so iteration writes succeed.\n\nAll branches share:\n1. Pre-dispatch prompt rendering via `renderPromptPack` (writes to `{artifact_dir}/prompts/iteration-{n}.md`).\n2. Post-dispatch validation via `validateIterationOutputs` (asserts iteration file + JSONL delta + required fields).\n3. Executor audit append via `appendExecutorAuditToLastRecord` (skipped when kind=='native').\n\nPer-kind flag-compatibility is enforced at config parse time by `EXECUTOR_KIND_FLAG_SUPPORT` in `executor-config.ts`. Setting a flag that the chosen kind does not support throws `ExecutorConfigError` before dispatch.\n\nCross-CLI delegation (a running executor invoking other CLIs via its shell) is documented design intent. Runtime recursion detection is out of scope; see the SKILL.md Cross-CLI Delegation subsection.\n\nFailure handling remains unchanged from spec 018: `schema_mismatch` вҶ’ conflict event вҶ’ 3 consecutive failures вҶ’ `stuck_recovery`.\n\nThe dispatch context may include a suggested `focusTrack` label (e.g., `\"focusTrack\": \"performance\"`, `\"focusTrack\": \"security\"`). Agents may tag their iteration with this track label for post-hoc grouping and analysis. Track labels are metadata only - the orchestrator does not use them for loop decisions.\n\n#### Step 3a: Per-Iteration Budget\n\nAfter dispatch, the orchestrator monitors the running iteration against budget limits:\n- **Tool call count**: tracked against `config.maxToolCallsPerIteration` (default: 12)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":260,"totalLines":617,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md","time":{"start":1782532211359,"end":1782532211372}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e76213ab5cc5f56016a3f48734bc48191b924c85cc8a72955"}},"id":"prt_f0733029b001RE4SQJWWb2aSJJ","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","messageID":"msg_f073297d6001A3dxut5pYElRvw"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532211384,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_bXhmFPmAPsNNzClrWNkLSEOk","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/state/state_format.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/state/state_format.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: State Format Reference\n3: description: Live state packet hub for the deep-research loop.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"research state format\"\n6:   - \"research state packet hub\"\n7:   - \"research file ownership model\"\n8:   - \"research file protection rules\"\n9:   - \"research packet location\"\n10: importance_tier: important\n11: contextType: implementation\n12: version: 1.14.0.29\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # State Format Reference\n16: \n17: Live state packet hub for deep-research files, mutability, and routed state references.\n18: \n19: ---\n20: \n21: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n22: \n23: ### Purpose\n24: \n25: Summarize the live deep-research packet files, mutability rules, and focused state references without carrying every JSON shape inline.\n26: \n27: ### When to Use\n28: \n29: Load this hub when navigating packet files, deciding file ownership, or choosing which detailed state reference to load next.\n30: \n31: ### Routed Details\n32: \n33: - `state_jsonl.md` for config, iteration, event, lifecycle, graph, and blocked-stop records.\n34: - `state_outputs.md` for strategy, iteration markdown, `research.md`, dashboard, and resource-map output.\n35: - `state_reducer_registry.md` for reducer ownership, findings registry, validation, reconstruction, and file protection.\n36: \n37: For iterative code review state, use `deep-review`. Review-mode state is not part of this skill's live state contract.\n38: \n39: ### Packet Summary\n40: \n41: The deep-research loop persists continuity in packet files so each iteration can run with fresh context.\n42: \n43: | File | Format | Purpose | Mutability |\n44: |------|--------|---------|------------|\n45: | `deep-research-config.json` | JSON | Loop parameters and lineage | Created at init; read-only after |\n46: | `deep-research-state.jsonl` | JSONL | Append-only structured log | Append-only |\n47: | `deep-research-strategy.md` | Markdown | Current research plan and next focus | Reducer-managed sections |\n48: | `deep-research-findings-registry.json` / `findings-registry.json` | JSON | Reducer-owned findings and question state | Auto-generated |\n49: | `deep-research-dashboard.md` | Markdown | Operator summary | Auto-generated |\n50: | `iterations/iteration-NNN.md` | Markdown | Per-iteration narrative | Write-once |\n51: | `deltas/iter-NNN.jsonl` | JSONL | Per-iteration structured delta | Write-once |\n52: | `research.md` | Markdown | Final/progressive synthesis | Workflow-owned |\n53: | `resource-map.md` | Markdown | Optional evidence-derived resource map | Workflow-owned |\n54: \n55: The artifact directory is resolved by `resolveArtifactRoot(specFolder, 'research')` from `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/review-research-paths.cjs`.\n56: \n57: ---\n58: \n59: ## 2. PACKET LOCATION\n60: \n61: Root specs use:\n62: \n63: ```text\n64: {spec_folder}/research/\n65: ```\n66: \n67: Child-phase and sub-phase targets use flat-first behavior:\n68: \n69: - first run with an empty local `research/` directory writes flat at `{spec_folder}/research/`;\n70: - a `{basename(spec_folder)}-pt-NN` subfolder is allocated only when prior content already exists for a non-matching target;\n71: - continuation runs reuse the existing matching packet.\n72: \n73: This avoids an unnecessary `pt-01` wrapper on first runs.\n74: \n75: ---\n76: \n77: ## 3. OWNERSHIP MODEL\n78: \n79: | Owner | Writes |\n80: |-------|--------|\n81: | Agent iteration | `iterations/iteration-NNN.md`, JSONL iteration/event append, optional progressive synthesis contribution |\n82: | Workflow reducer | strategy machine-owned sections, findings registry, dashboard |\n83: | Workflow synthesis | `research.md`, lifecycle snapshots |\n84: | Spec anchoring protocol | bounded `spec.md` seed/context/fenced findings block |\n85: \n86: The reducer is the source of truth for derived state. Manual edits to reducer-owned outputs are overwritten on the next refresh.\n87: \n88: ---\n89: \n90: ## 4. FILE PROTECTION\n91: \n92: | Protection | Meaning |\n93: |------------|---------|\n94: | `immutable` | Created once and not modified after init |\n95: | `append-only` | New JSONL records may be appended; existing records are not rewritten |\n96: | `write-once` | Each iteration artifact is created once |\n97: | `mutable` | Workflow may update the file under defined ownership rules |\n98: | `auto-generated` | Reducer/workflow regenerates the full file |\n99: \n100: The config file carries the protection map; details live in `state_reducer_registry.md`.\n101: \n102: ---\n103: \n104: ## 5. ROUTED REFERENCES\n105: \n106: | Resource | Use When |\n107: |----------|----------|\n108: | `state_jsonl.md` | Need the JSONL config, iteration, event, lineage, graph, or blocked-stop schemas |\n109: | `state_outputs.md` | Need markdown output structure for strategy, iterations, dashboard, research synthesis, or resource map |\n110: | `state_reducer_registry.md` | Need reducer ownership, registry schema, validation, fault tolerance, or reconstruction |\n111: | `../convergence/convergence.md` | Need STOP contract and legal-stop semantics |\n112: | `../protocol/spec_check_protocol.md` | Need bounded `spec.md` anchoring and generated-fence write-back |\n113: \n114: ---\n115: \n116: ## 6. NON-GOALS\n117: \n118: - Do not document `deep-review` state here; route to the sibling skill.\n119: - Do not treat legacy aliases as write targets. The workflow reads legacy aliases only for migration windows and writes canonical `deep-research-*` names.\n120: - Do not manually edit reducer-owned dashboard or registry files.\n\n(End of file - total 120 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: State Format Reference\ndescription: Live state packet hub for the deep-research loop.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"research state format\"\n  - \"research state packet hub\"\n  - \"research file ownership model\"\n  - \"research file protection rules\"\n  - \"research packet location\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.14.0.29\n---\n\n# State Format Reference\n\nLive state packet hub for deep-research files, mutability, and routed state references.\n\n---\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/state/state_format.md","text":"---\ntitle: State Format Reference\ndescription: Live state packet hub for the deep-research loop.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"research state format\"\n  - \"research state packet hub\"\n  - \"research file ownership model\"\n  - \"research file protection rules\"\n  - \"research packet location\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.14.0.29\n---\n\n# State Format Reference\n\nLive state packet hub for deep-research files, mutability, and routed state references.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nSummarize the live deep-research packet files, mutability rules, and focused state references without carrying every JSON shape inline.\n\n### When to Use\n\nLoad this hub when navigating packet files, deciding file ownership, or choosing which detailed state reference to load next.\n\n### Routed Details\n\n- `state_jsonl.md` for config, iteration, event, lifecycle, graph, and blocked-stop records.\n- `state_outputs.md` for strategy, iteration markdown, `research.md`, dashboard, and resource-map output.\n- `state_reducer_registry.md` for reducer ownership, findings registry, validation, reconstruction, and file protection.\n\nFor iterative code review state, use `deep-review`. Review-mode state is not part of this skill's live state contract.\n\n### Packet Summary\n\nThe deep-research loop persists continuity in packet files so each iteration can run with fresh context.\n\n| File | Format | Purpose | Mutability |\n|------|--------|---------|------------|\n| `deep-research-config.json` | JSON | Loop parameters and lineage | Created at init; read-only after |\n| `deep-research-state.jsonl` | JSONL | Append-only structured log | Append-only |\n| `deep-research-strategy.md` | Markdown | Current research plan and next focus | Reducer-managed sections |\n| `deep-research-findings-registry.json` / `findings-registry.json` | JSON | Reducer-owned findings and question state | Auto-generated |\n| `deep-research-dashboard.md` | Markdown | Operator summary | Auto-generated |\n| `iterations/iteration-NNN.md` | Markdown | Per-iteration narrative | Write-once |\n| `deltas/iter-NNN.jsonl` | JSONL | Per-iteration structured delta | Write-once |\n| `research.md` | Markdown | Final/progressive synthesis | Workflow-owned |\n| `resource-map.md` | Markdown | Optional evidence-derived resource map | Workflow-owned |\n\nThe artifact directory is resolved by `resolveArtifactRoot(specFolder, 'research')` from `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/review-research-paths.cjs`.\n\n---\n\n## 2. PACKET LOCATION\n\nRoot specs use:\n\n```text\n{spec_folder}/research/\n```\n\nChild-phase and sub-phase targets use flat-first behavior:\n\n- first run with an empty local `research/` directory writes flat at `{spec_folder}/research/`;\n- a `{basename(spec_folder)}-pt-NN` subfolder is allocated only when prior content already exists for a non-matching target;\n- continuation runs reuse the existing matching packet.\n\nThis avoids an unnecessary `pt-01` wrapper on first runs.\n\n---\n\n## 3. OWNERSHIP MODEL\n\n| Owner | Writes |\n|-------|--------|\n| Agent iteration | `iterations/iteration-NNN.md`, JSONL iteration/event append, optional progressive synthesis contribution |\n| Workflow reducer | strategy machine-owned sections, findings registry, dashboard |\n| Workflow synthesis | `research.md`, lifecycle snapshots |\n| Spec anchoring protocol | bounded `spec.md` seed/context/fenced findings block |\n\nThe reducer is the source of truth for derived state. Manual edits to reducer-owned outputs are overwritten on the next refresh.\n\n---\n\n## 4. FILE PROTECTION\n\n| Protection | Meaning |\n|------------|---------|\n| `immutable` | Created once and not modified after init |\n| `append-only` | New JSONL records may be appended; existing records are not rewritten |\n| `write-once` | Each iteration artifact is created once |\n| `mutable` | Workflow may update the file under defined ownership rules |\n| `auto-generated` | Reducer/workflow regenerates the full file |\n\nThe config file carries the protection map; details live in `state_reducer_registry.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. ROUTED REFERENCES\n\n| Resource | Use When |\n|----------|----------|\n| `state_jsonl.md` | Need the JSONL config, iteration, event, lineage, graph, or blocked-stop schemas |\n| `state_outputs.md` | Need markdown output structure for strategy, iterations, dashboard, research synthesis, or resource map |\n| `state_reducer_registry.md` | Need reducer ownership, registry schema, validation, fault tolerance, or reconstruction |\n| `../convergence/convergence.md` | Need STOP contract and legal-stop semantics |\n| `../protocol/spec_check_protocol.md` | Need bounded `spec.md` anchoring and generated-fence write-back |\n\n---\n\n## 6. NON-GOALS\n\n- Do not document `deep-review` state here; route to the sibling skill.\n- Do not treat legacy aliases as write targets. The workflow reads legacy aliases only for migration windows and writes canonical `deep-research-*` names.\n- Do not manually edit reducer-owned dashboard or registry files.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":120,"totalLines":120,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/state/state_format.md","time":{"start":1782532211377,"end":1782532211381}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e76213ab5cc5f56016a3f48734bd08191aba933544a63ca1d"}},"id":"prt_f073302a7001EvTnL8oSu64A9Q","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","messageID":"msg_f073297d6001A3dxut5pYElRvw"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532211392,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_EN0csITXK3Vi3YInFWCCXuXm","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/convergence/convergence.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/convergence/convergence.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Convergence Detection Reference\n3: description: Live stop contract and navigation hub for deep-research convergence.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"research convergence detection\"\n6:   - \"research stop contract\"\n7:   - \"research stopreason values\"\n8:   - \"research legal stop gates\"\n9:   - \"research convergence decision order\"\n10: importance_tier: important\n11: contextType: implementation\n12: version: 1.14.0.20\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # Convergence Detection Reference\n16: \n17: Live stop-contract hub for deep-research convergence and routed convergence references.\n18: \n19: ---\n20: \n21: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n22: \n23: ### Purpose\n24: \n25: Keep the executable deep-research stop contract short enough to load during routing while pointing detailed signal, recovery, and graph behavior to focused references.\n26: \n27: ### When to Use\n28: \n29: Load this hub when deciding whether a deep-research loop should continue, recover, or stop.\n30: \n31: ### Key Sources\n32: \n33: - Command syntax: `.opencode/commands/deep/research.md`\n34: - Workflow algorithm: `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml` and `_confirm.yaml`\n35: - Signal details: `references/convergence/convergence_signals.md`\n36: - Recovery details: `references/convergence/convergence_recovery.md`\n37: - Graph stop gates: `references/convergence/convergence_graph.md`\n38: \n39: For iterative code review convergence, use `deep-review`. Review-mode algorithms and state are not part of the deep-research live contract.\n40: \n41: ### Live Decision Model\n42: \n43: Convergence decides whether the loop should continue, recover from a stuck state, or stop. A STOP candidate is not legal until the legal-stop gate bundle passes. Novelty math can nominate STOP; gates authorize it.\n44: \n45: The live deep-research algorithm evaluates:\n46: \n47: | Stage | Outcome |\n48: |-------|---------|\n49: | Hard stops | Stop on max iterations or all key questions answered |\n50: | Stuck detection | Enter recovery after configured consecutive no-progress iterations |\n51: | Composite convergence | Nominate STOP when weighted signal score is above `0.60` |\n52: | Legal-stop gates | Allow or block the STOP candidate |\n53: | Graph gates | Add STOP-blocking graph checks when `graphEvents` exist |\n54: \n55: ---\n56: \n57: ## 2. STOP CONTRACT\n58: \n59: ### stopReason Values\n60: \n61: | Value | When It Is Used |\n62: |-------|-----------------|\n63: | `converged` | Legal-stop gates passed and the loop may exit normally |\n64: | `maxIterationsReached` | The loop hit the configured iteration cap |\n65: | `userPaused` | A pause sentinel or equivalent user pause request halted execution |\n66: | `blockedStop` | A STOP candidate was blocked by legal-stop or graph gates |\n67: | `stuckRecovery` | Stuck detection triggered or failed recovery |\n68: | `error` | The loop hit an unrecoverable workflow or state error |\n69: \n70: ### Legacy Stop Labels\n71: \n72: Legacy labels are normalized before persistence:\n73: \n74: | Legacy label or phrase | New `stopReason` |\n75: |------------------------|------------------|\n76: | `composite_converged` | `converged` |\n77: | `novelty below threshold` | `converged` |\n78: | `all_questions_answered` | `converged` |\n79: | `max_iterations_reached` | `maxIterationsReached` |\n80: | `paused` | `userPaused` |\n81: | `stuck_detected` | `stuckRecovery` |\n82: | `stuck_unrecoverable` | `stuckRecovery` |\n83: \n84: ---\n85: \n86: ## 3. LIVE ALGORITHM\n87: \n88: ### Decision Order\n89: \n90: ```text\n91: 1. If iteration count >= maxIterations, STOP with maxIterationsReached.\n92: 2. If all key questions have evidence-backed answers, nominate STOP.\n93: 3. If stuckCount >= stuckThreshold, enter stuck recovery.\n94: 4. Compute composite convergence signals.\n95: 5. If weighted stop score > 0.60, nominate STOP.\n96: 6. Evaluate legal-stop gates for every STOP candidate except hard max-iteration stop.\n97: 7. If graphEvents exist, evaluate graph-aware STOP blockers.\n98: 8. If gates pass, STOP; otherwise emit blockedStop and CONTINUE with recovery focus.\n99: ```\n100: \n101: ### Composite Signal Weights\n102: \n103: | Signal | Weight | Min Iterations | Measures |\n104: |--------|--------|----------------|----------|\n105: | Rolling Average | `0.30` | 3 evidence iterations | Recent information yield |\n106: | MAD Noise Floor | `0.35` | 4 evidence iterations | Signal vs noise in `newInfoRatio` |\n107: | Question Entropy | `0.35` | 1 key question | Evidence-backed question coverage |\n108: \n109: The weighted stop score is normalized over active signals. STOP is nominated only when the normalized score is greater than `0.60`. See `convergence_signals.md` for exact signal rules and reporting.\n110: \n111: ---\n112: \n113: ## 4. LEGAL STOP GATES\n114: \n115: Every non-terminal STOP candidate must pass the gate bundle before the workflow exits.\n116: \n117: | Gate | Rule | Failure |\n118: |------|------|---------|\n119: | Convergence Gate | Low novelty holds for the required consecutive evidence iterations | Emit `blocked_stop`, continue |\n120: | Coverage Gate | Every key question has an evidence-backed answer | Emit `blocked_stop`, continue |\n121: | Quality Gate | Source diversity, focus alignment, and no single weak-source dominance pass | Emit `blocked_stop`, continue |\n122: | Graph Gate | When graph data exists, graph coverage has no STOP blockers | Emit `graph_convergence`/`blocked_stop`, continue |\n123: \n124: The reducer surfaces legal-stop evidence through the findings registry and dashboard. The JSONL event shapes live in `../state/state_jsonl.md`.\n125: \n126: ---\n127: \n128: ## 5. ROUTED REFERENCES\n129: \n130: | Resource | Use When |\n131: |----------|----------|\n132: | `convergence_signals.md` | Need scoring, `newInfoRatio`, `stuckCount`, MAD, entropy, report fields, or threshold tuning |\n133: | `convergence_recovery.md` | Need stuck recovery, recovery strategy selection, tiered errors, or escalation behavior |\n134: | `convergence_graph.md` | Need graph-aware STOP gates, graph convergence events, or coverage graph fallback behavior |\n135: | `convergence_reference_only.md` | Need future/reference-only models such as segment filtering, semantic convergence, or optimizer metadata |\n136: | `../state/state_jsonl.md` | Need JSONL event shapes persisted by the convergence workflow |\n137: | `../state/state_reducer_registry.md` | Need reducer-owned registry/dashboard fields derived from convergence |\n138: \n139: ---\n140: \n141: ## 6. NON-GOALS\n142: \n143: - Do not copy `deep-review` convergence into this skill. Use the `deep-review` references for severity-weighted review convergence.\n144: - Do not treat reference-only semantic or segment models as executable contracts.\n145: - Do not change the YAML workflow by editing this document. This document describes and routes the live contract; workflow changes require command/YAML work.\n\n(End of file - total 145 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Convergence Detection Reference\ndescription: Live stop contract and navigation hub for deep-research convergence.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"research convergence detection\"\n  - \"research stop contract\"\n  - \"research stopreason values\"\n  - \"research legal stop gates\"\n  - \"research convergence decision order\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.14.0.20\n---\n\n# Convergence Detection Reference\n\nLive stop-contract hub for deep-research convergence and routed convergence references.\n\n---\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/convergence/convergence.md","text":"---\ntitle: Convergence Detection Reference\ndescription: Live stop contract and navigation hub for deep-research convergence.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"research convergence detection\"\n  - \"research stop contract\"\n  - \"research stopreason values\"\n  - \"research legal stop gates\"\n  - \"research convergence decision order\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.14.0.20\n---\n\n# Convergence Detection Reference\n\nLive stop-contract hub for deep-research convergence and routed convergence references.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nKeep the executable deep-research stop contract short enough to load during routing while pointing detailed signal, recovery, and graph behavior to focused references.\n\n### When to Use\n\nLoad this hub when deciding whether a deep-research loop should continue, recover, or stop.\n\n### Key Sources\n\n- Command syntax: `.opencode/commands/deep/research.md`\n- Workflow algorithm: `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml` and `_confirm.yaml`\n- Signal details: `references/convergence/convergence_signals.md`\n- Recovery details: `references/convergence/convergence_recovery.md`\n- Graph stop gates: `references/convergence/convergence_graph.md`\n\nFor iterative code review convergence, use `deep-review`. Review-mode algorithms and state are not part of the deep-research live contract.\n\n### Live Decision Model\n\nConvergence decides whether the loop should continue, recover from a stuck state, or stop. A STOP candidate is not legal until the legal-stop gate bundle passes. Novelty math can nominate STOP; gates authorize it.\n\nThe live deep-research algorithm evaluates:\n\n| Stage | Outcome |\n|-------|---------|\n| Hard stops | Stop on max iterations or all key questions answered |\n| Stuck detection | Enter recovery after configured consecutive no-progress iterations |\n| Composite convergence | Nominate STOP when weighted signal score is above `0.60` |\n| Legal-stop gates | Allow or block the STOP candidate |\n| Graph gates | Add STOP-blocking graph checks when `graphEvents` exist |\n\n---\n\n## 2. STOP CONTRACT\n\n### stopReason Values\n\n| Value | When It Is Used |\n|-------|-----------------|\n| `converged` | Legal-stop gates passed and the loop may exit normally |\n| `maxIterationsReached` | The loop hit the configured iteration cap |\n| `userPaused` | A pause sentinel or equivalent user pause request halted execution |\n| `blockedStop` | A STOP candidate was blocked by legal-stop or graph gates |\n| `stuckRecovery` | Stuck detection triggered or failed recovery |\n| `error` | The loop hit an unrecoverable workflow or state error |\n\n### Legacy Stop Labels\n\nLegacy labels are normalized before persistence:\n\n| Legacy label or phrase | New `stopReason` |\n|------------------------|------------------|\n| `composite_converged` | `converged` |\n| `novelty below threshold` | `converged` |\n| `all_questions_answered` | `converged` |\n| `max_iterations_reached` | `maxIterationsReached` |\n| `paused` | `userPaused` |\n| `stuck_detected` | `stuckRecovery` |\n| `stuck_unrecoverable` | `stuckRecovery` |\n\n---\n\n## 3. LIVE ALGORITHM\n\n### Decision Order\n\n```text\n1. If iteration count >= maxIterations, STOP with maxIterationsReached.\n2. If all key questions have evidence-backed answers, nominate STOP.\n3. If stuckCount >= stuckThreshold, enter stuck recovery.\n4. Compute composite convergence signals.\n5. If weighted stop score > 0.60, nominate STOP.\n6. Evaluate legal-stop gates for every STOP candidate except hard max-iteration stop.\n7. If graphEvents exist, evaluate graph-aware STOP blockers.\n8. If gates pass, STOP; otherwise emit blockedStop and CONTINUE with recovery focus.\n```\n\n### Composite Signal Weights\n\n| Signal | Weight | Min Iterations | Measures |\n|--------|--------|----------------|----------|\n| Rolling Average | `0.30` | 3 evidence iterations | Recent information yield |\n| MAD Noise Floor | `0.35` | 4 evidence iterations | Signal vs noise in `newInfoRatio` |\n| Question Entropy | `0.35` | 1 key question | Evidence-backed question coverage |\n\nThe weighted stop score is normalized over active signals. STOP is nominated only when the normalized score is greater than `0.60`. See `convergence_signals.md` for exact signal rules and reporting.\n\n---\n\n## 4. LEGAL STOP GATES\n\nEvery non-terminal STOP candidate must pass the gate bundle before the workflow exits.\n\n| Gate | Rule | Failure |\n|------|------|---------|\n| Convergence Gate | Low novelty holds for the required consecutive evidence iterations | Emit `blocked_stop`, continue |\n| Coverage Gate | Every key question has an evidence-backed answer | Emit `blocked_stop`, continue |\n| Quality Gate | Source diversity, focus alignment, and no single weak-source dominance pass | Emit `blocked_stop`, continue |\n| Graph Gate | When graph data exists, graph coverage has no STOP blockers | Emit `graph_convergence`/`blocked_stop`, continue |\n\nThe reducer surfaces legal-stop evidence through the findings registry and dashboard. The JSONL event shapes live in `../state/state_jsonl.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. ROUTED REFERENCES\n\n| Resource | Use When |\n|----------|----------|\n| `convergence_signals.md` | Need scoring, `newInfoRatio`, `stuckCount`, MAD, entropy, report fields, or threshold tuning |\n| `convergence_recovery.md` | Need stuck recovery, recovery strategy selection, tiered errors, or escalation behavior |\n| `convergence_graph.md` | Need graph-aware STOP gates, graph convergence events, or coverage graph fallback behavior |\n| `convergence_reference_only.md` | Need future/reference-only models such as segment filtering, semantic convergence, or optimizer metadata |\n| `../state/state_jsonl.md` | Need JSONL event shapes persisted by the convergence workflow |\n| `../state/state_reducer_registry.md` | Need reducer-owned registry/dashboard fields derived from convergence |\n\n---\n\n## 6. NON-GOALS\n\n- Do not copy `deep-review` convergence into this skill. Use the `deep-review` references for severity-weighted review convergence.\n- Do not treat reference-only semantic or segment models as executable contracts.\n- Do not change the YAML workflow by editing this document. This document describes and routes the live contract; workflow changes require command/YAML work.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":145,"totalLines":145,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/convergence/convergence.md","time":{"start":1782532211383,"end":1782532211391}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e76213ab5cc5f56016a3f48734bd8819195905194f24ab8f8"}},"id":"prt_f073302b2001ZLuA0vvVI7JjYD","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","messageID":"msg_f073297d6001A3dxut5pYElRvw"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532211440,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_AwpEZ8sMPZOplElkJZxUPHW6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: sk-design\n3: description: \"Distinctive, intentional UI design and the full design surface: visual direction, taste, and build for interfaces; color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, and design tokens; animation, transitions, and micro-interactions; accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, and anti-slop design audit with quality scoring; and live-website CSS to Style Reference DESIGN.md extraction. Use to make a UI look custom and polished rather than templated, design a visual system, choreograph motion, audit and harden design quality, or extract a real design system from a live site. The single advisor-routable design skill: it routes to five modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) via mode-registry.json, and each mode holds its own design logic.\"\n4: allowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\n5: version: 1.0.0.0\n6: metadata:\n7:   author: OpenCode\n8:   family: sk-code\n9: ---\n10: \n11: <!-- Keywords: sk-design, design-family, mode-registry, workflowmode, backendkind, reference-base, anti-slop, design-tokens, cognitive-laws, interface-design, frontend-design, visual-design, visual-identity, make-it-look-good, looks-templated, redesign-the-ui, hero-section, ui-build, typography, palette, color-palette, font-pairing, ux-quality-checklist, design-variations, foundations, color-system, oklch, color-token-system, dark-mode, typography-scale, spacing-system, responsive-layout, layout, hierarchy, grid, themes, motion-design, animation, animate-this, transitions, micro-interactions, framer-motion, animatepresence, exit-animation, reduced-motion, morphing-icons, motion-performance, design-audit, ui-critique, accessibility-audit, performance-audit, anti-slop-detection, production-hardening, design-quality-score, P0-P1-design-findings, polish, theming, design.md, design-md, css-extraction, website-design-extraction, design-reference, tokens.json, playwright, design-to-markdown, design-system-generator, css-tokens, color-extraction, typography-extraction, hex-extraction, shadow-extraction, spacing-extraction, design-fidelity, anti-hallucination, extract-design-system, generate-design-md, capture-website-css, design-tokens-from-url, distinctive-interface, intentional-design, polished-ui, refined-ui, custom-not-templated, premium-ui, aesthetic, design-taste, visual-direction, craft, make-it-beautiful, less-generic, redesign-distinctive, smooth-animation, hover-effect, scroll-animation, choreography, interaction-feel, animate-the-menu, transition-design, design-audit, accessibility-audit, design-quality-audit, design-review, design-qa, audit-the-design, review-the-ui, wcag-contrast, ui-quality-review -->\n12: \n13: # Design Family Hub (sk-design)\n14: \n15: One skill, five design modes, one shared reference base. `sk-design` is the public, advisor-routable home for every design persona; the shared design reference base (anti-slop principles, cognitive laws, design-token vocabulary) is the common vocabulary the modes cite. This hub holds NO per-mode design logic вҖ” each mode keeps its own contract in its packet, and the hub only routes by `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json`.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ## 1. WHEN TO USE\n20: \n21: Use this skill (through the hub) for any design-family workflow. Invoke it as `sk-design` (optionally with a mode hint such as `motion: <request>`); the hub classifies the request, resolves a mode key, and loads the matching nested packet.\n22: \n23: | Mode | Use it for | Packet |\n24: |------|-----------|--------|\n25: | **interface** | Distinctive, intentional UI direction and build judgment, visual identity, redesign, generic \"make it look good\", interface writing | `sk-design/design-interface/` |\n26: | **foundations** | Static visual-system decisions: color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, responsive adaptation, themes, design tokens | `sk-design/design-foundations/` |\n27: | **motion** | Temporal interaction design: animation, transitions, micro-interactions, motion materials, `AnimatePresence`, reduced motion | `sk-design/design-motion/` |\n28: | **audit** | Design QA and critique: accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, anti-slop detection, scoring, production hardening | `sk-design/design-audit/` |\n29: | **md-generator** | Extract a live website's real CSS into a v3 Style Reference `DESIGN.md` via the embedded extract-write-validate pipeline | `sk-design/design-md-generator/` |\n30: \n31: ### When NOT to Use\n32: - A single quick read/edit with no design judgment вҖ” use the relevant skill directly.\n33: - Pure implementation after design direction is settled вҖ” hand off to `sk-code`.\n34: - A design transport only (Figma, Open Design) вҖ” load the design judgment via this hub first, then use the transport. The transport is never the taste authority.\n35: - The shared reference base itself вҖ” it is the vocabulary the modes cite, not a user workflow.\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ## 2. SMART ROUTING\n40: \n41: Routing is **registry-driven**. `mode-registry.json` is the single source of truth; the hub reads it and does not re-derive the mapping. The advisor routes any design query to the single identity `sk-design`; the hub then picks the mode.\n42: \n43: ### The discriminator\n44: - **`workflowMode`** вҖ” the public mode key (every mode): `interface`, `foundations`, `motion`, `audit`, `md-generator`.\n45: - **`backendKind`** вҖ” which backend runs the mode: `reference-base` (the four doc-guidance modes cite the shared design reference base) or `playwright-extract` (`md-generator` runs its embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline).\n46: \n47: ### Routing rule\n48: ```\n49: classify the request to a workflowMode (dominant design intent; mode hint like \"motion: ...\" overrides)\n50: read mode-registry.json\n51:   вҶ’ resolve workflowMode from the hint / classified intent\n52:   вҶ’ load the mode packet at registry[mode].packet (e.g. sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md)\n53:   вҶ’ the mode cites the shared reference base, or runs its own backend per registry[mode].backendKind\n54: ```\n55: \n56: Intent classification favors the smallest useful mode. Default a generic \"make this look good\" prompt to **interface** unless the prompt is explicitly foundations (tokens/color/type/layout), motion (animation/transition), audit (critique/accessibility/slop), or md-generator (`DESIGN.md`/style-reference extraction). Pair modes only when the prompt has clearly separate design axes (e.g. interface + motion for a landing page with substantial choreography).\n57: \n58: Per-mode behavior is **not flattened**: each packet keeps its own design judgment, examples, standards, verification, and tool-permission needs. The four doc-guidance modes are read-and-guide; `md-generator` is the only mode that runs an extraction pipeline (Write/Edit/Bash over Playwright).\n59: \n60: ---\n61: \n62: ## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n63: \n64: ### Layout\n65: ```\n66: sk-design/\n67:   SKILL.md               # this routing hub (no per-mode design logic)\n68:   mode-registry.json     # the discriminator + advisorRouting (single source of truth)\n69:   graph-metadata.json    # the ONE advisor identity for the whole skill\n70:   references/            # shared design reference base the hub + modes cite\n71:   design-interface/  design-foundations/  design-motion/  design-audit/  design-md-generator/   # five mode packets\n72: ```\n73: \n74: Each mode packet is self-contained (its own `SKILL.md`, `references/`, `assets/`, and `md-generator`'s extraction backend), with internal paths repointed and **no per-packet `graph-metadata.json`** вҖ” only this hub carries one, so the advisor discovers exactly one skill. The mode packet folders are created when the flat skills move under the hub; the hub references those packet paths now.\n75: \n76: ### Backend\n77: The four doc-guidance modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit) consume the shared **design reference base** under `references/` вҖ” `anti_slop_principles.md`, `cognitive_laws.md`, `design_token_vocabulary.md` вҖ” so anti-slop critique, design-token vocabulary, and cognitive-law rationale stay consistent across modes without duplication. The `md-generator` mode consumes its own embedded Playwright extraction backend instead. The reference base provides shared vocabulary; it must never gain per-mode workflow logic.\n78: \n79: ---\n80: \n81: ## 4. RULES\n82: \n83: ### ALWAYS\n84: - **ALWAYS** resolve a mode through `mode-registry.json`; never hardcode a router mapping in the hub.\n85: - **ALWAYS** keep each mode's design judgment, examples, and verification in its packet вҖ” the hub stays logic-free.\n86: - **ALWAYS** keep exactly one `graph-metadata.json` (this hub's) so the advisor sees one skill identity.\n87: - **ALWAYS** give every mode an `advisorRouting` block with a valid `routingClass` and `packetSkillName`.\n88: - **ALWAYS** route a generic design prompt to the smallest useful mode; default to `interface` when no other axis dominates.\n89: \n90: ### NEVER\n91: - **NEVER** add a `graph-metadata.json` or a discoverable skill marker inside a mode packet or the shared reference base.\n92: - **NEVER** embed per-mode design instructions in this hub вҖ” that content lives in the packets.\n93: - **NEVER** treat `mcp-figma` or `mcp-open-design` as taste or critique authority; they are transports loaded after the design mode is chosen.\n94: - **NEVER** route pure code, backend, or data work through the design family.\n95: \n96: ### ESCALATE IF\n97: - A new design mode is needed вҖ” extend `mode-registry.json` and open a packet; do not bolt logic onto the hub.\n98: - A named mode conflicts with the request's actual intent, or the prompt spans more than three design axes needing an explicit workflow order.\n99: - Brand, accessibility, or production constraints make the requested visual direction unsafe or contradictory.\n100: \n101: ---\n102: \n103: ## 5. REFERENCES\n104: \n105: - Shared reference base: `references/anti_slop_principles.md`, `references/cognitive_laws.md`, `references/design_token_vocabulary.md` (cited by every doc-guidance mode).\n106: - Mode packets: `design-interface/SKILL.md`, `design-foundations/SKILL.md`, `design-motion/SKILL.md`, `design-audit/SKILL.md`, `design-md-generator/SKILL.md` (per-mode detail).\n107: - Registry: `mode-registry.json` (the routing contract).\n108: - Implementation handoff: `sk-code` consumes the design output; `sk-code-review` can audit it after build.\n109: \n110: ---\n111: \n112: ## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n113: \n114: - The hub resolves one primary mode for the request (or a small set only for clearly separate axes).\n115: - The selected mode packet owns the detailed design workflow; the hub stayed routing-only.\n116: - The shared reference base is used only for common vocabulary and cross-mode consistency.\n117: - Exactly one `graph-metadata.json` exists for the whole skill; no packet carries its own.\n118: \n119: ---\n120: \n121: ## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n122: \n123: ### Modes\n124: - `interface` вҖ” direction, distinctive UI build judgment, interface writing.\n125: - `foundations` вҖ” color, typography, layout, responsive systems, tokens.\n126: - `motion` вҖ” animation, transitions, micro-interactions, temporal feel.\n127: - `audit` вҖ” accessibility, performance, critique, hardening, production readiness.\n128: - `md-generator` вҖ” `DESIGN.md` / style-reference extraction other skills consume.\n129: \n130: ### Transports and Consumers\n131: - `mcp-figma` and `mcp-open-design` are transports. Use them after the design mode is chosen.\n132: - `sk-code` consumes design output and implements it in the detected code surface.\n133: - `sk-code-review` can audit implementation quality after design and build work converge.\n134: \n135: ---\n136: \n137: ## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n138: \n139: - Pattern: `.opencode/skills/sk-doc/references/skill_creation/parent_skills_nested_packets.md` (parent-skill hub + nested packets, the one-graph-metadata invariant).\n140: - Canonical example: `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/` (hub + `mode-registry.json` + mode packets).\n141: - Registry: `mode-registry.json` (this hub's routing contract).\n\n(End of file - total 141 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: sk-design\ndescription: \"Distinctive, intentional UI design and the full design surface: visual direction, taste, and build for interfaces; color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, and design tokens; animation, transitions, and micro-interactions; accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, and anti-slop design audit with quality scoring; and live-website CSS to Style Reference DESIGN.md extraction. Use to make a UI look custom and polished rather than templated, design a visual system, choreograph motion, audit and harden design quality, or extract a real design system from a live site. The single advisor-routable design skill: it routes to five modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) via mode-registry.json, and each mode holds its own design logic.\"\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nmetadata:\n  author: OpenCode\n  family: sk-code\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: sk-design, design-family, mode-registry, workflowmode, backendkind, reference-base, anti-slop, design-tokens, cognitive-laws, interface-design, frontend-design, visual-design, visual-identity, make-it-look-good, looks-templated, redesign-the-ui, hero-section, ui-build, typography, palette, color-palette, font-pairing, ux-quality-checklist, design-variations, foundations, color-system, oklch, color-token-system, dark-mode, typography-scale, spacing-system, responsive-layout, layout, hierarchy, grid, themes, motion-design, animation, animate-this, transitions, micro-interactions, framer-motion, animatepresence, exit-animation, reduced-motion, morphing-icons, motion-performance, design-audit, ui-critique, accessibility-audit, performance-audit, anti-slop-detection, production-hardening, design-quality-score, P0-P1-design-findings, polish, theming, design.md, design-md, css-extraction, website-design-extraction, design-reference, tokens.json, playwright, design-to-markdown, design-system-generator, css-tokens, color-extraction, typography-extraction, hex-extraction, shadow-extraction, spacing-extraction, design-fidelity, anti-hallucination, extract-design-system, generate-design-md, capture-website-css, design-tokens-from-url, distinctive-interface, intentional-design, polished-ui, refined-ui, custom-not-templated, premium-ui, aesthetic, design-taste, visual-direction, craft, make-it-beautiful, less-generic, redesign-distinctive, smooth-animation, hover-effect, scroll-animation, choreography, interaction-feel, animate-the-menu, transition-design, design-audit, accessibility-audit, design-quality-audit, design-review, design-qa, audit-the-design, review-the-ui, wcag-contrast, ui-quality-review -->\n\n# Design Family Hub (sk-design)\n\nOne skill, five design modes, one shared reference base. `sk-design` is the public, advisor-routable home for every design persona; the shared design reference base (anti-slop principles, cognitive laws, design-token vocabulary) is the common vocabulary the modes cite. This hub holds NO per-mode design logic вҖ” each mode keeps its own contract in its packet, and the hub only routes by `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: sk-design\ndescription: \"Distinctive, intentional UI design and the full design surface: visual direction, taste, and build for interfaces; color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, and design tokens; animation, transitions, and micro-interactions; accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, and anti-slop design audit with quality scoring; and live-website CSS to Style Reference DESIGN.md extraction. Use to make a UI look custom and polished rather than templated, design a visual system, choreograph motion, audit and harden design quality, or extract a real design system from a live site. The single advisor-routable design skill: it routes to five modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) via mode-registry.json, and each mode holds its own design logic.\"\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nmetadata:\n  author: OpenCode\n  family: sk-code\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: sk-design, design-family, mode-registry, workflowmode, backendkind, reference-base, anti-slop, design-tokens, cognitive-laws, interface-design, frontend-design, visual-design, visual-identity, make-it-look-good, looks-templated, redesign-the-ui, hero-section, ui-build, typography, palette, color-palette, font-pairing, ux-quality-checklist, design-variations, foundations, color-system, oklch, color-token-system, dark-mode, typography-scale, spacing-system, responsive-layout, layout, hierarchy, grid, themes, motion-design, animation, animate-this, transitions, micro-interactions, framer-motion, animatepresence, exit-animation, reduced-motion, morphing-icons, motion-performance, design-audit, ui-critique, accessibility-audit, performance-audit, anti-slop-detection, production-hardening, design-quality-score, P0-P1-design-findings, polish, theming, design.md, design-md, css-extraction, website-design-extraction, design-reference, tokens.json, playwright, design-to-markdown, design-system-generator, css-tokens, color-extraction, typography-extraction, hex-extraction, shadow-extraction, spacing-extraction, design-fidelity, anti-hallucination, extract-design-system, generate-design-md, capture-website-css, design-tokens-from-url, distinctive-interface, intentional-design, polished-ui, refined-ui, custom-not-templated, premium-ui, aesthetic, design-taste, visual-direction, craft, make-it-beautiful, less-generic, redesign-distinctive, smooth-animation, hover-effect, scroll-animation, choreography, interaction-feel, animate-the-menu, transition-design, design-audit, accessibility-audit, design-quality-audit, design-review, design-qa, audit-the-design, review-the-ui, wcag-contrast, ui-quality-review -->\n\n# Design Family Hub (sk-design)\n\nOne skill, five design modes, one shared reference base. `sk-design` is the public, advisor-routable home for every design persona; the shared design reference base (anti-slop principles, cognitive laws, design-token vocabulary) is the common vocabulary the modes cite. This hub holds NO per-mode design logic вҖ” each mode keeps its own contract in its packet, and the hub only routes by `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n\nUse this skill (through the hub) for any design-family workflow. Invoke it as `sk-design` (optionally with a mode hint such as `motion: <request>`); the hub classifies the request, resolves a mode key, and loads the matching nested packet.\n\n| Mode | Use it for | Packet |\n|------|-----------|--------|\n| **interface** | Distinctive, intentional UI direction and build judgment, visual identity, redesign, generic \"make it look good\", interface writing | `sk-design/design-interface/` |\n| **foundations** | Static visual-system decisions: color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, responsive adaptation, themes, design tokens | `sk-design/design-foundations/` |\n| **motion** | Temporal interaction design: animation, transitions, micro-interactions, motion materials, `AnimatePresence`, reduced motion | `sk-design/design-motion/` |\n| **audit** | Design QA and critique: accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, anti-slop detection, scoring, production hardening | `sk-design/design-audit/` |\n| **md-generator** | Extract a live website's real CSS into a v3 Style Reference `DESIGN.md` via the embedded extract-write-validate pipeline | `sk-design/design-md-generator/` |\n\n### When NOT to Use\n- A single quick read/edit with no design judgment вҖ” use the relevant skill directly.\n- Pure implementation after design direction is settled вҖ” hand off to `sk-code`.\n- A design transport only (Figma, Open Design) вҖ” load the design judgment via this hub first, then use the transport. The transport is never the taste authority.\n- The shared reference base itself вҖ” it is the vocabulary the modes cite, not a user workflow.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SMART ROUTING\n\nRouting is **registry-driven**. `mode-registry.json` is the single source of truth; the hub reads it and does not re-derive the mapping. The advisor routes any design query to the single identity `sk-design`; the hub then picks the mode.\n\n### The discriminator\n- **`workflowMode`** вҖ” the public mode key (every mode): `interface`, `foundations`, `motion`, `audit`, `md-generator`.\n- **`backendKind`** вҖ” which backend runs the mode: `reference-base` (the four doc-guidance modes cite the shared design reference base) or `playwright-extract` (`md-generator` runs its embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline).\n\n### Routing rule\n```\nclassify the request to a workflowMode (dominant design intent; mode hint like \"motion: ...\" overrides)\nread mode-registry.json\n  вҶ’ resolve workflowMode from the hint / classified intent\n  вҶ’ load the mode packet at registry[mode].packet (e.g. sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md)\n  вҶ’ the mode cites the shared reference base, or runs its own backend per registry[mode].backendKind\n```\n\nIntent classification favors the smallest useful mode. Default a generic \"make this look good\" prompt to **interface** unless the prompt is explicitly foundations (tokens/color/type/layout), motion (animation/transition), audit (critique/accessibility/slop), or md-generator (`DESIGN.md`/style-reference extraction). Pair modes only when the prompt has clearly separate design axes (e.g. interface + motion for a landing page with substantial choreography).\n\nPer-mode behavior is **not flattened**: each packet keeps its own design judgment, examples, standards, verification, and tool-permission needs. The four doc-guidance modes are read-and-guide; `md-generator` is the only mode that runs an extraction pipeline (Write/Edit/Bash over Playwright).\n\n---\n\n## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n\n### Layout\n```\nsk-design/\n  SKILL.md               # this routing hub (no per-mode design logic)\n  mode-registry.json     # the discriminator + advisorRouting (single source of truth)\n  graph-metadata.json    # the ONE advisor identity for the whole skill\n  references/            # shared design reference base the hub + modes cite\n  design-interface/  design-foundations/  design-motion/  design-audit/  design-md-generator/   # five mode packets\n```\n\nEach mode packet is self-contained (its own `SKILL.md`, `references/`, `assets/`, and `md-generator`'s extraction backend), with internal paths repointed and **no per-packet `graph-metadata.json`** вҖ” only this hub carries one, so the advisor discovers exactly one skill. The mode packet folders are created when the flat skills move under the hub; the hub references those packet paths now.\n\n### Backend\nThe four doc-guidance modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit) consume the shared **design reference base** under `references/` вҖ” `anti_slop_principles.md`, `cognitive_laws.md`, `design_token_vocabulary.md` вҖ” so anti-slop critique, design-token vocabulary, and cognitive-law rationale stay consistent across modes without duplication. The `md-generator` mode consumes its own embedded Playwright extraction backend instead. The reference base provides shared vocabulary; it must never gain per-mode workflow logic.\n\n---\n\n## 4. RULES\n\n### ALWAYS\n- **ALWAYS** resolve a mode through `mode-registry.json`; never hardcode a router mapping in the hub.\n- **ALWAYS** keep each mode's design judgment, examples, and verification in its packet вҖ” the hub stays logic-free.\n- **ALWAYS** keep exactly one `graph-metadata.json` (this hub's) so the advisor sees one skill identity.\n- **ALWAYS** give every mode an `advisorRouting` block with a valid `routingClass` and `packetSkillName`.\n- **ALWAYS** route a generic design prompt to the smallest useful mode; default to `interface` when no other axis dominates.\n\n### NEVER\n- **NEVER** add a `graph-metadata.json` or a discoverable skill marker inside a mode packet or the shared reference base.\n- **NEVER** embed per-mode design instructions in this hub вҖ” that content lives in the packets.\n- **NEVER** treat `mcp-figma` or `mcp-open-design` as taste or critique authority; they are transports loaded after the design mode is chosen.\n- **NEVER** route pure code, backend, or data work through the design family.\n\n### ESCALATE IF\n- A new design mode is needed вҖ” extend `mode-registry.json` and open a packet; do not bolt logic onto the hub.\n- A named mode conflicts with the request's actual intent, or the prompt spans more than three design axes needing an explicit workflow order.\n- Brand, accessibility, or production constraints make the requested visual direction unsafe or contradictory.\n\n---\n\n## 5. REFERENCES\n\n- Shared reference base: `references/anti_slop_principles.md`, `references/cognitive_laws.md`, `references/design_token_vocabulary.md` (cited by every doc-guidance mode).\n- Mode packets: `design-interface/SKILL.md`, `design-foundations/SKILL.md`, `design-motion/SKILL.md`, `design-audit/SKILL.md`, `design-md-generator/SKILL.md` (per-mode detail).\n- Registry: `mode-registry.json` (the routing contract).\n- Implementation handoff: `sk-code` consumes the design output; `sk-code-review` can audit it after build.\n\n---\n\n## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n\n- The hub resolves one primary mode for the request (or a small set only for clearly separate axes).\n- The selected mode packet owns the detailed design workflow; the hub stayed routing-only.\n- The shared reference base is used only for common vocabulary and cross-mode consistency.\n- Exactly one `graph-metadata.json` exists for the whole skill; no packet carries its own.\n\n---\n\n## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n\n### Modes\n- `interface` вҖ” direction, distinctive UI build judgment, interface writing.\n- `foundations` вҖ” color, typography, layout, responsive systems, tokens.\n- `motion` вҖ” animation, transitions, micro-interactions, temporal feel.\n- `audit` вҖ” accessibility, performance, critique, hardening, production readiness.\n- `md-generator` вҖ” `DESIGN.md` / style-reference extraction other skills consume.\n\n### Transports and Consumers\n- `mcp-figma` and `mcp-open-design` are transports. Use them after the design mode is chosen.\n- `sk-code` consumes design output and implements it in the detected code surface.\n- `sk-code-review` can audit implementation quality after design and build work converge.\n\n---\n\n## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- Pattern: `.opencode/skills/sk-doc/references/skill_creation/parent_skills_nested_packets.md` (parent-skill hub + nested packets, the one-graph-metadata invariant).\n- Canonical example: `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/` (hub + `mode-registry.json` + mode packets).\n- Registry: `mode-registry.json` (this hub's routing contract).","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":141,"totalLines":141,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782532211415,"end":1782532211419}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e76213ab5cc5f56016a3f48734be48191934f5b2b36b2f525"}},"id":"prt_f073302d5001yyaj22huEtV0j0","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","messageID":"msg_f073297d6001A3dxut5pYElRvw"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532211440,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_J4Zniq1tuXeQwF7A56kBR9s2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md","offset":1,"limit":320},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: design-md-generator\n3: description: \"Extracts a live website's real CSS into a v3 Style Reference DESIGN.md via an embedded extract-write-validate pipeline.\"\n4: allowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]\n5: version: 1.0.0.2\n6: ---\n7: \n8: <!-- Keywords: design system, design tokens, css extraction, design.md, website design extraction, design reference, tokens.json, playwright, design-to-markdown, design-system generator, css tokens, color extraction, typography extraction, hex extraction, shadow extraction, spacing extraction, design fidelity, anti-hallucination -->\n9: \n10: # Design System Extractor (md-generator)\n11: \n12: Captures a live website's **real, measured CSS** into a publication-quality `DESIGN.md` вҖ” a v3 **Style Reference**: a named, role-driven, ship-ready design-system handoff (named colour tokens, semantic type scale, named components, Surfaces, Elevation, Agent Prompt Guide, Similar Brands, and copy-paste Quick Start CSS + Tailwind) that AI agents build against without hallucinating colors, fonts, spacing, or shadows. Runs a three-phase pipeline (extract, write, validate) through an embedded Playwright crawler that samples five viewports and emits verbatim `tokens.json`. Deep operational detail lives in [`references/`](references/).\n13: \n14: > **Family boundary.** This skill is the **extraction and format-fidelity engine** of the `sk-design-*` family. It captures what already exists. Sibling `interface` invents **new** distinctive direction (palette, type, anti-default critique). The transports вҖ” `mcp-open-design` and `mcp-figma` вҖ” move design data; this skill produces the authoritative reference those transports and `interface` consume.\n15: \n16: ---\n17: \n18: ## 1. WHEN TO USE\n19: \n20: ### Activation Triggers\n21: \n22: **Use when** the user wants to:\n23: - Extract a live website's real CSS into a machine-readable `DESIGN.md` v3 Style Reference, with every hex, pixel, font-weight, radius, and shadow copied verbatim from the running page.\n24: - Produce a hallucination-proof design document for an AI agent to code against вҖ” `DESIGN.md` replaces guesses with measured ground truth.\n25: - Capture colors (including dark-mode palette if detected), typography stacks, shadows, border-radii, spacing scales, CSS custom properties, framework markers, icon-system hints, motion tokens, and a11y data across five responsive viewports.\n26: - Validate a generated `DESIGN.md` against its source `tokens.json` to confirm hex accuracy and section completeness.\n27: - Generate visual validation reports (HTML preview, diff report) from a `DESIGN.md` + `tokens.json` pair.\n28: - Re-extract a site after a redesign to update the design-system reference.\n29: \n30: **Keyword Triggers**: \"extract design system\", \"generate DESIGN.md\", \"capture website css\", \"design tokens from url\", \"create design reference\", \"anti-hallucination design doc\", \"design-to-markdown\", \"extract design tokens\".\n31: \n32: ### Use Cases\n33: \n34: **Full extraction вҖ” URL to DESIGN.md.** The canonical workflow: crawl a live URL, produce `tokens.json`, write `DESIGN.md` output conforming to the v3 Style Reference format, then validate hex accuracy, section completeness, and Quick-Start fidelity. This is the primary path.\n35: \n36: **Validation-only.** The user already has a `DESIGN.md` + `tokens.json` pair (from a prior extraction or hand-edited) and wants to confirm fidelity. Run the validator without re-extracting.\n37: \n38: **Visual report generation.** Given a `DESIGN.md` + `tokens.json` pair, render an HTML preview and a visual-diff report to confirm the written doc matches the extracted tokens.\n39: \n40: **Example study.** The user wants to understand how a gold-standard site (stripe, vercel, linear, supabase вҖ” included in `references/examples/`) structures its DESIGN.md output, to inform a new extraction or to learn the format conventions.\n41: \n42: ### When NOT to Use\n43: \n44: **Skip this skill when:**\n45: - The task is **inventing a new design direction** (palette, type scale, the anti-default critique). That is `interface`. This skill captures; that skill creates.\n46: - The task is **authoring a Style Reference from a brief alone** with no live site to measure. That is forward-authoring, and it is OUT OF SCOPE for this mode. This mode reports what is measurably there. A brief-only request is a different contract routed to a separate design-spec decision, never satisfied by loosening fidelity here. The line between measured values and a brief's stated intent is drawn in `references/authoring_boundary.md`.\n47: - The target is a **Figma file**, not a live website. Use `mcp-figma` to extract from Figma Desktop.\n48: - The target is an **Open Design project**. Use `mcp-open-design`.\n49: - The user only wants a **screenshot or visual preview** of a page. Use `mcp-chrome-devtools`.\n50: - The website cannot be reached (requires a live, renderable URL with JavaScript execution).\n51: \n52: ---\n53: \n54: ## 2. SMART ROUTING\n55: \n56: ### Primary Detection Signal\n57: \n58: Detect the **pipeline phase** first. The three phases are sequential and each has a distinct surface: EXTRACT hits the live URL, WRITE produces the markdown, VALIDATE checks fidelity. A fourth path вҖ” REPORT вҖ” renders visual artifacts from an existing pair.\n59: \n60: ```bash\n61: # Phase detection (pseudo)\n62: echo \"$REQUEST\" | grep -qiE 'validate|check.*accuracy|verify.*design|hex.*check|section.*completeness' && PHASE=\"VALIDATE\"\n63: echo \"$REQUEST\" | grep -qiE 'report|preview|visual.*report|html.*report|diff.*report' && PHASE=\"REPORT\"\n64: echo \"$REQUEST\" | grep -qiE 'example|gold.*standard|stripe|vercel|linear|supabase|reference.*format' && PHASE=\"STUDY\"\n65: # default for extract/write/url/crawl:\n66: : \"${PHASE:=EXTRACT_WRITE}\"\n67: \n68: # Tool readiness check\n69: [ -d \"backend/node_modules\" ] && TOOL_READY=true || TOOL_READY=false\n70: ```\n71: \n72: ### Phase Detection\n73: \n74: ```text\n75: TASK CONTEXT\n76:     |\n77:     +- STEP 0: Detect pipeline phase -> EXTRACT_WRITE | VALIDATE | REPORT | STUDY\n78:     +- STEP 1: Verify tool readiness (backend/node_modules + playwright chromium installed)\n79:     +- Phase 1: EXTRACT вҖ” crawl URL across 5 viewports, emit tokens.json\n80:     +- Phase 2: WRITE вҖ” run build-write-prompt.ts (pre-renders TokensвҖ”Colors/Spacing&Shapes/Surfaces/Quick Start + a facts block), paste those tables unchanged, then write prose only for the v3 Style Reference\n81:     +- Phase 3: VALIDATE вҖ” check hex accuracy + v3 section completeness + Quick-Start fidelity via validate.ts\n82:     +- Phase 4 (optional): REPORT вҖ” render visual HTML preview + diff report\n83: ```\n84: \n85: ### Resource Domains\n86: \n87: The router discovers knowledge from this skill's `references/` and `assets/` directories: nine reference docs covering the v3 format spec and writing-style guide, the colour and component taxonomies, anti-patterns, the authoring boundary, the quality checklist, and the operational extraction-workflow and troubleshooting guides, plus three assets (the WRITE-phase prompt template, the cardinal-rules card, and the source-of-truth router card). The gold-standard pairs under `references/examples/` are reachable only under STUDY intent вҖ” study artifacts the writer reads to learn format conventions, never copied into an extraction.\n88: \n89: ```text\n90: references/design_md_format.md       # v3 Style Reference section specification (DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n91: references/writing_style_guide.md    # voice, tone, section composition rules\n92: references/color_role_taxonomy.md    # color role naming + classification\n93: references/component_taxonomy.md     # component naming + hierarchy patterns\n94: references/anti_patterns.md          # common DESIGN.md mistakes to avoid\n95: references/authoring_boundary.md     # measured / brief-provided / inferred / absent line\n96: references/quality_checklist.md      # pre-validate self-check\n97: references/extraction_workflow.md    # three-phase workflow, invocations, handoff\n98: references/troubleshooting.md        # failure modes and fixes\n99: references/examples/{stripe,vercel,linear,supabase}/  # gold-standard DESIGN.md + writing-notes pairs (STUDY intent)\n100: assets/design_md_prompt_template.md  # copy-paste WRITE-phase prompt\n101: assets/cardinal_rules_card.md        # one-page pre-write / pre-validate fidelity gate\n102: assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md  # fill-in provenance card\n103: ```\n104: \n105: ### Resource Loading Levels\n106: \n107: | Level       | When to Load                         | Resources                                                                 |\n108: | ----------- | ------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n109: | ALWAYS      | Every invocation                     | `references/design_md_format.md`, `references/writing_style_guide.md`, `assets/cardinal_rules_card.md` (pre-write fabrication gate) |\n110: | CONDITIONAL | EXTRACT_WRITE intent                 | `references/color_role_taxonomy.md`, `references/component_taxonomy.md`, `references/anti_patterns.md` |\n111: | CONDITIONAL | A value's origin is unclear (brief vs measured), or a brief-only request with no live site | `references/authoring_boundary.md` (the measured / brief-provided / inferred / absent line, where forward-authoring is out of scope) and `assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md` (the fill-in provenance card) |\n112: | CONDITIONAL | VALIDATE / completion claim          | `references/quality_checklist.md`, `references/anti_patterns.md`  |\n113: | CONDITIONAL | STUDY intent                         | `references/examples/` (one site at a time, loaded as reference pairs)           |\n114: | ON_DEMAND   | Deep format edge-cases or component patterns | `references/anti_patterns.md`, `references/component_taxonomy.md` |\n115: \n116: ### Smart Router Pseudocode\n117: \n118: > Resilience pattern: see [sk-doc smart-router template](../sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_smart_router.md). Guard paths, discover at runtime, score intents, fall back to the full extract-write-validate pipeline when unsure.\n119: \n120: ```python\n121: from pathlib import Path\n122: \n123: SKILL_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent\n124: RESOURCE_BASES = (SKILL_ROOT / \"references\", SKILL_ROOT / \"assets\")\n125: DEFAULT_RESOURCE = \"references/design_md_format.md\"\n126: \n127: INTENT_SIGNALS = {\n128:     \"EXTRACT_WRITE\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"extract\", \"crawl\", \"url\", \"design.md\", \"generate\",\n129:                                                  \"capture\", \"tokens.json\", \"design system\", \"live\"]},\n130:     \"VALIDATE\":      {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"validate\", \"check\", \"verify\", \"accuracy\", \"hex\",\n131:                                                  \"section completeness\", \"fidelity\"]},\n132:     \"REPORT\":        {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"report\", \"preview\", \"visual\", \"html\", \"diff\", \"render\"]},\n133:     \"STUDY\":         {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"example\", \"stripe\", \"vercel\", \"linear\", \"supabase\",\n134:                                                  \"gold standard\", \"reference\"]},\n135: }\n136: \n137: # Every reference and asset on disk is reachable from a RESOURCE_MAP entry (or the\n138: # always-loaded DEFAULT_RESOURCE); no orphans. The examples/ pairs are reachable\n139: # only under STUDY intent вҖ” they are study artifacts the writer reads, never copied.\n140: RESOURCE_MAP = {\n141:     \"EXTRACT_WRITE\": [\"references/design_md_format.md\", \"references/writing_style_guide.md\",\n142:                        \"references/color_role_taxonomy.md\", \"references/component_taxonomy.md\",\n143:                        \"references/anti_patterns.md\", \"references/authoring_boundary.md\",\n144:                        \"references/extraction_workflow.md\", \"references/troubleshooting.md\",\n145:                        \"assets/design_md_prompt_template.md\", \"assets/cardinal_rules_card.md\",\n146:                        \"assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md\"],\n147:     \"VALIDATE\":      [\"references/quality_checklist.md\", \"references/anti_patterns.md\",\n148:                        \"references/design_md_format.md\", \"assets/cardinal_rules_card.md\"],\n149:     \"REPORT\":        [\"references/design_md_format.md\"],\n150:     \"STUDY\":         [\"references/design_md_format.md\", \"references/writing_style_guide.md\",\n151:                        \"references/examples/stripe/DESIGN.md\", \"references/examples/stripe/writing-notes.md\",\n152:                        \"references/examples/vercel/DESIGN.md\", \"references/examples/vercel/writing-notes.md\",\n153:                        \"references/examples/linear/DESIGN.md\", \"references/examples/linear/writing-notes.md\",\n154:                        \"references/examples/supabase/DESIGN.md\", \"references/examples/supabase/writing-notes.md\"],\n155: }\n156: \n157: UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST = [\n158:     \"Confirm the pipeline phase: full extraction (URL вҶ’ DESIGN.md), validation-only, report generation, or example study\",\n159:     \"For any extraction, confirm the target URL is live and renders JavaScript\",\n160:     \"Confirm the output paths for tokens.json and DESIGN.md before writing\",\n161:     \"Verify tool readiness: cd backend && npm install && npx playwright install chromium\",\n162: ]\n163: \n164: AMBIGUITY_DELTA = 1\n165: \n166: def _guard_in_skill(relative_path: str) -> str:\n167:     resolved = (SKILL_ROOT / relative_path).resolve()\n168:     resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT)\n169:     if resolved.suffix.lower() != \".md\":\n170:         raise ValueError(f\"Only markdown resources are routable: {relative_path}\")\n171:     return resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix()\n172: \n173: def discover_markdown_resources() -> set[str]:\n174:     docs = []\n175:     for base in RESOURCE_BASES:\n176:         if base.exists():\n177:             docs.extend(p for p in base.rglob(\"*.md\") if p.is_file())\n178:     return {d.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix() for d in docs}\n179: \n180: def classify_intents(request: str):\n181:     text = (request or \"\").lower()\n182:     scores = {i: 0 for i in INTENT_SIGNALS}\n183:     for intent, cfg in INTENT_SIGNALS.items():\n184:         for kw in cfg[\"keywords\"]:\n185:             if kw in text:\n186:                 scores[intent] += cfg[\"weight\"]\n187:     ranked = sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda kv: kv[1], reverse=True)\n188:     primary, top = ranked[0]\n189:     if top == 0:\n190:         return (\"EXTRACT_WRITE\", None, scores)\n191:     secondary, second = ranked[1]\n192:     if second > 0 and (top - second) <= AMBIGUITY_DELTA:\n193:         return (primary, secondary, scores)\n194:     return (primary, None, scores)\n195: \n196: def route_design_md_resources(request: str):\n197:     inventory = discover_markdown_resources()\n198:     primary, secondary, scores = classify_intents(request)\n199:     intents = [primary] + ([secondary] if secondary else [])\n200:     loaded, seen = [], set()\n201: \n202:     def load_if_available(rel: str):\n203:         guarded = _guard_in_skill(rel)\n204:         if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n205:             load(guarded); loaded.append(guarded); seen.add(guarded)\n206: \n207:     load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n208:     if max(scores.values() or [0]) < 1:\n209:         return {\"intents\": intents, \"needs_disambiguation\": True,\n210:                 \"disambiguation_checklist\": UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST, \"resources\": loaded}\n211:     for intent in intents:\n212:         for rel in RESOURCE_MAP.get(intent, []):\n213:             load_if_available(rel)\n214:     return {\"intents\": intents, \"intent_scores\": scores, \"resources\": loaded}\n215: ```\n216: \n217: ---\n218: \n219: ## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n220: \n221: ### The Three-Phase Pipeline\n222: \n223: Every extraction runs as a sequential pipeline. No phase can be skipped in a full run, though VALIDATE and REPORT can be invoked standalone on an existing `DESIGN.md` + `tokens.json` pair.\n224: \n225: **Process Flow:**\n226: ```\n227: EXTRACT (Phase 1)\n228:     в”ңв”Җ Playwright crawls the target URL across 5 viewports (mobile through wide desktop)\n229:     в”ңв”Җ Collects computed CSS: colors, typography, shadows, radii, spacing, CSS variables\n230:     в”ңв”Җ Detects dark-mode palette, framework markers, icon system, motion tokens, a11y data\n231:     в”ңв”Җ Each token tagged with a 4-layer stability class (L1 permanent вҶ’ L4 content)\n232:     в””в”Җ Output: tokens.json (verbatim measured values)\n233:          вҶ“\n234: WRITE (Phase 2)\n235:     в”ңв”Җ Run build-write-prompt.ts FIRST: it pre-renders Tokens вҖ” Colors, Tokens вҖ” Spacing &\n236:     в”Ӯ    Shapes, Surfaces, and Quick Start deterministically from tokens (doc-as-view, no AI on\n237:     в”Ӯ    the value tables) via formatters-v3.ts, plus a FACTS block of locked values\n238:     в”ңв”Җ Read tokens.json and references/design_md_format.md for the v3 Style Reference spec\n239:     в”ңв”Җ Paste the pre-rendered value sections UNCHANGED; write prose only (intro, Typography role\n240:     в”Ӯ    prose, Components, Do's/Don'ts, Elevation, Imagery, Layout, Agent Prompt Guide, Similar Brands)\n241:     в”ңв”Җ Every value comes from a pre-rendered section or the FACTS block вҖ” never invented or concretized\n242:     в”ңв”Җ Voice is NAMED, CONFIDENT, RESTRAINED; assign evocative colour names and roles, infer Similar\n243:     в”Ӯ    Brands, but never assert a system the data contradicts (no gradient-as-depth, no false focus)\n244:     в”ңв”Җ Elevation renders FLAT when 0 shadow tokens (states how depth is achieved instead)\n245:     в”ңв”Җ L1 (permanent) + L2 (system) colours in the main token table\n246:     в”ңв”Җ L3 (campaign) colours in a \"Current Campaign Colors (Subject to change)\" sub-table\n247:     в”ңв”Җ L4 (content) tokens excluded entirely\n248:     в””в”Җ Output: DESIGN.md (v3 Style Reference) at the user-specified path\n249:          вҶ“\n250: VALIDATE (Phase 3)\n251:     в”ңв”Җ Run validate.ts: check every hex code in DESIGN.md exists in tokens.json\n252:     в”ңв”Җ Check the required v3 Style Reference sections are present\n253:     в”ңв”Җ Check Quick-Start fidelity: every Quick Start hex traces to tokens, --page-max-width matches\n254:     в”ңв”Җ Check format consistency (hex casing, phantom colors) and prose provenance (claimsScore вүҘ 80)\n255:     в””в”Җ Output: validation pass/fail with a dual score and per-finding messages\n256:          вҶ“\n257: REPORT (Phase 4, optional)\n258:     в”ңв”Җ report-gen.ts: render an HTML report of token-to-section mapping\n259:     в”ңв”Җ preview-gen.ts: render a visual preview of the design system\n260:     в””в”Җ Output: visual artifacts for human review\n261: ```\n262: \n263: ### Cardinal Fidelity Rule\n264: \n265: **Every hex code, pixel value, font weight, box shadow, border radius, and spacing value in `DESIGN.md` MUST be copied verbatim from `tokens.json`.** No estimation, no rounding, no invention, no \"close enough\" substitution. This is the single non-negotiable contract of the skill вҖ” it is what makes `DESIGN.md` a hallucination-proof reference.\n266: \n267: - **Hex codes** must use **6-digit lowercase** format (e.g., `#1a1a2e`, never `#1A1A2E` or `#1a1a2`).\n268: - **Stability gates**: only L1 (permanent/brand-level) and L2 (system/component-level) tokens belong in the main DESIGN.md sections. L3 (campaign-level, e.g., a seasonal accent color) may appear with an explicit \"Subject to change\" annotation. L4 (content-level, e.g., a hero image's dominant color) is excluded.\n269: - **Dark mode**: include a dark-mode section ONLY when the extractor detected a dark-mode palette. Do not fabricate a dark palette from the light one.\n270: - **What `validate.ts` traces**: validation hard-checks hex codes (against `tokens.colorTokens`) and the Quick Start values (every Quick Start hex traces to a token; `--page-max-width` matches `tokens.spacingSystem.maxContentWidth`). Non-hex values (pixel sizes, font weights, shadows, radii) are NOT re-traced by the validator вҖ” their fidelity is guaranteed upstream because the WRITE phase pre-renders the value tables from `formatters-v3.ts` and supplies the typography/component numbers verbatim in the FACTS block, so the AI never types them. Treat the cardinal rule as the binding contract for those values even though validation does not re-check each one.\n271: \n272: ### Authoring Boundary\n273: \n274: The cardinal rule stays enforceable by inspection because every value has a legible origin. A value is **measured** (read off the page and present in `tokens.json`), **brief-provided** (supplied by the user, not the page), **inferred** (a grounded characterization of a measured value) or **absent** (never captured). Only measured values enter the token tables, and they enter unlabeled, so an unlabeled value is a promise it was measured. Brief-provided values stay in prose as a stated intent and never sit in a value table. Inferred claims carry `[INFERRED]` and cite the measured token they rest on. Absent values are stamped or omitted rather than backfilled. This boundary adds no capability and relaxes the fidelity contract by not one digit. When a value's origin is unclear, or a request asks to author from a brief with no live site, load `references/authoring_boundary.md` for the full line and `assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md` to sort each value before writing. Authoring from a brief alone is forward-authoring and stays out of scope (Section 1, When NOT to Use).\n275: \n276: ### Invocation\n277: \n278: > **Working directory.** Run the one-time setup from `backend/` (npm needs the package\n279: > manifest there). Run every `extract.ts` invocation from the **repo root** with the full\n280: > script path: `extract.ts` refuses any `--output` that resolves inside the skill, so a\n281: > relative `--output .opencode/specs/...` only resolves correctly from the repo root.\n282: \n283: ```bash\n284: # One-time setup (from the skill's backend/ directory)\n285: cd .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend && npm install && npx playwright install chromium\n286: \n287: # Phase 1 вҖ” extract (run from the repo root). --fast crawls 5 pages at 8 concurrency\n288: # (default is 8 pages). Interaction capture (hover/focus/active) runs by DEFAULT, including\n289: # under --fast. tokens.json is written to <--output>/. The relative --output resolves under\n290: # the repo root (outside the skill), which is what the output guard requires.\n291: npx ts-node .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/extract.ts <url> --fast --output .opencode/specs/<track>/<packet>/output\n292: \n293: # Phase 2 вҖ” write DESIGN.md per references/design_md_format.md, every value from tokens.json.\n294: # Run build-write-prompt.ts first: it pre-renders TokensвҖ”Colors/Spacing&Shapes/Surfaces/Quick Start\n295: # (via formatters-v3.ts) plus a FACTS block, then you paste those unchanged and write prose only:\n296: npx ts-node .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/build-write-prompt.ts .opencode/specs/<track>/<packet>/output/tokens.json\n297: \n298: # Phase 3 вҖ” validate (DESIGN.md first, tokens.json second):\n299: npx ts-node .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/validate.ts <DESIGN.md> .opencode/specs/<track>/<packet>/output/tokens.json\n300: \n301: # Optional вҖ” fidelity proof + visual report/preview (these take tokens.json FIRST):\n302: npx ts-node .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/proof.ts <url> .opencode/specs/<track>/<packet>/output/tokens.json\n303: npx ts-node .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/report-gen.ts .opencode/specs/<track>/<packet>/output/tokens.json <dir> <DESIGN.md>\n304: npx ts-node .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/preview-gen.ts .opencode/specs/<track>/<packet>/output/tokens.json <dir>\n305: ```\n306: \n307: Real extract flags (see `backend/README.md`): `--fast` (5 pages, 8 concurrency вҖ” still captures interaction), `--max-pages <n>` (default 8), `--concurrency <n>` (default 5), `--with-interaction` (the default вҖ” capture hover/focus/active states), `--no-interaction` (opt OUT of interaction capture), `--fast-no-interaction` (fast crawl AND skip interaction вҖ” the old `--fast` behavior), `--no-dark-mode` (skip dark detection), `--wait-for <strategy>`, `--extra-urls`, `--merge-with`, `--output <dir>` (REQUIRED вҖ” a spec folder outside the skill), `--insecure` (ignore HTTPS certificate errors for self-signed / staging hosts), `--verbose`. Interaction capture is **default-on**; opt out only with `--no-interaction` or `--fast-no-interaction`.\n308: \n309: ### Token Stability Classes (L1вҖ“L4)\n310: \n311: Each extracted token receives a stability classification that governs whether it appears in `DESIGN.md`:\n312: \n313: | Class | Name (emitted `layer`)     | Description                                              | DESIGN.md treatment                      |\n314: | ----- | -------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |\n315: | L1    | Permanent (`infrastructure`) | Brand identity вҖ” logo colors, brand typeface, core radii | Included in main sections                |\n316: | L2    | System (`system`)          | Design-system tokens вҖ” semantic colors, spacing scale    | Included in main sections                |\n317: | L3    | Campaign (`campaign`)      | Temporary вҖ” hero gradients, seasonal accents             | Included with \"Subject to change\" annotation |\n318: | L4    | Content (`content`)        | Image-derived, one-off, article-specific                 | Excluded entirely                        |\n319: \n320: The classifier lives in `backend/scripts/cluster.ts` and is deterministic. Tokens that sit at a boundary are assigned the higher (more restrictive) class. In `tokens.json` each token's `stability.layer` carries the emitted string (`infrastructure` for L1, then `system`, `campaign`, `content`) вҖ” \"Permanent\" is the human-facing label for the `infrastructure` layer.\n\n(Showing lines 1-320 of 462. Use offset=321 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: design-md-generator\ndescription: \"Extracts a live website's real CSS into a v3 Style Reference DESIGN.md via an embedded extract-write-validate pipeline.\"\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]\nversion: 1.0.0.2\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: design system, design tokens, css extraction, design.md, website design extraction, design reference, tokens.json, playwright, design-to-markdown, design-system generator, css tokens, color extraction, typography extraction, hex extraction, shadow extraction, spacing extraction, design fidelity, anti-hallucination -->\n\n# Design System Extractor (md-generator)\n\nCaptures a live website's **real, measured CSS** into a publication-quality `DESIGN.md` вҖ” a v3 **Style Reference**: a named, role-driven, ship-ready design-system handoff (named colour tokens, semantic type scale, named components, Surfaces, Elevation, Agent Prompt Guide, Similar Brands, and copy-paste Quick Start CSS + Tailwind) that AI agents build against without hallucinating colors, fonts, spacing, or shadows. Runs a three-phase pipeline (extract, write, validate) through an embedded Playwright crawler that samples five viewports and emits verbatim `tokens.json`. Deep operational detail lives in [`references/`](references/).\n\n> **Family boundary.** This skill is the **extraction and format-fidelity engine** of the `sk-design-*` family. It captures what already exists. Sibling `interface` invents **new** distinctive direction (palette, type, anti-default critique). The transports вҖ” `mcp-open-design` and `mcp-figma` вҖ” move design data; this skill produces the authoritative reference those transports and `interface` consume.\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n\n### Activation Triggers","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: design-md-generator\ndescription: \"Extracts a live website's real CSS into a v3 Style Reference DESIGN.md via an embedded extract-write-validate pipeline.\"\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]\nversion: 1.0.0.2\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: design system, design tokens, css extraction, design.md, website design extraction, design reference, tokens.json, playwright, design-to-markdown, design-system generator, css tokens, color extraction, typography extraction, hex extraction, shadow extraction, spacing extraction, design fidelity, anti-hallucination -->\n\n# Design System Extractor (md-generator)\n\nCaptures a live website's **real, measured CSS** into a publication-quality `DESIGN.md` вҖ” a v3 **Style Reference**: a named, role-driven, ship-ready design-system handoff (named colour tokens, semantic type scale, named components, Surfaces, Elevation, Agent Prompt Guide, Similar Brands, and copy-paste Quick Start CSS + Tailwind) that AI agents build against without hallucinating colors, fonts, spacing, or shadows. Runs a three-phase pipeline (extract, write, validate) through an embedded Playwright crawler that samples five viewports and emits verbatim `tokens.json`. Deep operational detail lives in [`references/`](references/).\n\n> **Family boundary.** This skill is the **extraction and format-fidelity engine** of the `sk-design-*` family. It captures what already exists. Sibling `interface` invents **new** distinctive direction (palette, type, anti-default critique). The transports вҖ” `mcp-open-design` and `mcp-figma` вҖ” move design data; this skill produces the authoritative reference those transports and `interface` consume.\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n\n### Activation Triggers\n\n**Use when** the user wants to:\n- Extract a live website's real CSS into a machine-readable `DESIGN.md` v3 Style Reference, with every hex, pixel, font-weight, radius, and shadow copied verbatim from the running page.\n- Produce a hallucination-proof design document for an AI agent to code against вҖ” `DESIGN.md` replaces guesses with measured ground truth.\n- Capture colors (including dark-mode palette if detected), typography stacks, shadows, border-radii, spacing scales, CSS custom properties, framework markers, icon-system hints, motion tokens, and a11y data across five responsive viewports.\n- Validate a generated `DESIGN.md` against its source `tokens.json` to confirm hex accuracy and section completeness.\n- Generate visual validation reports (HTML preview, diff report) from a `DESIGN.md` + `tokens.json` pair.\n- Re-extract a site after a redesign to update the design-system reference.\n\n**Keyword Triggers**: \"extract design system\", \"generate DESIGN.md\", \"capture website css\", \"design tokens from url\", \"create design reference\", \"anti-hallucination design doc\", \"design-to-markdown\", \"extract design tokens\".\n\n### Use Cases\n\n**Full extraction вҖ” URL to DESIGN.md.** The canonical workflow: crawl a live URL, produce `tokens.json`, write `DESIGN.md` output conforming to the v3 Style Reference format, then validate hex accuracy, section completeness, and Quick-Start fidelity. This is the primary path.\n\n**Validation-only.** The user already has a `DESIGN.md` + `tokens.json` pair (from a prior extraction or hand-edited) and wants to confirm fidelity. Run the validator without re-extracting.\n\n**Visual report generation.** Given a `DESIGN.md` + `tokens.json` pair, render an HTML preview and a visual-diff report to confirm the written doc matches the extracted tokens.\n\n**Example study.** The user wants to understand how a gold-standard site (stripe, vercel, linear, supabase вҖ” included in `references/examples/`) structures its DESIGN.md output, to inform a new extraction or to learn the format conventions.\n\n### When NOT to Use\n\n**Skip this skill when:**\n- The task is **inventing a new design direction** (palette, type scale, the anti-default critique). That is `interface`. This skill captures; that skill creates.\n- The task is **authoring a Style Reference from a brief alone** with no live site to measure. That is forward-authoring, and it is OUT OF SCOPE for this mode. This mode reports what is measurably there. A brief-only request is a different contract routed to a separate design-spec decision, never satisfied by loosening fidelity here. The line between measured values and a brief's stated intent is drawn in `references/authoring_boundary.md`.\n- The target is a **Figma file**, not a live website. Use `mcp-figma` to extract from Figma Desktop.\n- The target is an **Open Design project**. Use `mcp-open-design`.\n- The user only wants a **screenshot or visual preview** of a page. Use `mcp-chrome-devtools`.\n- The website cannot be reached (requires a live, renderable URL with JavaScript execution).\n\n---\n\n## 2. SMART ROUTING\n\n### Primary Detection Signal\n\nDetect the **pipeline phase** first. The three phases are sequential and each has a distinct surface: EXTRACT hits the live URL, WRITE produces the markdown, VALIDATE checks fidelity. A fourth path вҖ” REPORT вҖ” renders visual artifacts from an existing pair.\n\n```bash\n# Phase detection (pseudo)\necho \"$REQUEST\" | grep -qiE 'validate|check.*accuracy|verify.*design|hex.*check|section.*completeness' && PHASE=\"VALIDATE\"\necho \"$REQUEST\" | grep -qiE 'report|preview|visual.*report|html.*report|diff.*report' && PHASE=\"REPORT\"\necho \"$REQUEST\" | grep -qiE 'example|gold.*standard|stripe|vercel|linear|supabase|reference.*format' && PHASE=\"STUDY\"\n# default for extract/write/url/crawl:\n: \"${PHASE:=EXTRACT_WRITE}\"\n\n# Tool readiness check\n[ -d \"backend/node_modules\" ] && TOOL_READY=true || TOOL_READY=false\n```\n\n### Phase Detection\n\n```text\nTASK CONTEXT\n    |\n    +- STEP 0: Detect pipeline phase -> EXTRACT_WRITE | VALIDATE | REPORT | STUDY\n    +- STEP 1: Verify tool readiness (backend/node_modules + playwright chromium installed)\n    +- Phase 1: EXTRACT вҖ” crawl URL across 5 viewports, emit tokens.json\n    +- Phase 2: WRITE вҖ” run build-write-prompt.ts (pre-renders TokensвҖ”Colors/Spacing&Shapes/Surfaces/Quick Start + a facts block), paste those tables unchanged, then write prose only for the v3 Style Reference\n    +- Phase 3: VALIDATE вҖ” check hex accuracy + v3 section completeness + Quick-Start fidelity via validate.ts\n    +- Phase 4 (optional): REPORT вҖ” render visual HTML preview + diff report\n```\n\n### Resource Domains\n\nThe router discovers knowledge from this skill's `references/` and `assets/` directories: nine reference docs covering the v3 format spec and writing-style guide, the colour and component taxonomies, anti-patterns, the authoring boundary, the quality checklist, and the operational extraction-workflow and troubleshooting guides, plus three assets (the WRITE-phase prompt template, the cardinal-rules card, and the source-of-truth router card). The gold-standard pairs under `references/examples/` are reachable only under STUDY intent вҖ” study artifacts the writer reads to learn format conventions, never copied into an extraction.\n\n```text\nreferences/design_md_format.md       # v3 Style Reference section specification (DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\nreferences/writing_style_guide.md    # voice, tone, section composition rules\nreferences/color_role_taxonomy.md    # color role naming + classification\nreferences/component_taxonomy.md     # component naming + hierarchy patterns\nreferences/anti_patterns.md          # common DESIGN.md mistakes to avoid\nreferences/authoring_boundary.md     # measured / brief-provided / inferred / absent line\nreferences/quality_checklist.md      # pre-validate self-check\nreferences/extraction_workflow.md    # three-phase workflow, invocations, handoff\nreferences/troubleshooting.md        # failure modes and fixes\nreferences/examples/{stripe,vercel,linear,supabase}/  # gold-standard DESIGN.md + writing-notes pairs (STUDY intent)\nassets/design_md_prompt_template.md  # copy-paste WRITE-phase prompt\nassets/cardinal_rules_card.md        # one-page pre-write / pre-validate fidelity gate\nassets/source_of_truth_router_card.md  # fill-in provenance card\n```\n\n### Resource Loading Levels\n\n| Level       | When to Load                         | Resources                                                                 |\n| ----------- | ------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| ALWAYS      | Every invocation                     | `references/design_md_format.md`, `references/writing_style_guide.md`, `assets/cardinal_rules_card.md` (pre-write fabrication gate) |\n| CONDITIONAL | EXTRACT_WRITE intent                 | `references/color_role_taxonomy.md`, `references/component_taxonomy.md`, `references/anti_patterns.md` |\n| CONDITIONAL | A value's origin is unclear (brief vs measured), or a brief-only request with no live site | `references/authoring_boundary.md` (the measured / brief-provided / inferred / absent line, where forward-authoring is out of scope) and `assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md` (the fill-in provenance card) |\n| CONDITIONAL | VALIDATE / completion claim          | `references/quality_checklist.md`, `references/anti_patterns.md`  |\n| CONDITIONAL | STUDY intent                         | `references/examples/` (one site at a time, loaded as reference pairs)           |\n| ON_DEMAND   | Deep format edge-cases or component patterns | `references/anti_patterns.md`, `references/component_taxonomy.md` |\n\n### Smart Router Pseudocode\n\n> Resilience pattern: see [sk-doc smart-router template](../sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_smart_router.md). Guard paths, discover at runtime, score intents, fall back to the full extract-write-validate pipeline when unsure.\n\n```python\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nSKILL_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent\nRESOURCE_BASES = (SKILL_ROOT / \"references\", SKILL_ROOT / \"assets\")\nDEFAULT_RESOURCE = \"references/design_md_format.md\"\n\nINTENT_SIGNALS = {\n    \"EXTRACT_WRITE\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"extract\", \"crawl\", \"url\", \"design.md\", \"generate\",\n                                                 \"capture\", \"tokens.json\", \"design system\", \"live\"]},\n    \"VALIDATE\":      {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"validate\", \"check\", \"verify\", \"accuracy\", \"hex\",\n                                                 \"section completeness\", \"fidelity\"]},\n    \"REPORT\":        {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"report\", \"preview\", \"visual\", \"html\", \"diff\", \"render\"]},\n    \"STUDY\":         {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"example\", \"stripe\", \"vercel\", \"linear\", \"supabase\",\n                                                 \"gold standard\", \"reference\"]},\n}\n\n# Every reference and asset on disk is reachable from a RESOURCE_MAP entry (or the\n# always-loaded DEFAULT_RESOURCE); no orphans. The examples/ pairs are reachable\n# only under STUDY intent вҖ” they are study artifacts the writer reads, never copied.\nRESOURCE_MAP = {\n    \"EXTRACT_WRITE\": [\"references/design_md_format.md\", \"references/writing_style_guide.md\",\n                       \"references/color_role_taxonomy.md\", \"references/component_taxonomy.md\",\n                       \"references/anti_patterns.md\", \"references/authoring_boundary.md\",\n                       \"references/extraction_workflow.md\", \"references/troubleshooting.md\",\n                       \"assets/design_md_prompt_template.md\", \"assets/cardinal_rules_card.md\",\n                       \"assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md\"],\n    \"VALIDATE\":      [\"references/quality_checklist.md\", \"references/anti_patterns.md\",\n                       \"references/design_md_format.md\", \"assets/cardinal_rules_card.md\"],\n    \"REPORT\":        [\"references/design_md_format.md\"],\n    \"STUDY\":         [\"references/design_md_format.md\", \"references/writing_style_guide.md\",\n                       \"references/examples/stripe/DESIGN.md\", \"references/examples/stripe/writing-notes.md\",\n                       \"references/examples/vercel/DESIGN.md\", \"references/examples/vercel/writing-notes.md\",\n                       \"references/examples/linear/DESIGN.md\", \"references/examples/linear/writing-notes.md\",\n                       \"references/examples/supabase/DESIGN.md\", \"references/examples/supabase/writing-notes.md\"],\n}\n\nUNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST = [\n    \"Confirm the pipeline phase: full extraction (URL вҶ’ DESIGN.md), validation-only, report generation, or example study\",\n    \"For any extraction, confirm the target URL is live and renders JavaScript\",\n    \"Confirm the output paths for tokens.json and DESIGN.md before writing\",\n    \"Verify tool readiness: cd backend && npm install && npx playwright install chromium\",\n]\n\nAMBIGUITY_DELTA = 1\n\ndef _guard_in_skill(relative_path: str) -> str:\n    resolved = (SKILL_ROOT / relative_path).resolve()\n    resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT)\n    if resolved.suffix.lower() != \".md\":\n        raise ValueError(f\"Only markdown resources are routable: {relative_path}\")\n    return resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix()\n\ndef discover_markdown_resources() -> set[str]:\n    docs = []\n    for base in RESOURCE_BASES:\n        if base.exists():\n            docs.extend(p for p in base.rglob(\"*.md\") if p.is_file())\n    return {d.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix() for d in docs}\n\ndef classify_intents(request: str):\n    text = (request or \"\").lower()\n    scores = {i: 0 for i in INTENT_SIGNALS}\n    for intent, cfg in INTENT_SIGNALS.items():\n        for kw in cfg[\"keywords\"]:\n            if kw in text:\n                scores[intent] += cfg[\"weight\"]\n    ranked = sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda kv: kv[1], reverse=True)\n    primary, top = ranked[0]\n    if top == 0:\n        return (\"EXTRACT_WRITE\", None, scores)\n    secondary, second = ranked[1]\n    if second > 0 and (top - second) <= AMBIGUITY_DELTA:\n        return (primary, secondary, scores)\n    return (primary, None, scores)\n\ndef route_design_md_resources(request: str):\n    inventory = discover_markdown_resources()\n    primary, secondary, scores = classify_intents(request)\n    intents = [primary] + ([secondary] if secondary else [])\n    loaded, seen = [], set()\n\n    def load_if_available(rel: str):\n        guarded = _guard_in_skill(rel)\n        if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n            load(guarded); loaded.append(guarded); seen.add(guarded)\n\n    load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n    if max(scores.values() or [0]) < 1:\n        return {\"intents\": intents, \"needs_disambiguation\": True,\n                \"disambiguation_checklist\": UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST, \"resources\": loaded}\n    for intent in intents:\n        for rel in RESOURCE_MAP.get(intent, []):\n            load_if_available(rel)\n    return {\"intents\": intents, \"intent_scores\": scores, \"resources\": loaded}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n\n### The Three-Phase Pipeline\n\nEvery extraction runs as a sequential pipeline. No phase can be skipped in a full run, though VALIDATE and REPORT can be invoked standalone on an existing `DESIGN.md` + `tokens.json` pair.\n\n**Process Flow:**\n```\nEXTRACT (Phase 1)\n    в”ңв”Җ Playwright crawls the target URL across 5 viewports (mobile through wide desktop)\n    в”ңв”Җ Collects computed CSS: colors, typography, shadows, radii, spacing, CSS variables\n    в”ңв”Җ Detects dark-mode palette, framework markers, icon system, motion tokens, a11y data\n    в”ңв”Җ Each token tagged with a 4-layer stability class (L1 permanent вҶ’ L4 content)\n    в””в”Җ Output: tokens.json (verbatim measured values)\n         вҶ“\nWRITE (Phase 2)\n    в”ңв”Җ Run build-write-prompt.ts FIRST: it pre-renders Tokens вҖ” Colors, Tokens вҖ” Spacing &\n    в”Ӯ    Shapes, Surfaces, and Quick Start deterministically from tokens (doc-as-view, no AI on\n    в”Ӯ    the value tables) via formatters-v3.ts, plus a FACTS block of locked values\n    в”ңв”Җ Read tokens.json and references/design_md_format.md for the v3 Style Reference spec\n    в”ңв”Җ Paste the pre-rendered value sections UNCHANGED; write prose only (intro, Typography role\n    в”Ӯ    prose, Components, Do's/Don'ts, Elevation, Imagery, Layout, Agent Prompt Guide, Similar Brands)\n    в”ңв”Җ Every value comes from a pre-rendered section or the FACTS block вҖ” never invented or concretized\n    в”ңв”Җ Voice is NAMED, CONFIDENT, RESTRAINED; assign evocative colour names and roles, infer Similar\n    в”Ӯ    Brands, but never assert a system the data contradicts (no gradient-as-depth, no false focus)\n    в”ңв”Җ Elevation renders FLAT when 0 shadow tokens (states how depth is achieved instead)\n    в”ңв”Җ L1 (permanent) + L2 (system) colours in the main token table\n    в”ңв”Җ L3 (campaign) colours in a \"Current Campaign Colors (Subject to change)\" sub-table\n    в”ңв”Җ L4 (content) tokens excluded entirely\n    в””в”Җ Output: DESIGN.md (v3 Style Reference) at the user-specified path\n         вҶ“\nVALIDATE (Phase 3)\n    в”ңв”Җ Run validate.ts: check every hex code in DESIGN.md exists in tokens.json\n    в”ңв”Җ Check the required v3 Style Reference sections are present\n    в”ңв”Җ Check Quick-Start fidelity: every Quick Start hex traces to tokens, --page-max-width matches\n    в”ңв”Җ Check format consistency (hex casing, phantom colors) and prose provenance (claimsScore вүҘ 80)\n    в””в”Җ Output: validation pass/fail with a dual score and per-finding messages\n         вҶ“\nREPORT (Phase 4, optional)\n    в”ңв”Җ report-gen.ts: render an HTML report of token-to-section mapping\n    в”ңв”Җ preview-gen.ts: render a visual preview of the design system\n    в””в”Җ Output: visual artifacts for human review\n```\n\n### Cardinal Fidelity Rule\n\n**Every hex code, pixel value, font weight, box shadow, border radius, and spacing value in `DESIGN.md` MUST be copied verbatim from `tokens.json`.** No estimation, no rounding, no invention, no \"close enough\" substitution. This is the single non-negotiable contract of the skill вҖ” it is what makes `DESIGN.md` a hallucination-proof reference.\n\n- **Hex codes** must use **6-digit lowercase** format (e.g., `#1a1a2e`, never `#1A1A2E` or `#1a1a2`).\n- **Stability gates**: only L1 (permanent/brand-level) and L2 (system/component-level) tokens belong in the main DESIGN.md sections. L3 (campaign-level, e.g., a seasonal accent color) may appear with an explicit \"Subject to change\" annotation. L4 (content-level, e.g., a hero image's dominant color) is excluded.\n- **Dark mode**: include a dark-mode section ONLY when the extractor detected a dark-mode palette. Do not fabricate a dark palette from the light one.\n- **What `validate.ts` traces**: validation hard-checks hex codes (against `tokens.colorTokens`) and the Quick Start values (every Quick Start hex traces to a token; `--page-max-width` matches `tokens.spacingSystem.maxContentWidth`). Non-hex values (pixel sizes, font weights, shadows, radii) are NOT re-traced by the validator вҖ” their fidelity is guaranteed upstream because the WRITE phase pre-renders the value tables from `formatters-v3.ts` and supplies the typography/component numbers verbatim in the FACTS block, so the AI never types them. Treat the cardinal rule as the binding contract for those values even though validation does not re-check each one.\n\n### Authoring Boundary\n\nThe cardinal rule stays enforceable by inspection because every value has a legible origin. A value is **measured** (read off the page and present in `tokens.json`), **brief-provided** (supplied by the user, not the page), **inferred** (a grounded characterization of a measured value) or **absent** (never captured). Only measured values enter the token tables, and they enter unlabeled, so an unlabeled value is a promise it was measured. Brief-provided values stay in prose as a stated intent and never sit in a value table. Inferred claims carry `[INFERRED]` and cite the measured token they rest on. Absent values are stamped or omitted rather than backfilled. This boundary adds no capability and relaxes the fidelity contract by not one digit. When a value's origin is unclear, or a request asks to author from a brief with no live site, load `references/authoring_boundary.md` for the full line and `assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md` to sort each value before writing. Authoring from a brief alone is forward-authoring and stays out of scope (Section 1, When NOT to Use).\n\n### Invocation\n\n> **Working directory.** Run the one-time setup from `backend/` (npm needs the package\n> manifest there). Run every `extract.ts` invocation from the **repo root** with the full\n> script path: `extract.ts` refuses any `--output` that resolves inside the skill, so a\n> relative `--output .opencode/specs/...` only resolves correctly from the repo root.\n\n```bash\n# One-time setup (from the skill's backend/ directory)\ncd .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend && npm install && npx playwright install chromium\n\n# Phase 1 вҖ” extract (run from the repo root). --fast crawls 5 pages at 8 concurrency\n# (default is 8 pages). Interaction capture (hover/focus/active) runs by DEFAULT, including\n# under --fast. tokens.json is written to <--output>/. The relative --output resolves under\n# the repo root (outside the skill), which is what the output guard requires.\nnpx ts-node .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/extract.ts <url> --fast --output .opencode/specs/<track>/<packet>/output\n\n# Phase 2 вҖ” write DESIGN.md per references/design_md_format.md, every value from tokens.json.\n# Run build-write-prompt.ts first: it pre-renders TokensвҖ”Colors/Spacing&Shapes/Surfaces/Quick Start\n# (via formatters-v3.ts) plus a FACTS block, then you paste those unchanged and write prose only:\nnpx ts-node .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/build-write-prompt.ts .opencode/specs/<track>/<packet>/output/tokens.json\n\n# Phase 3 вҖ” validate (DESIGN.md first, tokens.json second):\nnpx ts-node .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/validate.ts <DESIGN.md> .opencode/specs/<track>/<packet>/output/tokens.json\n\n# Optional вҖ” fidelity proof + visual report/preview (these take tokens.json FIRST):\nnpx ts-node .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/proof.ts <url> .opencode/specs/<track>/<packet>/output/tokens.json\nnpx ts-node .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/report-gen.ts .opencode/specs/<track>/<packet>/output/tokens.json <dir> <DESIGN.md>\nnpx ts-node .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/preview-gen.ts .opencode/specs/<track>/<packet>/output/tokens.json <dir>\n```\n\nReal extract flags (see `backend/README.md`): `--fast` (5 pages, 8 concurrency вҖ” still captures interaction), `--max-pages <n>` (default 8), `--concurrency <n>` (default 5), `--with-interaction` (the default вҖ” capture hover/focus/active states), `--no-interaction` (opt OUT of interaction capture), `--fast-no-interaction` (fast crawl AND skip interaction вҖ” the old `--fast` behavior), `--no-dark-mode` (skip dark detection), `--wait-for <strategy>`, `--extra-urls`, `--merge-with`, `--output <dir>` (REQUIRED вҖ” a spec folder outside the skill), `--insecure` (ignore HTTPS certificate errors for self-signed / staging hosts), `--verbose`. Interaction capture is **default-on**; opt out only with `--no-interaction` or `--fast-no-interaction`.\n\n### Token Stability Classes (L1вҖ“L4)\n\nEach extracted token receives a stability classification that governs whether it appears in `DESIGN.md`:\n\n| Class | Name (emitted `layer`)     | Description                                              | DESIGN.md treatment                      |\n| ----- | -------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |\n| L1    | Permanent (`infrastructure`) | Brand identity вҖ” logo colors, brand typeface, core radii | Included in main sections                |\n| L2    | System (`system`)          | Design-system tokens вҖ” semantic colors, spacing scale    | Included in main sections                |\n| L3    | Campaign (`campaign`)      | Temporary вҖ” hero gradients, seasonal accents             | Included with \"Subject to change\" annotation |\n| L4    | Content (`content`)        | Image-derived, one-off, article-specific                 | Excluded entirely                        |\n\nThe classifier lives in `backend/scripts/cluster.ts` and is deterministic. Tokens that sit at a boundary are assigned the higher (more restrictive) class. In `tokens.json` each token's `stability.layer` carries the emitted string (`infrastructure` for L1, then `system`, `campaign`, `content`) вҖ” \"Permanent\" is the human-facing label for the `infrastructure` layer.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":320,"totalLines":462,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782532211411,"end":1782532211434}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e76213ab5cc5f56016a3f48734bdc8191946832e2d828e999"}},"id":"prt_f073302bc001ZR58xTUK1F9jDA","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","messageID":"msg_f073297d6001A3dxut5pYElRvw"}}
