{"type":"text","timestamp":1782532293478,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"id":"prt_f0733f799001MWm5605HvcnW6E","messageID":"msg_f0733e001001u7RASZufmf6CNx","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","type":"text","text":"There is older lineage material from the reference-expansion run that specifically covered md-generator. IвҖҷm using it as prior research, but IвҖҷll re-check against the live skill because some proposals may already be implemented or ruled out.","time":{"start":1782532274073,"end":1782532293476},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_07a1153d994a9141016a3f48b21380819183b6b724d7172a60","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532293543,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_VwBYq4KbpxQSKGsR5L7zUvNZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/design_md_format.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/design_md_format.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: DESIGN.md Style Reference Format\n3: version: 1.0.0.3\n4: description: \"The authoritative Style Reference section specification: named colour tokens, semantic type scale, named components, Surfaces, Elevation, Agent Prompt Guide, Similar Brands, and copy-paste Quick Start вҖ” every value verbatim from tokens.json.\"\n5: trigger_phrases:\n6:   - design md format specification\n7:   - style reference schema\n8:   - design md section order\n9:   - named colour tokens\n10:   - quick start css tailwind\n11:   - agent prompt guide section\n12:   - similar brands section\n13: importance_tier: important\n14: contextType: implementation\n15: ---\n16: \n17: # DESIGN.md Style Reference Format\n18: \n19: > The v3 schema produces a **Style Reference**: a named, role-driven, ship-ready design\n20: > system handoff вҖ” not an extraction report. It matches the reference house style:\n21: > confident and grounded, with copy-paste CSS + Tailwind. Every value is still verbatim\n22: > from `tokens.json`; what changes from v2 is the voice (named + restrained, not\n23: > mechanical + hedged) and the section set.\n24: \n25: ---\n26: \n27: ## 0. Cardinal rules (unchanged from the fidelity contract)\n28: \n29: 1. Every hex, px, weight, radius, duration, and shadow is copied **verbatim** from\n30:    `tokens.json`. Never estimate, round, or invent a value.\n31: 2. **No false systems.** Do not assert a relationship, cause, or system the data\n32:    contradicts: no \"gradient-as-depth\" when there are 0 shadow tokens, no \"focus is\n33:    consistent\" when `focusIndicator.consistent` is false. This guard is absolute.\n34: 3. **Confident but grounded.** DO assign evocative semantic names, state roles plainly,\n35:    and infer Similar Brands вҖ” these are grounded inferences, not fabricated data. The\n36:    line is: name and characterize what IS there; never invent what is NOT.\n37: 4. **No mechanical noise.** Never print raw frequency dumps (\"border 9685, text 4258\"),\n38:    the extractor's internal CSS var names (`--_color-primitives---neutral--1400`), or\n39:    placeholder labels (\"div\", \"Variant-1\"). Frequency DECIDES prominence/role; it is not\n40:    displayed.\n41: 5. **Restraint over purple prose.** Characterize in one grounded clause, not a paragraph\n42:    of metaphor. \"A warm-tinted near-black\" beats \"letters like hull plates.\"\n43: 6. A section with no backing data is **omitted** (when conditional) or stamped\n44:    `_No <X> data was extracted._` вҖ” never filled with invention.\n45: \n46: ---\n47: \n48: ## 1. File header\n49: \n50: ```\n51: # <Brand or Domain> вҖ” Style Reference\n52: > <one-line evocative tagline вҖ” the design's essence in a phrase>\n53: \n54: **Theme:** light | dark | mixed\n55: ```\n56: \n57: - Brand name: from the page title / wordmark when available, else the domain.\n58: - Tagline: a single grounded, evocative phrase (e.g. \"Broadsheet financial broadside вҖ”\n59:   the masthead itself is the design\"). Characterizes; does not fabricate facts.\n60: - Theme: `light` if the page background is light, `dark` if dark, `mixed` if it\n61:   alternates full-bleed light and dark sections.\n62: \n63: ## 2. Intro paragraph (unlabeled, directly under the header)\n64: \n65: One paragraph, 4вҖ“6 sentences. Characterize the system's voice: canvas, the dominant\n66: type move, how color is rationed, layout density, what carries the page. Every\n67: characterizing claim must map to a real token (a hex, a size, a weight). Restrained, not\n68: purple. No assumed audience (\"targets captains and port agents\") unless the page states\n69: it.\n70: \n71: ## 3. `## Tokens вҖ” Colors`\n72: \n73: A table, most-prominent first:\n74: \n75: ```\n76: | Name | Value | Token | Role |\n77: |------|-------|-------|------|\n78: | Obsidian Ink | `#121613` | `--color-obsidian-ink` | Primary text, borders, image frames вҖ” a warm-tinted near-black |\n79: ```\n80: \n81: - **Name:** evocative + grounded (hue + lightness + character). \"Linen\", \"Obsidian Ink\",\n82:   \"Voltage\", \"Sage\", \"Mist\". Neutrals by lightness (Snow/Linen вҶ’ Ink/Obsidian/Void);\n83:   hued by family + character (Voltage/Azure/Ember). Be consistent within a doc.\n84: - **Value:** 6-digit lowercase hex, verbatim. Gradients render their full\n85:   `linear-gradient(...)` value.\n86: - **Token:** `--color-<kebab-name>` derived from the Name. NEVER the extractor's internal\n87:   var. (The Quick Start В§16 re-uses these exact slugs.)\n88: - **Role:** where it is used (grounded in the measured usage) + one characterizing\n89:   clause. No frequency numbers. For a supporting accent, add a usage guard\n90:   (\"Do not promote it to the primary CTA color\").\n91: - L1/L2 colours in the main table. L3 in a `### Current Campaign Colors (Subject to\n92:   change)` sub-table. L4 excluded entirely.\n93: \n94: ## 4. `## Tokens вҖ” Typography`\n95: \n96: Per-font block, then a Type Scale table.\n97: \n98: ```\n99: ### <Font Family> вҖ” <role prose> В· `--font-<slug>`\n100: - **Substitute:** <closest open/system substitute>\n101: - **Weights:** <comma list, verbatim>\n102: - **Sizes:** <comma list, verbatim>\n103: - **Line height:** <range or list, verbatim>\n104: - **Letter spacing:** <per-size, verbatim; omit if all normal>\n105: - **OpenType features:** `<value>` (omit if none)\n106: - **Role:** <the role prose, repeated as the bullet>\n107: ```\n108: \n109: Then:\n110: \n111: ```\n112: ### Type Scale\n113: | Role | Size | Line Height | Letter Spacing | Token |\n114: |------|------|-------------|----------------|-------|\n115: | body | 16px | 1.4 | -0.32px | `--text-body` |\n116: | display | 140px | 0.9 | -1.4px | `--text-display` |\n117: ```\n118: \n119: - Role names are **semantic** вҖ” `caption, body-sm, body, subheading, heading-sm,\n120:   heading, heading-lg, display, hero` вҖ” mapped by size rank, NEVER the raw DOM tag\n121:   (\"div\"). Map the extracted levels onto this scale by ascending size.\n122: - Token: `--text-<role>`.\n123: \n124: ## 5. `## Tokens вҖ” Spacing & Shapes`\n125: \n126: ```\n127: **Base unit:** <Npx>   (omit if no clear base)\n128: **Density:** compact | comfortable | spacious\n129: \n130: ### Spacing Scale\n131: | Name | Value | Token |\n132: |------|-------|-------|\n133: | 8 | 8px | `--spacing-8` |\n134: \n135: ### Border Radius\n136: | Element | Value |\n137: |---------|-------|\n138: | buttons | 7px |\n139: | cards | 14px |\n140: \n141: ### Shadows\n142: | Name | Value | Token |\n143: |------|-------|-------|\n144: | lg | `<shadow value>` | `--shadow-lg` |\n145:    (omit the whole Shadows block when 0 shadow tokens)\n146: \n147: ### Layout\n148: - **Page max-width:** <value>\n149: - **Section gap:** <value>\n150: - **Card padding:** <value>\n151: - **Element gap:** <value>\n152: ```\n153: \n154: - Density: `spacious` if section gaps are large relative to content; `compact` if tight.\n155: - Border Radius: map measured radii to element roles (buttons/cards/inputs/badges/etc.).\n156: \n157: ## 6. `## Components`\n158: \n159: ```\n160: ### <Named Component>\n161: **Role:** <one line вҖ” what it is and where it's used>\n162: \n163: <prose with EXACT values: background, text (color + size + family + weight), padding,\n164: radius, border, hover/focus states, transition, and an example label or use.>\n165: ```\n166: \n167: - Name components by function: Primary CTA, Secondary Button, Ghost Link, Nav Header,\n168:   Card, Badge, Footer. NEVER \"Variant-1\" вҖ” if a variant cannot be characterized, fold it\n169:   into the nearest named component or describe it by its distinguishing property\n170:   (\"a lighter green status variant\").\n171: - Only include states that were actually captured. Do not repeat an invisible \"0px\n172:   focus\" line on every component вҖ” characterize it once where it matters (and flag it in\n173:   Accessibility / Agent Guide if it is an a11y problem).\n174: \n175: ## 7. `## Do's and Don'ts`\n176: \n177: `### Do` and `### Don't` bullet lists. Each bullet cites a concrete value and reads as an\n178: instruction (\"Use `#06458c` for all link colors\", \"Do not add `box-shadow` вҖ” there are\n179: zero shadow tokens; any shadow is an invention\").\n180: \n181: ## 8. `## Surfaces`\n182: \n183: ```\n184: | Level | Name | Value | Purpose |\n185: |-------|------|-------|---------|\n186: | 0 | Canvas | `#fefefe` | Full-bleed page background |\n187: | 1 | Card | `#f8f8f8` | Card surfaces |\n188: ```\n189: \n190: Derive levels from the background colours actually used, ordered base вҶ’ elevated. If\n191: cards share the canvas hex, say so (\"same hex as canvas вҖ” cards are defined by radius +\n192: padding, not fill\").\n193: \n194: ## 9. `## Elevation`\n195: \n196: Either a per-component shadow list, or вҖ” when there are 0 shadow tokens вҖ” a prose line\n197: stating the system is flat and HOW depth is achieved instead (border, tonal contrast,\n198: whitespace). This is the honest replacement for the old \"gradient-as-depth\" failure.\n199: \n200: ## 10. `## Imagery`\n201: \n202: Prose: what imagery the site uses and its treatment (B&W, full-bleed, rounded, etc.),\n203: grounded in what was observed. If no meaningful imagery signal was extracted, say so\n204: plainly rather than inventing a visual language.\n205: \n206: ## 11. `## Layout`\n207: \n208: Prose: max-width, hero structure, section rhythm, nav behavior, grid vs asymmetric вҖ”\n209: grounded in the breakpoint/spacing/column data.\n210: \n211: ## 12. `## Agent Prompt Guide`\n212: \n213: ```\n214: ### Quick Color Reference\n215: - background: <hex>\n216: - text (primary): <hex>\n217: - border: <hex>\n218: - accent / primary action: <hex or \"no distinct CTA color\">\n219: \n220: ### Example Component Prompts\n221: 1. <fully-specified, copy-paste component prompt with every value inline>\n222: ... (3вҖ“5 total)\n223: ```\n224: \n225: If no distinct CTA/action colour was observed, say \"no distinct CTA color\" вҖ” do not\n226: invent one.\n227: \n228: ## 13. `## Similar Brands`\n229: \n230: 3вҖ“5 brands with a one-line WHY each, as **confident grounded inference** from the\n231: observed system (palette discipline, type scale, layout rhythm). This section is\n232: explicitly inferential and that is allowed вҖ” it characterizes the design's family, it\n233: does not fabricate the site's own data.\n234: \n235: ## 14. `## Quick Start`\n236: \n237: Two fenced code blocks, every value verbatim from tokens, slugs matching В§3/В§4/В§5.\n238: \n239: ````\n240: ### CSS Custom Properties\n241: \n242: ```css\n243: :root {\n244:   /* Colors */\n245:   --color-<name>: <hex>;\n246:   ...\n247:   /* Typography вҖ” Font Families */\n248:   --font-<slug>: '<family>', <fallback stack>;\n249:   /* Typography вҖ” Scale */\n250:   --text-<role>: <size>;\n251:   --leading-<role>: <lh>;\n252:   --tracking-<role>: <ls>;\n253:   /* Typography вҖ” Weights */\n254:   --font-weight-<name>: <weight>;\n255:   /* Spacing */\n256:   --spacing-<n>: <Npx>;\n257:   /* Layout */\n258:   --page-max-width: <value>;\n259:   /* Border Radius */\n260:   --radius-<name>: <value>;\n\n(Showing lines 1-260 of 300. Use offset=261 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: DESIGN.md Style Reference Format\nversion: 1.0.0.3\ndescription: \"The authoritative Style Reference section specification: named colour tokens, semantic type scale, named components, Surfaces, Elevation, Agent Prompt Guide, Similar Brands, and copy-paste Quick Start вҖ” every value verbatim from tokens.json.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - design md format specification\n  - style reference schema\n  - design md section order\n  - named colour tokens\n  - quick start css tailwind\n  - agent prompt guide section\n  - similar brands section\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\n---\n\n# DESIGN.md Style Reference Format\n\n> The v3 schema produces a **Style Reference**: a named, role-driven, ship-ready design\n> system handoff вҖ” not an extraction report. It matches the reference house style:","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/design_md_format.md","text":"---\ntitle: DESIGN.md Style Reference Format\nversion: 1.0.0.3\ndescription: \"The authoritative Style Reference section specification: named colour tokens, semantic type scale, named components, Surfaces, Elevation, Agent Prompt Guide, Similar Brands, and copy-paste Quick Start вҖ” every value verbatim from tokens.json.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - design md format specification\n  - style reference schema\n  - design md section order\n  - named colour tokens\n  - quick start css tailwind\n  - agent prompt guide section\n  - similar brands section\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\n---\n\n# DESIGN.md Style Reference Format\n\n> The v3 schema produces a **Style Reference**: a named, role-driven, ship-ready design\n> system handoff вҖ” not an extraction report. It matches the reference house style:\n> confident and grounded, with copy-paste CSS + Tailwind. Every value is still verbatim\n> from `tokens.json`; what changes from v2 is the voice (named + restrained, not\n> mechanical + hedged) and the section set.\n\n---\n\n## 0. Cardinal rules (unchanged from the fidelity contract)\n\n1. Every hex, px, weight, radius, duration, and shadow is copied **verbatim** from\n   `tokens.json`. Never estimate, round, or invent a value.\n2. **No false systems.** Do not assert a relationship, cause, or system the data\n   contradicts: no \"gradient-as-depth\" when there are 0 shadow tokens, no \"focus is\n   consistent\" when `focusIndicator.consistent` is false. This guard is absolute.\n3. **Confident but grounded.** DO assign evocative semantic names, state roles plainly,\n   and infer Similar Brands вҖ” these are grounded inferences, not fabricated data. The\n   line is: name and characterize what IS there; never invent what is NOT.\n4. **No mechanical noise.** Never print raw frequency dumps (\"border 9685, text 4258\"),\n   the extractor's internal CSS var names (`--_color-primitives---neutral--1400`), or\n   placeholder labels (\"div\", \"Variant-1\"). Frequency DECIDES prominence/role; it is not\n   displayed.\n5. **Restraint over purple prose.** Characterize in one grounded clause, not a paragraph\n   of metaphor. \"A warm-tinted near-black\" beats \"letters like hull plates.\"\n6. A section with no backing data is **omitted** (when conditional) or stamped\n   `_No <X> data was extracted._` вҖ” never filled with invention.\n\n---\n\n## 1. File header\n\n```\n# <Brand or Domain> вҖ” Style Reference\n> <one-line evocative tagline вҖ” the design's essence in a phrase>\n\n**Theme:** light | dark | mixed\n```\n\n- Brand name: from the page title / wordmark when available, else the domain.\n- Tagline: a single grounded, evocative phrase (e.g. \"Broadsheet financial broadside вҖ”\n  the masthead itself is the design\"). Characterizes; does not fabricate facts.\n- Theme: `light` if the page background is light, `dark` if dark, `mixed` if it\n  alternates full-bleed light and dark sections.\n\n## 2. Intro paragraph (unlabeled, directly under the header)\n\nOne paragraph, 4вҖ“6 sentences. Characterize the system's voice: canvas, the dominant\ntype move, how color is rationed, layout density, what carries the page. Every\ncharacterizing claim must map to a real token (a hex, a size, a weight). Restrained, not\npurple. No assumed audience (\"targets captains and port agents\") unless the page states\nit.\n\n## 3. `## Tokens вҖ” Colors`\n\nA table, most-prominent first:\n\n```\n| Name | Value | Token | Role |\n|------|-------|-------|------|\n| Obsidian Ink | `#121613` | `--color-obsidian-ink` | Primary text, borders, image frames вҖ” a warm-tinted near-black |\n```\n\n- **Name:** evocative + grounded (hue + lightness + character). \"Linen\", \"Obsidian Ink\",\n  \"Voltage\", \"Sage\", \"Mist\". Neutrals by lightness (Snow/Linen вҶ’ Ink/Obsidian/Void);\n  hued by family + character (Voltage/Azure/Ember). Be consistent within a doc.\n- **Value:** 6-digit lowercase hex, verbatim. Gradients render their full\n  `linear-gradient(...)` value.\n- **Token:** `--color-<kebab-name>` derived from the Name. NEVER the extractor's internal\n  var. (The Quick Start В§16 re-uses these exact slugs.)\n- **Role:** where it is used (grounded in the measured usage) + one characterizing\n  clause. No frequency numbers. For a supporting accent, add a usage guard\n  (\"Do not promote it to the primary CTA color\").\n- L1/L2 colours in the main table. L3 in a `### Current Campaign Colors (Subject to\n  change)` sub-table. L4 excluded entirely.\n\n## 4. `## Tokens вҖ” Typography`\n\nPer-font block, then a Type Scale table.\n\n```\n### <Font Family> вҖ” <role prose> В· `--font-<slug>`\n- **Substitute:** <closest open/system substitute>\n- **Weights:** <comma list, verbatim>\n- **Sizes:** <comma list, verbatim>\n- **Line height:** <range or list, verbatim>\n- **Letter spacing:** <per-size, verbatim; omit if all normal>\n- **OpenType features:** `<value>` (omit if none)\n- **Role:** <the role prose, repeated as the bullet>\n```\n\nThen:\n\n```\n### Type Scale\n| Role | Size | Line Height | Letter Spacing | Token |\n|------|------|-------------|----------------|-------|\n| body | 16px | 1.4 | -0.32px | `--text-body` |\n| display | 140px | 0.9 | -1.4px | `--text-display` |\n```\n\n- Role names are **semantic** вҖ” `caption, body-sm, body, subheading, heading-sm,\n  heading, heading-lg, display, hero` вҖ” mapped by size rank, NEVER the raw DOM tag\n  (\"div\"). Map the extracted levels onto this scale by ascending size.\n- Token: `--text-<role>`.\n\n## 5. `## Tokens вҖ” Spacing & Shapes`\n\n```\n**Base unit:** <Npx>   (omit if no clear base)\n**Density:** compact | comfortable | spacious\n\n### Spacing Scale\n| Name | Value | Token |\n|------|-------|-------|\n| 8 | 8px | `--spacing-8` |\n\n### Border Radius\n| Element | Value |\n|---------|-------|\n| buttons | 7px |\n| cards | 14px |\n\n### Shadows\n| Name | Value | Token |\n|------|-------|-------|\n| lg | `<shadow value>` | `--shadow-lg` |\n   (omit the whole Shadows block when 0 shadow tokens)\n\n### Layout\n- **Page max-width:** <value>\n- **Section gap:** <value>\n- **Card padding:** <value>\n- **Element gap:** <value>\n```\n\n- Density: `spacious` if section gaps are large relative to content; `compact` if tight.\n- Border Radius: map measured radii to element roles (buttons/cards/inputs/badges/etc.).\n\n## 6. `## Components`\n\n```\n### <Named Component>\n**Role:** <one line вҖ” what it is and where it's used>\n\n<prose with EXACT values: background, text (color + size + family + weight), padding,\nradius, border, hover/focus states, transition, and an example label or use.>\n```\n\n- Name components by function: Primary CTA, Secondary Button, Ghost Link, Nav Header,\n  Card, Badge, Footer. NEVER \"Variant-1\" вҖ” if a variant cannot be characterized, fold it\n  into the nearest named component or describe it by its distinguishing property\n  (\"a lighter green status variant\").\n- Only include states that were actually captured. Do not repeat an invisible \"0px\n  focus\" line on every component вҖ” characterize it once where it matters (and flag it in\n  Accessibility / Agent Guide if it is an a11y problem).\n\n## 7. `## Do's and Don'ts`\n\n`### Do` and `### Don't` bullet lists. Each bullet cites a concrete value and reads as an\ninstruction (\"Use `#06458c` for all link colors\", \"Do not add `box-shadow` вҖ” there are\nzero shadow tokens; any shadow is an invention\").\n\n## 8. `## Surfaces`\n\n```\n| Level | Name | Value | Purpose |\n|-------|------|-------|---------|\n| 0 | Canvas | `#fefefe` | Full-bleed page background |\n| 1 | Card | `#f8f8f8` | Card surfaces |\n```\n\nDerive levels from the background colours actually used, ordered base вҶ’ elevated. If\ncards share the canvas hex, say so (\"same hex as canvas вҖ” cards are defined by radius +\npadding, not fill\").\n\n## 9. `## Elevation`\n\nEither a per-component shadow list, or вҖ” when there are 0 shadow tokens вҖ” a prose line\nstating the system is flat and HOW depth is achieved instead (border, tonal contrast,\nwhitespace). This is the honest replacement for the old \"gradient-as-depth\" failure.\n\n## 10. `## Imagery`\n\nProse: what imagery the site uses and its treatment (B&W, full-bleed, rounded, etc.),\ngrounded in what was observed. If no meaningful imagery signal was extracted, say so\nplainly rather than inventing a visual language.\n\n## 11. `## Layout`\n\nProse: max-width, hero structure, section rhythm, nav behavior, grid vs asymmetric вҖ”\ngrounded in the breakpoint/spacing/column data.\n\n## 12. `## Agent Prompt Guide`\n\n```\n### Quick Color Reference\n- background: <hex>\n- text (primary): <hex>\n- border: <hex>\n- accent / primary action: <hex or \"no distinct CTA color\">\n\n### Example Component Prompts\n1. <fully-specified, copy-paste component prompt with every value inline>\n... (3вҖ“5 total)\n```\n\nIf no distinct CTA/action colour was observed, say \"no distinct CTA color\" вҖ” do not\ninvent one.\n\n## 13. `## Similar Brands`\n\n3вҖ“5 brands with a one-line WHY each, as **confident grounded inference** from the\nobserved system (palette discipline, type scale, layout rhythm). This section is\nexplicitly inferential and that is allowed вҖ” it characterizes the design's family, it\ndoes not fabricate the site's own data.\n\n## 14. `## Quick Start`\n\nTwo fenced code blocks, every value verbatim from tokens, slugs matching В§3/В§4/В§5.\n\n````\n### CSS Custom Properties\n\n```css\n:root {\n  /* Colors */\n  --color-<name>: <hex>;\n  ...\n  /* Typography вҖ” Font Families */\n  --font-<slug>: '<family>', <fallback stack>;\n  /* Typography вҖ” Scale */\n  --text-<role>: <size>;\n  --leading-<role>: <lh>;\n  --tracking-<role>: <ls>;\n  /* Typography вҖ” Weights */\n  --font-weight-<name>: <weight>;\n  /* Spacing */\n  --spacing-<n>: <Npx>;\n  /* Layout */\n  --page-max-width: <value>;\n  /* Border Radius */\n  --radius-<name>: <value>;","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":260,"totalLines":300,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/design_md_format.md","time":{"start":1782532293525,"end":1782532293538}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07a1153d994a9141016a3f48c572148191b3fd9a37b816de0d"}},"id":"prt_f07344394001hw5QEF0VPh9Jk2","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","messageID":"msg_f0733e001001u7RASZufmf6CNx"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532293544,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ocrNiIhQKGz3A5PVupheX2bN","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/authoring_boundary.md","offset":1,"limit":240},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/authoring_boundary.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Authoring Boundary\n3: description: The line between values measured from a live site, values a brief provides, values inferred and values that are absent. It defines the source-of-truth labels that keep a Style Reference faithful to its tokens.json and route forward-authoring out of scope.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - authoring boundary\n6:   - measured vs authored\n7:   - source of truth labels\n8:   - brief provided values\n9:   - forward authoring out of scope\n10:   - design md provenance\n11: importance_tier: normal\n12: contextType: implementation\n13: version: 1.0.0.0\n14: ---\n15: \n16: # Authoring Boundary\n17: \n18: This mode extracts a live site and renders its real CSS into a Style Reference. Every numeric value is copied verbatim from `tokens.json`. That is the cardinal fidelity rule and it is absolute. This document draws the line around it. It names four origins a value can have, gives each a source-of-truth label and states plainly which origins this mode is allowed to write. Read it as a boundary map, not a feature. It adds no new capability and it does not relax the fidelity contract by one digit.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. WHY THE BOUNDARY EXISTS\n23: \n24: A Style Reference is trusted because a reader can assume every hex, pixel, weight, radius and shadow in it was measured from a running page. The moment a value with a different origin slips in unlabeled, that assumption breaks for the whole document and the reader can no longer tell ground truth from a guess.\n25: \n26: The risk is not careless invention. It is the quiet drift where a plausible-looking value from a brief or a reasonable inference about direction gets written into a token table as if it were measured. The defense is a clear boundary plus a label on anything that is not a measured value.\n27: \n28: This mode captures what already exists. It does not author a design from a brief. Keeping those two jobs separate is what this boundary protects.\n29: \n30: ---\n31: \n32: ## 2. THE FOUR ORIGINS\n33: \n34: Every value a reader might want in a Style Reference comes from one of four origins. The first is the only one this mode writes into token tables.\n35: \n36: ### 2.1 Measured\n37: \n38: A value read off the running page by the extractor and present in `tokens.json`. Hex codes, pixel sizes, font weights, border radii, box shadows, spacing steps, durations. These are the only values allowed in the Tokens tables, Surfaces, Elevation and the Quick Start blocks. They are copied verbatim, never rounded, never normalized, never concretized.\n39: \n40: ### 2.2 Brief-provided\n41: \n42: A value the user supplied in the request rather than the site. A stakeholder might say the brand red is a specific hex or that the body font should be a named family, before any extraction confirms it on the page. A brief-provided value is a stated intent, not a measurement. It is not ground truth about the live surface and it never enters a token table as if the extractor found it.\n43: \n44: ### 2.3 Inferred\n45: \n46: A characterization the writer derives from measured values. Naming a near-black `Obsidian Ink`, stating a color's role, calling the density spacious, listing Similar Brands. These are grounded inferences built on real tokens and the format already allows them. The line is exact: name and characterize what IS measured, never invent a fact, a value or an audience that is not.\n47: \n48: ### 2.4 Absent\n49: \n50: A value the extractor did not capture. No dark palette, no shadow tokens, no imagery signal, no accessibility data. Absent is a real state with a real treatment in the format. A section with no backing data is omitted when conditional or stamped that no data was extracted. Absent is never filled by reaching for a brief-provided guess or by deriving a value the page never showed.\n51: \n52: ---\n53: \n54: ## 3. SOURCE-OF-TRUTH LABELS\n55: \n56: Labels keep the four origins legible inside one document so the cardinal rule stays enforceable by inspection.\n57: \n58: | Origin | Label in the document | Where it may appear |\n59: |---|---|---|\n60: | Measured | unlabeled, the default | Token tables, Surfaces, Elevation, Quick Start, characterizing prose |\n61: | Brief-provided | stated as the brief's intent, never as a token | Prose context only, kept out of value tables |\n62: | Inferred | `[INFERRED]` and cites the measured token it rests on | Names, roles, Similar Brands, characterizing prose |\n63: | Absent | stamped that no data was extracted or the section omitted | The section that would have held the value |\n64: \n65: Three rules govern the labels.\n66: \n67: 1. Measured is the default and carries no label. Because it is the default, anything that is NOT measured has to be marked, so an unlabeled value is a promise that the extractor measured it.\n68: 2. A brief-provided value never sits in a token table. It is not a measurement and the table is reserved for measurements. If a brief value needs recording, it belongs in prose as a stated intent, plainly distinct from the measured tokens.\n69: 3. An inferred claim names what is measured and cites the token under it. Inference characterizes real data. It never manufactures a value, and the citation is what lets a reader trace it back to ground truth.\n70: \n71: ---\n72: \n73: ## 4. WHAT THIS MODE WRITES\n74: \n75: This mode writes measured values and grounded inferences about them. Nothing else reaches a token table.\n76: \n77: - Measured values fill the Tokens tables, Surfaces, Elevation and the Quick Start, verbatim from `tokens.json`.\n78: - Inferences supply evocative names, plain role statements and Similar Brands, each grounded in a measured token.\n79: - Brief-provided values stay out of the value tables. They may set context in prose as a stated intent and they never wear the appearance of a measurement.\n80: - Absent values are stamped or omitted, never backfilled.\n81: \n82: The Quick Start exists because the output is ship-ready, and it is ship-ready precisely because every value in it was measured. A brief-provided or invented value in the Quick Start would hand a coding agent a fabricated token under the banner of ground truth, which is the exact failure the cardinal rule exists to prevent.\n83: \n84: ---\n85: \n86: ## 5. FORWARD-AUTHORING IS OUT OF SCOPE\n87: \n88: Generating a Style Reference from a brief alone, with no live site to measure, is forward-authoring. It is OUT OF SCOPE for this mode and this document does not enable it.\n89: \n90: Forward-authoring inverts the input contract. This mode starts from a running page and reports what is measurably there. Forward-authoring starts from a brief and proposes what should be there. A skill in the wider field, the Stitch design-taste skill, illustrates the forward-authoring shape: it turns a vibe and a set of directives into a `DESIGN.md` for screen generation with no extraction step and no measured source. That is a different job with a different contract, and treating its output and this mode's output as interchangeable is the category error this boundary guards against.\n91: \n92: The reasons forward-authoring stays out are structural, not a matter of effort.\n93: \n94: - Different input contract. Measured extraction needs a live, renderable URL. Forward-authoring needs only a brief. Folding both into one mode would blur the very assumption that makes a Style Reference trustworthy.\n95: - Fidelity must not weaken. The cardinal rule binds every value to `tokens.json`. A brief-driven path has no `tokens.json` to bind to, so admitting it here would force a relaxation of the contract. That trade is refused.\n96: - No second backend. This mode already extracts, writes, validates and reports through one pipeline. Forward-authoring is not a missing stage of that pipeline. It is a separate capability.\n97: \n98: When a user wants a design authored from a brief with no site to measure, that is a separate future design-spec decision, routed away from this mode. Do not satisfy the request by loosening fidelity here. State that this mode captures an existing surface, and that brief-only authoring is a different contract handled elsewhere.\n99: \n100: ---\n101: \n102: ## 6. QUICK BOUNDARY CHECK\n103: \n104: Run this before writing any value into a Style Reference.\n105: \n106: ```text\n107: в–Ў Is the value in tokens.json? If yes, it is measured. Copy it verbatim, no label.\n108: в–Ў Did it come from the brief, not the page? Keep it out of token tables. Note it as intent in prose only.\n109: в–Ў Is it a characterization of a measured value? Mark it [INFERRED] and cite the token.\n110: в–Ў Did the extractor not capture it? Stamp the section absent or omit it. Never backfill.\n111: в–Ў Are you authoring from a brief with no live site? Stop. That is forward-authoring, out of scope, route to the separate design-spec decision.\n112: ```\n113: \n114: ---\n115: \n116: ## 7. RELATED RESOURCES\n117: \n118: - [design_md_format.md](design_md_format.md) - the Style Reference section specification and the Section 0 cardinal rules this boundary protects.\n119: - [../assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md](../assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md) - the fill-in card that sorts each value into measured, brief-provided, inferred or absent before writing.\n120: - [../assets/cardinal_rules_card.md](../assets/cardinal_rules_card.md) - the pre-validate fidelity checklist.\n121: - [../../shared/register.md](../../shared/register.md) - the Brand-vs-Product register. This mode records the extracted surface's register, it does not author one from a brief.\n\n(End of file - total 121 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Authoring Boundary\ndescription: The line between values measured from a live site, values a brief provides, values inferred and values that are absent. It defines the source-of-truth labels that keep a Style Reference faithful to its tokens.json and route forward-authoring out of scope.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - authoring boundary\n  - measured vs authored\n  - source of truth labels\n  - brief provided values\n  - forward authoring out of scope\n  - design md provenance\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Authoring Boundary\n\nThis mode extracts a live site and renders its real CSS into a Style Reference. Every numeric value is copied verbatim from `tokens.json`. That is the cardinal fidelity rule and it is absolute. This document draws the line around it. It names four origins a value can have, gives each a source-of-truth label and states plainly which origins this mode is allowed to write. Read it as a boundary map, not a feature. It adds no new capability and it does not relax the fidelity contract by one digit.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/authoring_boundary.md","text":"---\ntitle: Authoring Boundary\ndescription: The line between values measured from a live site, values a brief provides, values inferred and values that are absent. It defines the source-of-truth labels that keep a Style Reference faithful to its tokens.json and route forward-authoring out of scope.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - authoring boundary\n  - measured vs authored\n  - source of truth labels\n  - brief provided values\n  - forward authoring out of scope\n  - design md provenance\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Authoring Boundary\n\nThis mode extracts a live site and renders its real CSS into a Style Reference. Every numeric value is copied verbatim from `tokens.json`. That is the cardinal fidelity rule and it is absolute. This document draws the line around it. It names four origins a value can have, gives each a source-of-truth label and states plainly which origins this mode is allowed to write. Read it as a boundary map, not a feature. It adds no new capability and it does not relax the fidelity contract by one digit.\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHY THE BOUNDARY EXISTS\n\nA Style Reference is trusted because a reader can assume every hex, pixel, weight, radius and shadow in it was measured from a running page. The moment a value with a different origin slips in unlabeled, that assumption breaks for the whole document and the reader can no longer tell ground truth from a guess.\n\nThe risk is not careless invention. It is the quiet drift where a plausible-looking value from a brief or a reasonable inference about direction gets written into a token table as if it were measured. The defense is a clear boundary plus a label on anything that is not a measured value.\n\nThis mode captures what already exists. It does not author a design from a brief. Keeping those two jobs separate is what this boundary protects.\n\n---\n\n## 2. THE FOUR ORIGINS\n\nEvery value a reader might want in a Style Reference comes from one of four origins. The first is the only one this mode writes into token tables.\n\n### 2.1 Measured\n\nA value read off the running page by the extractor and present in `tokens.json`. Hex codes, pixel sizes, font weights, border radii, box shadows, spacing steps, durations. These are the only values allowed in the Tokens tables, Surfaces, Elevation and the Quick Start blocks. They are copied verbatim, never rounded, never normalized, never concretized.\n\n### 2.2 Brief-provided\n\nA value the user supplied in the request rather than the site. A stakeholder might say the brand red is a specific hex or that the body font should be a named family, before any extraction confirms it on the page. A brief-provided value is a stated intent, not a measurement. It is not ground truth about the live surface and it never enters a token table as if the extractor found it.\n\n### 2.3 Inferred\n\nA characterization the writer derives from measured values. Naming a near-black `Obsidian Ink`, stating a color's role, calling the density spacious, listing Similar Brands. These are grounded inferences built on real tokens and the format already allows them. The line is exact: name and characterize what IS measured, never invent a fact, a value or an audience that is not.\n\n### 2.4 Absent\n\nA value the extractor did not capture. No dark palette, no shadow tokens, no imagery signal, no accessibility data. Absent is a real state with a real treatment in the format. A section with no backing data is omitted when conditional or stamped that no data was extracted. Absent is never filled by reaching for a brief-provided guess or by deriving a value the page never showed.\n\n---\n\n## 3. SOURCE-OF-TRUTH LABELS\n\nLabels keep the four origins legible inside one document so the cardinal rule stays enforceable by inspection.\n\n| Origin | Label in the document | Where it may appear |\n|---|---|---|\n| Measured | unlabeled, the default | Token tables, Surfaces, Elevation, Quick Start, characterizing prose |\n| Brief-provided | stated as the brief's intent, never as a token | Prose context only, kept out of value tables |\n| Inferred | `[INFERRED]` and cites the measured token it rests on | Names, roles, Similar Brands, characterizing prose |\n| Absent | stamped that no data was extracted or the section omitted | The section that would have held the value |\n\nThree rules govern the labels.\n\n1. Measured is the default and carries no label. Because it is the default, anything that is NOT measured has to be marked, so an unlabeled value is a promise that the extractor measured it.\n2. A brief-provided value never sits in a token table. It is not a measurement and the table is reserved for measurements. If a brief value needs recording, it belongs in prose as a stated intent, plainly distinct from the measured tokens.\n3. An inferred claim names what is measured and cites the token under it. Inference characterizes real data. It never manufactures a value, and the citation is what lets a reader trace it back to ground truth.\n\n---\n\n## 4. WHAT THIS MODE WRITES\n\nThis mode writes measured values and grounded inferences about them. Nothing else reaches a token table.\n\n- Measured values fill the Tokens tables, Surfaces, Elevation and the Quick Start, verbatim from `tokens.json`.\n- Inferences supply evocative names, plain role statements and Similar Brands, each grounded in a measured token.\n- Brief-provided values stay out of the value tables. They may set context in prose as a stated intent and they never wear the appearance of a measurement.\n- Absent values are stamped or omitted, never backfilled.\n\nThe Quick Start exists because the output is ship-ready, and it is ship-ready precisely because every value in it was measured. A brief-provided or invented value in the Quick Start would hand a coding agent a fabricated token under the banner of ground truth, which is the exact failure the cardinal rule exists to prevent.\n\n---\n\n## 5. FORWARD-AUTHORING IS OUT OF SCOPE\n\nGenerating a Style Reference from a brief alone, with no live site to measure, is forward-authoring. It is OUT OF SCOPE for this mode and this document does not enable it.\n\nForward-authoring inverts the input contract. This mode starts from a running page and reports what is measurably there. Forward-authoring starts from a brief and proposes what should be there. A skill in the wider field, the Stitch design-taste skill, illustrates the forward-authoring shape: it turns a vibe and a set of directives into a `DESIGN.md` for screen generation with no extraction step and no measured source. That is a different job with a different contract, and treating its output and this mode's output as interchangeable is the category error this boundary guards against.\n\nThe reasons forward-authoring stays out are structural, not a matter of effort.\n\n- Different input contract. Measured extraction needs a live, renderable URL. Forward-authoring needs only a brief. Folding both into one mode would blur the very assumption that makes a Style Reference trustworthy.\n- Fidelity must not weaken. The cardinal rule binds every value to `tokens.json`. A brief-driven path has no `tokens.json` to bind to, so admitting it here would force a relaxation of the contract. That trade is refused.\n- No second backend. This mode already extracts, writes, validates and reports through one pipeline. Forward-authoring is not a missing stage of that pipeline. It is a separate capability.\n\nWhen a user wants a design authored from a brief with no site to measure, that is a separate future design-spec decision, routed away from this mode. Do not satisfy the request by loosening fidelity here. State that this mode captures an existing surface, and that brief-only authoring is a different contract handled elsewhere.\n\n---\n\n## 6. QUICK BOUNDARY CHECK\n\nRun this before writing any value into a Style Reference.\n\n```text\nв–Ў Is the value in tokens.json? If yes, it is measured. Copy it verbatim, no label.\nв–Ў Did it come from the brief, not the page? Keep it out of token tables. Note it as intent in prose only.\nв–Ў Is it a characterization of a measured value? Mark it [INFERRED] and cite the token.\nв–Ў Did the extractor not capture it? Stamp the section absent or omit it. Never backfill.\nв–Ў Are you authoring from a brief with no live site? Stop. That is forward-authoring, out of scope, route to the separate design-spec decision.\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- [design_md_format.md](design_md_format.md) - the Style Reference section specification and the Section 0 cardinal rules this boundary protects.\n- [../assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md](../assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md) - the fill-in card that sorts each value into measured, brief-provided, inferred or absent before writing.\n- [../assets/cardinal_rules_card.md](../assets/cardinal_rules_card.md) - the pre-validate fidelity checklist.\n- [../../shared/register.md](../../shared/register.md) - the Brand-vs-Product register. This mode records the extracted surface's register, it does not author one from a brief.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":121,"totalLines":121,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/authoring_boundary.md","time":{"start":1782532293529,"end":1782532293540}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07a1153d994a9141016a3f48c572248191bd3d43aedf8b8fa0"}},"id":"prt_f07344398001xxEmHWa36RZD10","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","messageID":"msg_f0733e001001u7RASZufmf6CNx"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532293544,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Rky0NJzB89nsoQTWpYDshAZr","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Source-of-Truth Router Card\n3: description: A one-page fill-in card that sorts each value bound for a Style Reference into measured, brief-provided, inferred or absent, so a writer never fabricates a token or backfills missing data.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - source of truth router card\n6:   - measured or inferred card\n7:   - design md value provenance card\n8:   - is this value measured\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Source-of-Truth Router Card\n15: \n16: Fill this in before writing values into a Style Reference. It sorts every value by origin so only measured values land in the token tables and nothing gets invented or backfilled. Full rationale: [`../references/authoring_boundary.md`](../references/authoring_boundary.md).\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. SORT EACH VALUE\n21: \n22: For each value you are about to write, walk the questions top to bottom. The first yes decides the origin.\n23: \n24: | Question | If yes, the origin is |\n25: |---|---|\n26: | Is the value present in `tokens.json`, read off the running page? | Measured |\n27: | Did the user state it in the brief, not the page? | Brief-provided |\n28: | Are you characterizing a measured value (a name, a role, a Similar Brand)? | Inferred |\n29: | Did the extractor not capture it at all? | Absent |\n30: \n31: A value can have only one origin. When the brief states a value AND the extractor measured it, the measured token is the source of truth and the brief value is context.\n32: \n33: ---\n34: \n35: ## 2. ROUTE BY ORIGIN\n36: \n37: Copy the row for each value's origin and follow its rule.\n38: \n39: | Origin | Label | Goes where | Never |\n40: |---|---|---|---|\n41: | Measured | none, it is the default | Token tables, Surfaces, Elevation, Quick Start | rounded, normalized, concretized or re-typed by hand |\n42: | Brief-provided | stated as the brief's intent | Prose context only | placed in a token table as if measured |\n43: | Inferred | `[INFERRED]` plus the token it cites | Names, roles, Similar Brands, characterizing prose | a value, fact or audience the page never showed |\n44: | Absent | stamped no data extracted or omitted | The section that would have held it | backfilled from a brief or a derived guess |\n45: \n46: An unlabeled value is a promise it was measured. If you cannot point to its row in `tokens.json`, it does not go in unlabeled.\n47: \n48: ---\n49: \n50: ## 3. FILL IN THE DOUBTFUL VALUES\n51: \n52: List any value whose origin was not obvious, so the boundary call is on the record.\n53: \n54: | Value (what it is) | Origin (one of the four) | Token it traces to or why absent |\n55: |---|---|---|\n56: | `__________` | `__________` | `__________` |\n57: | `__________` | `__________` | `__________` |\n58: | `__________` | `__________` | `__________` |\n59: \n60: If a row cannot name a measured token and the origin is not honestly brief-provided, inferred or absent, the value is an invention. Remove it.\n61: \n62: ---\n63: \n64: ## 4. STOP CHECK\n65: \n66: ```text\n67: в–Ў Every value in a token table is measured and verbatim from tokens.json\n68: в–Ў No brief-provided value is sitting in a token table\n69: в–Ў Every inference is marked [INFERRED] and cites a measured token\n70: в–Ў Every absent value is stamped or omitted, none backfilled\n71: в–Ў You are extracting a live surface, not authoring from a brief with no site\n72: ```\n73: \n74: If the last box fails, this is forward-authoring. It is out of scope for this mode. Route it to the separate design-spec decision and do not loosen fidelity to fit it here.\n75: \n76: ---\n77: \n78: ## 5. RELATED RESOURCES\n79: \n80: - [`../references/authoring_boundary.md`](../references/authoring_boundary.md) - the four origins, the source-of-truth labels and why forward-authoring stays out of scope.\n81: - [`cardinal_rules_card.md`](cardinal_rules_card.md) - the pre-validate fidelity checklist.\n82: - [`../../shared/assets/register_card.md`](../../shared/assets/register_card.md) - the Brand-vs-Product register card. This mode records the extracted surface's register.\n\n(End of file - total 82 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Source-of-Truth Router Card\ndescription: A one-page fill-in card that sorts each value bound for a Style Reference into measured, brief-provided, inferred or absent, so a writer never fabricates a token or backfills missing data.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - source of truth router card\n  - measured or inferred card\n  - design md value provenance card\n  - is this value measured\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Source-of-Truth Router Card\n\nFill this in before writing values into a Style Reference. It sorts every value by origin so only measured values land in the token tables and nothing gets invented or backfilled. Full rationale: [`../references/authoring_boundary.md`](../references/authoring_boundary.md).\n\n---\n\n## 1. SORT EACH VALUE","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md","text":"---\ntitle: Source-of-Truth Router Card\ndescription: A one-page fill-in card that sorts each value bound for a Style Reference into measured, brief-provided, inferred or absent, so a writer never fabricates a token or backfills missing data.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - source of truth router card\n  - measured or inferred card\n  - design md value provenance card\n  - is this value measured\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Source-of-Truth Router Card\n\nFill this in before writing values into a Style Reference. It sorts every value by origin so only measured values land in the token tables and nothing gets invented or backfilled. Full rationale: [`../references/authoring_boundary.md`](../references/authoring_boundary.md).\n\n---\n\n## 1. SORT EACH VALUE\n\nFor each value you are about to write, walk the questions top to bottom. The first yes decides the origin.\n\n| Question | If yes, the origin is |\n|---|---|\n| Is the value present in `tokens.json`, read off the running page? | Measured |\n| Did the user state it in the brief, not the page? | Brief-provided |\n| Are you characterizing a measured value (a name, a role, a Similar Brand)? | Inferred |\n| Did the extractor not capture it at all? | Absent |\n\nA value can have only one origin. When the brief states a value AND the extractor measured it, the measured token is the source of truth and the brief value is context.\n\n---\n\n## 2. ROUTE BY ORIGIN\n\nCopy the row for each value's origin and follow its rule.\n\n| Origin | Label | Goes where | Never |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Measured | none, it is the default | Token tables, Surfaces, Elevation, Quick Start | rounded, normalized, concretized or re-typed by hand |\n| Brief-provided | stated as the brief's intent | Prose context only | placed in a token table as if measured |\n| Inferred | `[INFERRED]` plus the token it cites | Names, roles, Similar Brands, characterizing prose | a value, fact or audience the page never showed |\n| Absent | stamped no data extracted or omitted | The section that would have held it | backfilled from a brief or a derived guess |\n\nAn unlabeled value is a promise it was measured. If you cannot point to its row in `tokens.json`, it does not go in unlabeled.\n\n---\n\n## 3. FILL IN THE DOUBTFUL VALUES\n\nList any value whose origin was not obvious, so the boundary call is on the record.\n\n| Value (what it is) | Origin (one of the four) | Token it traces to or why absent |\n|---|---|---|\n| `__________` | `__________` | `__________` |\n| `__________` | `__________` | `__________` |\n| `__________` | `__________` | `__________` |\n\nIf a row cannot name a measured token and the origin is not honestly brief-provided, inferred or absent, the value is an invention. Remove it.\n\n---\n\n## 4. STOP CHECK\n\n```text\nв–Ў Every value in a token table is measured and verbatim from tokens.json\nв–Ў No brief-provided value is sitting in a token table\nв–Ў Every inference is marked [INFERRED] and cites a measured token\nв–Ў Every absent value is stamped or omitted, none backfilled\nв–Ў You are extracting a live surface, not authoring from a brief with no site\n```\n\nIf the last box fails, this is forward-authoring. It is out of scope for this mode. Route it to the separate design-spec decision and do not loosen fidelity to fit it here.\n\n---\n\n## 5. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- [`../references/authoring_boundary.md`](../references/authoring_boundary.md) - the four origins, the source-of-truth labels and why forward-authoring stays out of scope.\n- [`cardinal_rules_card.md`](cardinal_rules_card.md) - the pre-validate fidelity checklist.\n- [`../../shared/assets/register_card.md`](../../shared/assets/register_card.md) - the Brand-vs-Product register card. This mode records the extracted surface's register.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":82,"totalLines":82,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md","time":{"start":1782532293531,"end":1782532293541}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07a1153d994a9141016a3f48c57228819195261bbfd5f219a3"}},"id":"prt_f07344399001ekmuAHV116ByjS","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","messageID":"msg_f0733e001001u7RASZufmf6CNx"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532293544,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_7CEvcKWyDTw29lsNLXQHQ1LD","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/assets/cardinal_rules_card.md","offset":1,"limit":180},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/assets/cardinal_rules_card.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Cardinal Rules Card\"\n3: description: \"One-page checklist of the fidelity rules that keep a DESIGN.md hallucination-proof, for a pre-validate self-check.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"design.md cardinal rules\"\n6:   - \"fidelity checklist\"\n7:   - \"verbatim value rule\"\n8:   - \"design md pre-validate check\"\n9: importance_tier: \"high\"\n10: contextType: \"implementation\"\n11: version: 1.0.0.3\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Cardinal Rules Card\n15: \n16: A one-page checklist of the rules that make a v3 **Style Reference** trustworthy, for a quick self-check before running validation.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: A Style Reference earns its value by being hallucination-proof AND ship-ready. These rules are the contract that property depends on; breaking any one turns the document back into a guess. Run this card before `validate.ts`.\n25: \n26: ### Usage\n27: \n28: Read top to bottom against the draft Style Reference. The value-bearing sections (Tokens вҖ” Colors, Tokens вҖ” Spacing & Shapes, Surfaces, Quick Start) are pre-rendered by `formatters-v3.ts` and pasted unchanged вҖ” verify you did not edit them. Every prose claim must be checkable with evidence in `tokens.json` or the facts block. Anything that cannot be checked is a claim to remove, not to estimate.\n29: \n30: ---\n31: \n32: ## 2. THE CHECKLIST\n33: \n34: ```text\n35: в–Ў Every hex, pixel, font-weight, shadow, and radius traces to a value in tokens.json\n36: в–Ў No value was estimated, rounded, normalized, or invented (no \"100rem\" where tokens say \"100%\")\n37: в–Ў All hex codes are 6-digit lowercase (#1a1a2e) - no #1A1A2E, #333, rgb(), hsl()\n38: в–Ў Pre-rendered sections (Tokens вҖ” Colors, Spacing & Shapes, Surfaces, Quick Start) pasted UNCHANGED\n39: в–Ў Colours are NAMED evocatively (Obsidian Ink, Voltage); each maps to a --color-<slug> token\n40: в–Ў Token column uses --color-<slug>, NEVER the extractor's --_color-primitives internal var\n41: в–Ў Components are NAMED by function (Primary CTA, Card, Badge) - no \"Variant-N\", no \"div\"\n42: в–Ў Quick Start CSS :root and Tailwind @theme: every hex/slug traces to a В§3/В§4/В§5 token row\n43: в–Ў Quick Start --page-max-width matches tokens maxContentWidth (no concretized/invented value)\n44: в–Ў L1 + L2 tokens are in the main tables; L3 only in a \"Subject to change\" sub-table; L4 excluded\n45: в–Ў Elevation is FLAT (stated plainly) when 0 shadow tokens - never \"gradient-as-depth\"\n46: в–Ў Imagery section is stamped ABSENT (_No <X> data was extracted._) when no imagery signal\n47: в–Ў No frequency dump in prose - frequency decides prominence/role, it is never printed\n48: в–Ў No false SYSTEM asserted: no \"focus is consistent\" when focusIndicator.consistent is false\n49: в–Ў DO name confidently and infer Similar Brands (grounded inference); NEVER invent a fact or audience\n50: в–Ў Any necessary inference is labeled [INFERRED] and cites a token\n51: в–Ў validate.ts passes: score >= 80 AND claimsScore >= 80, zero hex mismatches, no missing sections\n52: ```\n53: \n54: ---\n55: \n56: ## 3. STABILITY CLASS QUICK REFERENCE\n57: \n58: | Class | Keep? | Treatment |\n59: |-------|-------|-----------|\n60: | L1 Permanent | Yes | Main sections |\n61: | L2 System | Yes | Main sections |\n62: | L3 Campaign | Conditional | \"Subject to change\" annotation |\n63: | L4 Content | No | Excluded |\n64: \n65: ---\n66: \n67: ## 4. RELATED RESOURCES\n68: \n69: - [design_md_prompt_template.md](./design_md_prompt_template.md) - the WRITE-phase prompt that encodes these rules.\n70: - [../references/troubleshooting.md](../references/troubleshooting.md) - what to do when validation fails.\n\n(End of file - total 70 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Cardinal Rules Card\"\ndescription: \"One-page checklist of the fidelity rules that keep a DESIGN.md hallucination-proof, for a pre-validate self-check.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"design.md cardinal rules\"\n  - \"fidelity checklist\"\n  - \"verbatim value rule\"\n  - \"design md pre-validate check\"\nimportance_tier: \"high\"\ncontextType: \"implementation\"\nversion: 1.0.0.3\n---\n\n# Cardinal Rules Card\n\nA one-page checklist of the rules that make a v3 **Style Reference** trustworthy, for a quick self-check before running validation.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/assets/cardinal_rules_card.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Cardinal Rules Card\"\ndescription: \"One-page checklist of the fidelity rules that keep a DESIGN.md hallucination-proof, for a pre-validate self-check.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"design.md cardinal rules\"\n  - \"fidelity checklist\"\n  - \"verbatim value rule\"\n  - \"design md pre-validate check\"\nimportance_tier: \"high\"\ncontextType: \"implementation\"\nversion: 1.0.0.3\n---\n\n# Cardinal Rules Card\n\nA one-page checklist of the rules that make a v3 **Style Reference** trustworthy, for a quick self-check before running validation.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nA Style Reference earns its value by being hallucination-proof AND ship-ready. These rules are the contract that property depends on; breaking any one turns the document back into a guess. Run this card before `validate.ts`.\n\n### Usage\n\nRead top to bottom against the draft Style Reference. The value-bearing sections (Tokens вҖ” Colors, Tokens вҖ” Spacing & Shapes, Surfaces, Quick Start) are pre-rendered by `formatters-v3.ts` and pasted unchanged вҖ” verify you did not edit them. Every prose claim must be checkable with evidence in `tokens.json` or the facts block. Anything that cannot be checked is a claim to remove, not to estimate.\n\n---\n\n## 2. THE CHECKLIST\n\n```text\nв–Ў Every hex, pixel, font-weight, shadow, and radius traces to a value in tokens.json\nв–Ў No value was estimated, rounded, normalized, or invented (no \"100rem\" where tokens say \"100%\")\nв–Ў All hex codes are 6-digit lowercase (#1a1a2e) - no #1A1A2E, #333, rgb(), hsl()\nв–Ў Pre-rendered sections (Tokens вҖ” Colors, Spacing & Shapes, Surfaces, Quick Start) pasted UNCHANGED\nв–Ў Colours are NAMED evocatively (Obsidian Ink, Voltage); each maps to a --color-<slug> token\nв–Ў Token column uses --color-<slug>, NEVER the extractor's --_color-primitives internal var\nв–Ў Components are NAMED by function (Primary CTA, Card, Badge) - no \"Variant-N\", no \"div\"\nв–Ў Quick Start CSS :root and Tailwind @theme: every hex/slug traces to a В§3/В§4/В§5 token row\nв–Ў Quick Start --page-max-width matches tokens maxContentWidth (no concretized/invented value)\nв–Ў L1 + L2 tokens are in the main tables; L3 only in a \"Subject to change\" sub-table; L4 excluded\nв–Ў Elevation is FLAT (stated plainly) when 0 shadow tokens - never \"gradient-as-depth\"\nв–Ў Imagery section is stamped ABSENT (_No <X> data was extracted._) when no imagery signal\nв–Ў No frequency dump in prose - frequency decides prominence/role, it is never printed\nв–Ў No false SYSTEM asserted: no \"focus is consistent\" when focusIndicator.consistent is false\nв–Ў DO name confidently and infer Similar Brands (grounded inference); NEVER invent a fact or audience\nв–Ў Any necessary inference is labeled [INFERRED] and cites a token\nв–Ў validate.ts passes: score >= 80 AND claimsScore >= 80, zero hex mismatches, no missing sections\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. STABILITY CLASS QUICK REFERENCE\n\n| Class | Keep? | Treatment |\n|-------|-------|-----------|\n| L1 Permanent | Yes | Main sections |\n| L2 System | Yes | Main sections |\n| L3 Campaign | Conditional | \"Subject to change\" annotation |\n| L4 Content | No | Excluded |\n\n---\n\n## 4. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- [design_md_prompt_template.md](./design_md_prompt_template.md) - the WRITE-phase prompt that encodes these rules.\n- [../references/troubleshooting.md](../references/troubleshooting.md) - what to do when validation fails.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":70,"totalLines":70,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/assets/cardinal_rules_card.md","time":{"start":1782532293532,"end":1782532293542}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07a1153d994a9141016a3f48c5722c81919ccab81deb01be49"}},"id":"prt_f0734439b001LdJNsTGN1U3ktn","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","messageID":"msg_f0733e001001u7RASZufmf6CNx"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532293554,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_9c0zClx9hw20TKIVAPXoflZv","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/writing_style_guide.md","offset":1,"limit":240},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/writing_style_guide.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: DESIGN.md Writing Style Guide\n3: description: Writing quality standard for the v3 Style Reference вҖ” named, confident, restrained prose with concrete examples and banned-word discipline.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - design writing style\n6:   - banned words in design docs\n7:   - tagline and intro rules\n8:   - colour naming format\n9:   - comparative framing\n10:   - value embedding in prose\n11:   - agent prompt self-containment\n12:   - information density\n13: importance_tier: normal\n14: contextType: general\n15: version: 1.0.0.6\n16: ---\n17: # DESIGN.md Writing Style Guide\n18: \n19: Writing quality standard for the v3 **Style Reference** output (see `design_md_format.md`). The Style Reference is a named, role-driven, ship-ready design-system handoff вҖ” not an extraction report. Every value still traces verbatim to `tokens.json`; what this guide governs is the prose voice (named + restrained, not mechanical + hedged).\n20: \n21: **Division of labour (read this first).** In the v3 pipeline the value-bearing sections вҖ” `## Tokens вҖ” Colors`, `## Tokens вҖ” Spacing & Shapes`, `## Surfaces`, and `## Quick Start` вҖ” are pre-rendered deterministically by `backend/scripts/formatters-v3.ts` (a hue+lightness colour-namer and emitters) and pasted into the doc unchanged. The agent writes **prose only** (header, intro, Typography role prose, Components, Do's/Don'ts, Elevation, Imagery, Layout, Agent Prompt Guide, Similar Brands). You never hand-author a value table, so \"100rem where the tokens say 100%\" cannot happen вҖ” this guide is about making the prose worthy of the named tokens, not about transcribing numbers.\n22: \n23: ---\n24: \n25: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n26: \n27: Write like a design-systems lead handing the system off to the team that will ship it tomorrow. The reader already knows CSS, typography, and color theory -- never explain fundamentals.\n28: \n29: **Voice characteristics вҖ” named, confident, restrained:**\n30: - **Named.** Colours, components, and surfaces carry evocative, grounded names (Obsidian Ink, Voltage, Primary CTA, Canvas), never \"Color 1\" or \"Variant-1\". Naming is a grounded inference about hue, lightness, and role вҖ” it is allowed and expected.\n31: - **Confident.** State roles plainly and assign Similar Brands as grounded inference. Do not hedge every sentence with \"appears to\" or \"seems\". You are characterizing what IS there.\n32: - **Restrained.** One grounded clause, not a paragraph of metaphor. \"A warm-tinted near-black\" beats \"letters like hull plates.\" No purple prose.\n33: - **Honest.** Confident never means inventing a SYSTEM the data contradicts. No \"gradient-as-depth\" with 0 shadow tokens, no \"focus is consistent\" when `focusIndicator.consistent` is false. Name and characterize what exists; never assert a relationship the tokens deny.\n34: - **Dense, not noisy.** Every sentence carries one piece of implementation-changing information. But never dump raw mechanics: no frequency counts (\"border 9685, text 4258\"), no extractor-internal var names (`--_color-primitives---neutral--1400`), no DOM-tag labels (\"div\"). Frequency DECIDES prominence and role; it is never printed.\n35: \n36: **Audience model:** A frontend engineer absorbing the system before building a component. Do NOT assume a market audience the page never states (\"targets captains and port agents\") вҖ” characterize the design, not an imagined user.\n37: \n38: ---\n39: \n40: ## 2. Banned Words\n41: \n42: NEVER use these words in descriptive prose. They communicate nothing specific and signal that the writer ran out of things to observe:\n43: \n44: `clean`, `modern`, `sleek`, `professional`, `user-friendly`, `intuitive`, `elegant`, `beautiful`, `stunning`, `gorgeous`, `polished`, `refined`, `sophisticated`, `seamless`, `cutting-edge`, `state-of-the-art`, `next-generation`, `innovative`, `revolutionary`, `world-class`, `premium` (when used as a vague adjective rather than a pricing tier), `crisp`, `delightful`, `lovely`, `nice`, `simple` (when used approvingly without specifics)\n45: \n46: **The replacement rule:** Every banned word is a placeholder for a specific observation you have not yet made. Find the observation.\n47: \n48: | Banned phrase | What to write instead |\n49: |---|---|\n50: | \"clean design\" | \"gallery-like emptiness where section padding exceeds 80px and the only color signal comes from three workflow-specific accents\" |\n51: | \"modern typography\" | \"Inter Variable at weight 510 with OpenType `cv01` and `ss03` -- a between-weight that creates emphasis without the heaviness of traditional medium\" |\n52: | \"sleek interface\" | \"near-black canvas (`#08090a`) where content emerges through four luminance steps of semi-transparent white backgrounds\" |\n53: | \"professional color palette\" | \"achromatic system with a single chromatic accent (`#5e6ad2`) reserved exclusively for interactive elements\" |\n54: | \"intuitive layout\" | \"single-column hero with 80-120px vertical padding, collapsing to 2-3 column card grids at the feature section level\" |\n55: | \"elegant shadows\" | \"multi-layer shadow stacks where blue-tinted `rgba(50,50,93,0.25)` sits at 30px offset while neutral `rgba(0,0,0,0.1)` sits closer at 18px, creating parallax depth\" |\n56: \n57: ---\n58: \n59: ## 3. Header вҖ” Tagline Rules\n60: \n61: The header is a title line, an evocative `> tagline`, and a `**Theme:**` line:\n62: \n63: ```\n64: # <Brand or Domain> вҖ” Style Reference\n65: > <one-line evocative tagline вҖ” the design's essence in a phrase>\n66: \n67: **Theme:** light | dark | mixed\n68: ```\n69: \n70: The **tagline** is a single grounded, evocative phrase. It must do three things simultaneously:\n71: \n72: 1. **Capture the design system's essence** -- not its parameters, but its character and position\n73: 2. **Use a precise framing** that makes this system distinguishable from every other\n74: 3. **Let a reader who has never seen the site form a mental image** that would survive comparison with the real thing\n75: \n76: ### What the tagline is NOT\n77: \n78: - A parameter list: \"Uses Inter font, dark backgrounds, and purple accents.\"\n79: - A compliment or banned word: \"A beautifully designed, modern system.\"\n80: - A bare category label: \"A minimalist dark-mode design system.\"\n81: - An invented fact about the brand or its audience.\n82: \n83: ### What the tagline IS\n84: \n85: An essence capture -- one phrase that makes someone say \"I know exactly what this looks like.\" It characterizes; it never fabricates a fact.\n86: \n87: ### Example taglines\n88: \n89: > Broadsheet financial broadside вҖ” the masthead itself is the design\n90: \n91: > A near-black canvas where content emerges through four luminance steps\n92: \n93: > Developer infrastructure made invisible вҖ” restraint as a thesis\n94: \n95: ### Tagline test\n96: \n97: Ask: \"Could this phrase describe three other sites?\" If yes, it fails. A tagline must be so specific that swapping it onto a different site would feel wrong.\n98: \n99: ---\n100: \n101: ## 4. Intro Paragraph\n102: \n103: Directly under the header, one unlabeled paragraph of **4-6 sentences**. It characterizes the system's voice across these dimensions: the canvas, the dominant type move, how colour is rationed, layout density, and what carries the page. Every characterizing claim must map to a real token (a hex, a size, a weight). Restrained, not purple. No assumed audience unless the page states it.\n104: \n105: > \"The canvas is a warm-tinted near-black (`#121613`), with Obsidian Ink doing double duty as text, borders, and image frames. A single high-voltage accent (`#06458c`) is rationed strictly to interactive elements вҖ” everything else is neutral by default. Display type runs at 140px with -1.4px tracking against a 16px body, so hierarchy comes from scale, not weight. Section rhythm is spacious: large gaps frame each block as self-contained. The system is flat вҖ” no shadow tokens вҖ” and depth is carried by border contrast and whitespace alone.\"\n106: \n107: Note: every claim cites a real value, colours are named (Obsidian Ink, the accent), the flat-elevation truth is stated plainly rather than dressed up as \"gradient-as-depth\", and there is no invented audience.\n108: \n109: ### Intro test\n110: \n111: Each sentence should be deletable without making the others incomprehensible, but their combined effect is a complete picture: canvas вҶ’ type вҶ’ colour rationing вҶ’ layout вҶ’ what carries depth. A sentence with zero values is an opinion вҖ” cut it or ground it.\n112: \n113: ---\n114: \n115: ## 5. Key Characteristics Format\n116: \n117: Each key characteristic follows a strict two-part structure joined by an em-dash:\n118: \n119: ```\n120: - [Design intent / what it achieves] -- [implementation parameters / how to do it]\n121: ```\n122: \n123: The front half tells you WHY. The back half tells you WHAT. Neither half works alone.\n124: \n125: ### Good key characteristics\n126: \n127: ```\n128: - Geist Sans with extreme negative letter-spacing (-2.4px to -2.88px at display) -- text as compressed infrastructure\n129: - Shadow-as-border technique: `box-shadow 0px 0px 0px 1px` replaces traditional borders throughout\n130: - Weight 300 as the signature headline weight -- light, confident, anti-convention\n131: - Dark-mode-native: `#08090a` marketing background, `#0f1011` panel background, `#191a1b` elevated surfaces\n132: ```\n133: \n134: ### Bad key characteristics\n135: \n136: ```\n137: - Uses a nice dark color palette (no values, no contrast, \"nice\" is banned)\n138: - The font is Inter (no weight, no features, no personality)\n139: - Has good spacing (no values, no philosophy)\n140: - Borders are thin (how thin? what technique? why?)\n141: ```\n142: \n143: ### Quantity\n144: \n145: 8-12 key characteristics. Fewer means you missed something. More means you are listing parameters instead of characteristics. A characteristic is a parameter + its design significance.\n146: \n147: ---\n148: \n149: ## 6. Colour Naming (`## Tokens вҖ” Colors`)\n150: \n151: In v3 the colour table is **pre-rendered** by `formatters-v3.ts` in the `Name | Value | Token | Role` shape, most-prominent first. You do not hand-author it вҖ” but you must understand the naming style, because the Quick Start re-uses these exact slugs and the rest of your prose references colours by their names.\n152: \n153: ```\n154: | Name | Value | Token | Role |\n155: |------|-------|-------|------|\n156: | Obsidian Ink | `#121613` | `--color-obsidian-ink` | Primary text, borders, image frames вҖ” a warm-tinted near-black |\n157: | Voltage | `#06458c` | `--color-voltage` | Interactive elements only вҖ” do not promote it to a static text colour |\n158: ```\n159: \n160: Each column has a job:\n161: \n162: 1. **Name** вҖ” evocative + grounded (hue + lightness + character). Neutrals by lightness (Snow/Linen вҶ’ Ink/Obsidian/Void); hued by family + character (Voltage/Azure/Ember/Sage/Mist). Be consistent within a doc.\n163: 2. **Value** вҖ” 6-digit lowercase hex, verbatim. Gradients render their full `linear-gradient(...)` value.\n164: 3. **Token** вҖ” `--color-<kebab-name>` derived from the Name. NEVER the extractor's internal `--_color-primitives` var.\n165: 4. **Role** вҖ” where it is used (grounded in measured usage) plus one characterizing clause. No frequency numbers. For a supporting accent, add a usage guard (\"Do not promote it to the primary CTA color\").\n166: \n167: ### Good role clauses\n168: \n169: > Primary text, borders, image frames вҖ” a warm-tinted near-black\n170: \n171: > Card surfaces вҖ” same hex as canvas, so cards are defined by radius and padding, not fill\n172: \n173: ### Bad role clauses\n174: \n175: > Used for buttons. (No character, no usage guard)\n176: \n177: > The colour that appears 9685 times. (Frequency dump вҖ” frequency decides prominence, it is never printed)\n178: \n179: > `--_color-primitives---neutral--1400`. (Extractor-internal var leaked into the token column)\n180: \n181: ### The characterizing clause\n182: \n183: It describes visual quality, not emotional reaction, and never restates the hex in words. \"A warm-tinted near-black\" tells you something measurable. \"Beautiful dark colour\" does not. L1/L2 colours go in the main table; L3 in a `### Current Campaign Colors (Subject to change)` sub-table; L4 is excluded entirely.\n184: \n185: ---\n186: \n187: ## 7. Value Embedding\n188: \n189: Design values (font sizes, letter-spacing, weights, hex codes, opacity values) must be woven into prose. They never stand alone as facts.\n190: \n191: ### The rule\n192: \n193: A value without context is a spec sheet entry. A value inside a sentence that explains its effect is design documentation.\n194: \n195: ### Good value embedding\n196: \n197: > \"The aggressive negative letter-spacing (-2.4px at display sizes) creates text that feels minified for production.\"\n198: \n199: > \"The 510 weight sits between regular and medium, creating a subtle emphasis that doesn't shout.\"\n200: \n201: > \"Individual shadow layer opacity never exceeds 0.05, producing ambient occlusion that feels like natural light rather than computer-generated depth.\"\n202: \n203: ### Bad value embedding\n204: \n205: > \"Letter spacing: -2.4px. This creates compression.\"\n206: \n207: Two sentences where one would do. The value and its effect are separated, making the reader do assembly work.\n208: \n209: > \"The letter-spacing is -2.4px.\"\n210: \n211: A fact with no consequence. Why should someone care that it is -2.4px? What does -2.4px produce that -1px or -0.5px does not?\n212: \n213: > \"Font size: 48px, Weight: 600, Line height: 1.00, Letter spacing: -2.4px\"\n214: \n215: A parameter dump. This belongs in a table, not in prose. Prose exists to explain what tables cannot: the relationships between parameters and the reasons behind choices.\n216: \n217: ### Where values DO stand alone\n218: \n219: Tables, component specs, and agent prompt guides. These are reference contexts where scanability matters more than narrative. In those contexts, every value should be present and findable. In prose sections, values are evidence for claims.\n220: \n221: ---\n222: \n223: ## 8. Do's and Don'ts Quality\n224: \n225: The Do's and Don'ts section is where most DESIGN.md files fail. Generic advice wastes the reader's time. Every entry must pass the specificity test.\n226: \n227: ### Don'ts: The Counter-Intuitive Test\n228: \n229: A good Don't tells the reader something they would naturally do that is WRONG in this specific system. It should surprise someone who knows CSS and design but does not know this particular system.\n230: \n231: **Each Don't needs three components:**\n232: 1. What not to do\n233: 2. Why it is wrong in THIS system (not in general)\n234: 3. What to do instead (with at least one specific value)\n235: \n236: ### Good Don'ts\n237: \n238: > \"Don't use weight 600-700 for sohne-var headlines -- weight 300 is the brand voice\"\n239: \n240: Counter-intuitive: most systems use heavy weights for headlines. The reader would default to 600+ without this warning.\n\n(Showing lines 1-240 of 786. Use offset=241 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: DESIGN.md Writing Style Guide\ndescription: Writing quality standard for the v3 Style Reference вҖ” named, confident, restrained prose with concrete examples and banned-word discipline.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - design writing style\n  - banned words in design docs\n  - tagline and intro rules\n  - colour naming format\n  - comparative framing\n  - value embedding in prose\n  - agent prompt self-containment\n  - information density\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.6\n---\n# DESIGN.md Writing Style Guide\n\nWriting quality standard for the v3 **Style Reference** output (see `design_md_format.md`). The Style Reference is a named, role-driven, ship-ready design-system handoff вҖ” not an extraction report. Every value still traces verbatim to `tokens.json`; what this guide governs is the prose voice (named + restrained, not mechanical + hedged).\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/writing_style_guide.md","text":"---\ntitle: DESIGN.md Writing Style Guide\ndescription: Writing quality standard for the v3 Style Reference вҖ” named, confident, restrained prose with concrete examples and banned-word discipline.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - design writing style\n  - banned words in design docs\n  - tagline and intro rules\n  - colour naming format\n  - comparative framing\n  - value embedding in prose\n  - agent prompt self-containment\n  - information density\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.6\n---\n# DESIGN.md Writing Style Guide\n\nWriting quality standard for the v3 **Style Reference** output (see `design_md_format.md`). The Style Reference is a named, role-driven, ship-ready design-system handoff вҖ” not an extraction report. Every value still traces verbatim to `tokens.json`; what this guide governs is the prose voice (named + restrained, not mechanical + hedged).\n\n**Division of labour (read this first).** In the v3 pipeline the value-bearing sections вҖ” `## Tokens вҖ” Colors`, `## Tokens вҖ” Spacing & Shapes`, `## Surfaces`, and `## Quick Start` вҖ” are pre-rendered deterministically by `backend/scripts/formatters-v3.ts` (a hue+lightness colour-namer and emitters) and pasted into the doc unchanged. The agent writes **prose only** (header, intro, Typography role prose, Components, Do's/Don'ts, Elevation, Imagery, Layout, Agent Prompt Guide, Similar Brands). You never hand-author a value table, so \"100rem where the tokens say 100%\" cannot happen вҖ” this guide is about making the prose worthy of the named tokens, not about transcribing numbers.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nWrite like a design-systems lead handing the system off to the team that will ship it tomorrow. The reader already knows CSS, typography, and color theory -- never explain fundamentals.\n\n**Voice characteristics вҖ” named, confident, restrained:**\n- **Named.** Colours, components, and surfaces carry evocative, grounded names (Obsidian Ink, Voltage, Primary CTA, Canvas), never \"Color 1\" or \"Variant-1\". Naming is a grounded inference about hue, lightness, and role вҖ” it is allowed and expected.\n- **Confident.** State roles plainly and assign Similar Brands as grounded inference. Do not hedge every sentence with \"appears to\" or \"seems\". You are characterizing what IS there.\n- **Restrained.** One grounded clause, not a paragraph of metaphor. \"A warm-tinted near-black\" beats \"letters like hull plates.\" No purple prose.\n- **Honest.** Confident never means inventing a SYSTEM the data contradicts. No \"gradient-as-depth\" with 0 shadow tokens, no \"focus is consistent\" when `focusIndicator.consistent` is false. Name and characterize what exists; never assert a relationship the tokens deny.\n- **Dense, not noisy.** Every sentence carries one piece of implementation-changing information. But never dump raw mechanics: no frequency counts (\"border 9685, text 4258\"), no extractor-internal var names (`--_color-primitives---neutral--1400`), no DOM-tag labels (\"div\"). Frequency DECIDES prominence and role; it is never printed.\n\n**Audience model:** A frontend engineer absorbing the system before building a component. Do NOT assume a market audience the page never states (\"targets captains and port agents\") вҖ” characterize the design, not an imagined user.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Banned Words\n\nNEVER use these words in descriptive prose. They communicate nothing specific and signal that the writer ran out of things to observe:\n\n`clean`, `modern`, `sleek`, `professional`, `user-friendly`, `intuitive`, `elegant`, `beautiful`, `stunning`, `gorgeous`, `polished`, `refined`, `sophisticated`, `seamless`, `cutting-edge`, `state-of-the-art`, `next-generation`, `innovative`, `revolutionary`, `world-class`, `premium` (when used as a vague adjective rather than a pricing tier), `crisp`, `delightful`, `lovely`, `nice`, `simple` (when used approvingly without specifics)\n\n**The replacement rule:** Every banned word is a placeholder for a specific observation you have not yet made. Find the observation.\n\n| Banned phrase | What to write instead |\n|---|---|\n| \"clean design\" | \"gallery-like emptiness where section padding exceeds 80px and the only color signal comes from three workflow-specific accents\" |\n| \"modern typography\" | \"Inter Variable at weight 510 with OpenType `cv01` and `ss03` -- a between-weight that creates emphasis without the heaviness of traditional medium\" |\n| \"sleek interface\" | \"near-black canvas (`#08090a`) where content emerges through four luminance steps of semi-transparent white backgrounds\" |\n| \"professional color palette\" | \"achromatic system with a single chromatic accent (`#5e6ad2`) reserved exclusively for interactive elements\" |\n| \"intuitive layout\" | \"single-column hero with 80-120px vertical padding, collapsing to 2-3 column card grids at the feature section level\" |\n| \"elegant shadows\" | \"multi-layer shadow stacks where blue-tinted `rgba(50,50,93,0.25)` sits at 30px offset while neutral `rgba(0,0,0,0.1)` sits closer at 18px, creating parallax depth\" |\n\n---\n\n## 3. Header вҖ” Tagline Rules\n\nThe header is a title line, an evocative `> tagline`, and a `**Theme:**` line:\n\n```\n# <Brand or Domain> вҖ” Style Reference\n> <one-line evocative tagline вҖ” the design's essence in a phrase>\n\n**Theme:** light | dark | mixed\n```\n\nThe **tagline** is a single grounded, evocative phrase. It must do three things simultaneously:\n\n1. **Capture the design system's essence** -- not its parameters, but its character and position\n2. **Use a precise framing** that makes this system distinguishable from every other\n3. **Let a reader who has never seen the site form a mental image** that would survive comparison with the real thing\n\n### What the tagline is NOT\n\n- A parameter list: \"Uses Inter font, dark backgrounds, and purple accents.\"\n- A compliment or banned word: \"A beautifully designed, modern system.\"\n- A bare category label: \"A minimalist dark-mode design system.\"\n- An invented fact about the brand or its audience.\n\n### What the tagline IS\n\nAn essence capture -- one phrase that makes someone say \"I know exactly what this looks like.\" It characterizes; it never fabricates a fact.\n\n### Example taglines\n\n> Broadsheet financial broadside вҖ” the masthead itself is the design\n\n> A near-black canvas where content emerges through four luminance steps\n\n> Developer infrastructure made invisible вҖ” restraint as a thesis\n\n### Tagline test\n\nAsk: \"Could this phrase describe three other sites?\" If yes, it fails. A tagline must be so specific that swapping it onto a different site would feel wrong.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Intro Paragraph\n\nDirectly under the header, one unlabeled paragraph of **4-6 sentences**. It characterizes the system's voice across these dimensions: the canvas, the dominant type move, how colour is rationed, layout density, and what carries the page. Every characterizing claim must map to a real token (a hex, a size, a weight). Restrained, not purple. No assumed audience unless the page states it.\n\n> \"The canvas is a warm-tinted near-black (`#121613`), with Obsidian Ink doing double duty as text, borders, and image frames. A single high-voltage accent (`#06458c`) is rationed strictly to interactive elements вҖ” everything else is neutral by default. Display type runs at 140px with -1.4px tracking against a 16px body, so hierarchy comes from scale, not weight. Section rhythm is spacious: large gaps frame each block as self-contained. The system is flat вҖ” no shadow tokens вҖ” and depth is carried by border contrast and whitespace alone.\"\n\nNote: every claim cites a real value, colours are named (Obsidian Ink, the accent), the flat-elevation truth is stated plainly rather than dressed up as \"gradient-as-depth\", and there is no invented audience.\n\n### Intro test\n\nEach sentence should be deletable without making the others incomprehensible, but their combined effect is a complete picture: canvas вҶ’ type вҶ’ colour rationing вҶ’ layout вҶ’ what carries depth. A sentence with zero values is an opinion вҖ” cut it or ground it.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Key Characteristics Format\n\nEach key characteristic follows a strict two-part structure joined by an em-dash:\n\n```\n- [Design intent / what it achieves] -- [implementation parameters / how to do it]\n```\n\nThe front half tells you WHY. The back half tells you WHAT. Neither half works alone.\n\n### Good key characteristics\n\n```\n- Geist Sans with extreme negative letter-spacing (-2.4px to -2.88px at display) -- text as compressed infrastructure\n- Shadow-as-border technique: `box-shadow 0px 0px 0px 1px` replaces traditional borders throughout\n- Weight 300 as the signature headline weight -- light, confident, anti-convention\n- Dark-mode-native: `#08090a` marketing background, `#0f1011` panel background, `#191a1b` elevated surfaces\n```\n\n### Bad key characteristics\n\n```\n- Uses a nice dark color palette (no values, no contrast, \"nice\" is banned)\n- The font is Inter (no weight, no features, no personality)\n- Has good spacing (no values, no philosophy)\n- Borders are thin (how thin? what technique? why?)\n```\n\n### Quantity\n\n8-12 key characteristics. Fewer means you missed something. More means you are listing parameters instead of characteristics. A characteristic is a parameter + its design significance.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Colour Naming (`## Tokens вҖ” Colors`)\n\nIn v3 the colour table is **pre-rendered** by `formatters-v3.ts` in the `Name | Value | Token | Role` shape, most-prominent first. You do not hand-author it вҖ” but you must understand the naming style, because the Quick Start re-uses these exact slugs and the rest of your prose references colours by their names.\n\n```\n| Name | Value | Token | Role |\n|------|-------|-------|------|\n| Obsidian Ink | `#121613` | `--color-obsidian-ink` | Primary text, borders, image frames вҖ” a warm-tinted near-black |\n| Voltage | `#06458c` | `--color-voltage` | Interactive elements only вҖ” do not promote it to a static text colour |\n```\n\nEach column has a job:\n\n1. **Name** вҖ” evocative + grounded (hue + lightness + character). Neutrals by lightness (Snow/Linen вҶ’ Ink/Obsidian/Void); hued by family + character (Voltage/Azure/Ember/Sage/Mist). Be consistent within a doc.\n2. **Value** вҖ” 6-digit lowercase hex, verbatim. Gradients render their full `linear-gradient(...)` value.\n3. **Token** вҖ” `--color-<kebab-name>` derived from the Name. NEVER the extractor's internal `--_color-primitives` var.\n4. **Role** вҖ” where it is used (grounded in measured usage) plus one characterizing clause. No frequency numbers. For a supporting accent, add a usage guard (\"Do not promote it to the primary CTA color\").\n\n### Good role clauses\n\n> Primary text, borders, image frames вҖ” a warm-tinted near-black\n\n> Card surfaces вҖ” same hex as canvas, so cards are defined by radius and padding, not fill\n\n### Bad role clauses\n\n> Used for buttons. (No character, no usage guard)\n\n> The colour that appears 9685 times. (Frequency dump вҖ” frequency decides prominence, it is never printed)\n\n> `--_color-primitives---neutral--1400`. (Extractor-internal var leaked into the token column)\n\n### The characterizing clause\n\nIt describes visual quality, not emotional reaction, and never restates the hex in words. \"A warm-tinted near-black\" tells you something measurable. \"Beautiful dark colour\" does not. L1/L2 colours go in the main table; L3 in a `### Current Campaign Colors (Subject to change)` sub-table; L4 is excluded entirely.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Value Embedding\n\nDesign values (font sizes, letter-spacing, weights, hex codes, opacity values) must be woven into prose. They never stand alone as facts.\n\n### The rule\n\nA value without context is a spec sheet entry. A value inside a sentence that explains its effect is design documentation.\n\n### Good value embedding\n\n> \"The aggressive negative letter-spacing (-2.4px at display sizes) creates text that feels minified for production.\"\n\n> \"The 510 weight sits between regular and medium, creating a subtle emphasis that doesn't shout.\"\n\n> \"Individual shadow layer opacity never exceeds 0.05, producing ambient occlusion that feels like natural light rather than computer-generated depth.\"\n\n### Bad value embedding\n\n> \"Letter spacing: -2.4px. This creates compression.\"\n\nTwo sentences where one would do. The value and its effect are separated, making the reader do assembly work.\n\n> \"The letter-spacing is -2.4px.\"\n\nA fact with no consequence. Why should someone care that it is -2.4px? What does -2.4px produce that -1px or -0.5px does not?\n\n> \"Font size: 48px, Weight: 600, Line height: 1.00, Letter spacing: -2.4px\"\n\nA parameter dump. This belongs in a table, not in prose. Prose exists to explain what tables cannot: the relationships between parameters and the reasons behind choices.\n\n### Where values DO stand alone\n\nTables, component specs, and agent prompt guides. These are reference contexts where scanability matters more than narrative. In those contexts, every value should be present and findable. In prose sections, values are evidence for claims.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Do's and Don'ts Quality\n\nThe Do's and Don'ts section is where most DESIGN.md files fail. Generic advice wastes the reader's time. Every entry must pass the specificity test.\n\n### Don'ts: The Counter-Intuitive Test\n\nA good Don't tells the reader something they would naturally do that is WRONG in this specific system. It should surprise someone who knows CSS and design but does not know this particular system.\n\n**Each Don't needs three components:**\n1. What not to do\n2. Why it is wrong in THIS system (not in general)\n3. What to do instead (with at least one specific value)\n\n### Good Don'ts\n\n> \"Don't use weight 600-700 for sohne-var headlines -- weight 300 is the brand voice\"\n\nCounter-intuitive: most systems use heavy weights for headlines. The reader would default to 600+ without this warning.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":240,"totalLines":786,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/writing_style_guide.md","time":{"start":1782532293527,"end":1782532293550}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07a1153d994a9141016a3f48c5721c819184a143c88506c5a2"}},"id":"prt_f07344396001Y51Jv1i3e3IeFD","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","messageID":"msg_f0733e001001u7RASZufmf6CNx"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532293554,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_uUsiKI14JOdcX1o27WVeBBmp","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/lineages/gpt55fast/research.md","offset":80,"limit":100},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/lineages/gpt55fast/research.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n80: | P1 | Asset | `assets/animate_presence_checklist.md` | Exit wrapper, exit prop, key, symmetry, presence hook, safeToRemove, mode, and nested-exit checks. | AnimatePresence priority categories and rules [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/mastering-animate-presence.md:21]. | 0.5d |\n81: | P1 | Asset | `assets/motion_performance_failure_card.md` | Failure-mode card for layout thrash, scroll polling, endless rAF, mixed systems, layer promotion, paint-heavy effects, and blur. | `fixing-motion-performance` quick reference [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/fixing-motion-performance.md:52]. | 0.5d |\n82: | P2 | Reference subsection | Add `polish_details` to `micro_interactions.md` | Concentric radii, optical alignment, tabular numbers, image outlines, scale-on-press, and transition-property rules. | `make-interfaces-feel-better` core principles [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/make-interfaces-feel-better.md:19]. | 0.5d |\n83: \n84: Do not add:\n85: \n86: - Overdrive/advanced rendering as core motion behavior. Prior gap analysis classifies advanced rendering as nice-to-have [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md:30].\n87: - A default rule that all interfaces must be motion-rich. Current success criteria require motion not to exhaust the user [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:306].\n88: \n89: ### 3.5 `design-audit`\n90: \n91: | Priority | Type | Proposed file | What it adds | Sources | Effort |\n92: |---|---|---|---|---|---|\n93: | P1 | Reference | `references/evidence_capture.md` | Evidence model for file/source target resolution, browser evidence, deterministic scans, screenshot/overlay notes, and fallback labels. | `critique` requires independent assessment and detector/browser evidence [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/critique.md:12]. | 1.0d |\n94: | P1 | Asset | `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md` | Snippet-level fixes for accessible names, keyboard, focus/dialogs, semantics, forms/errors, announcements, contrast, and motion. | `fixing-accessibility` priority categories and quick fixes [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/fixing-accessibility.md:33]. | 0.75d |\n95: | P1 | Reference | `references/hardening_edge_cases.md` | Production-readiness matrix for extreme inputs, API/network errors, permissions, rate limits, concurrency, i18n, RTL, text expansion, and CJK/emoji. | `harden` edge-case assessment [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/harden.md:14]. | 0.75d |\n96: | P1 | Reference | `references/transform_remediation.md` | Maps bolder/quieter/distill/redesign verbs to findings, owner mode, and accepted remediation path. | Prior gap analysis flags transform verbs and redesign/remediation as should-adds [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md:17]. | 0.75d |\n97: | P2 | Asset | `assets/audit_report_template.md` | Findings-first report skeleton with score, anti-pattern verdict, positive findings, priority issues, owner mapping, and evidence caveats. | `audit` five-dimension score and severity contract [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/audit.md:12]. | 0.5d |\n98: \n99: Do not add:\n100: \n101: - Fix implementation into audit. Current audit integration delegates direction to interface, color/type/layout to foundations, motion to motion, and implementation to sk-code [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:337].\n102: - Full two-sub-agent critique orchestration from `critique.md`; keep only evidence principles unless a later workflow packet owns orchestration.\n103: \n104: ### 3.6 `design-md-generator`\n105: \n106: | Priority | Type | Proposed file | What it adds | Sources | Effort |\n107: |---|---|---|---|---|---|\n108: | P1 | Reference | `references/authoring_boundary.md` | Distinguishes measured extraction, brief-authored Style Reference, and hybrid extension; defines source-of-truth labels and fidelity constraints. | Current cardinal fidelity rule [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:248]; `stitch-skill` forward authoring goal [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/stitch-skill.md:17]. | 1.0d |\n109: | P1 | Asset | `assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md` | Quick card that asks: measured tokens, brief-provided values, inferred style direction, or missing backing data? Prevents fabricated values. | v3 format cardinal rules [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/design_md_format.md:27]. | 0.5d |\n110: | P1 | Asset | `assets/brief_to_style_reference_prompt.md` | Prompt skeleton for non-extraction authoring that requires explicit labels for measured, brief-provided, inferred, and absent sections. | `stitch-skill` output structure [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/stitch-skill.md:115]; writing guide voice rules [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/writing_style_guide.md:29]. | 0.75d |\n111: | P2 | Reference subsection | Add component decision examples to `component_taxonomy.md` | Enriches component selection guide with examples for dialog/toast/banner, card/list/table, dropdown/radio/segmented control where needed. | Current component taxonomy already defines Use lines and decision logic [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/component_taxonomy.md:347]. | 0.25d |\n112: \n113: Do not add:\n114: \n115: - A second extraction backend or crawler path. Current pipeline already extracts, writes, validates, and reports [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:206].\n116: - A rename or new `design-spec` child in this phase. The phase scope excludes taxonomy changes [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/spec.md:53].\n117: \n118: ## 4. Implementation Sequence\n119: \n120: | Step | Scope | Why first |\n121: |---|---|---|\n122: | 1 | `shared/register.md` and `shared/assets/register_card.md` | Gates multiple mode decisions and prior gap analysis marks it must-add. |\n123: | 2 | `design-interface/assets/interface_preflight_card.md` plus `brief_to_dials.md` | Highest operator leverage; converts taste corpus into repeatable checks. |\n124: | 3 | `design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md` and `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md` | Makes review/fix guidance evidence-backed before new content expands. |\n125: | 4 | `foundations` register/data-viz/adaptation references | Completes static visual-system gaps without duplicating basics. |\n126: | 5 | `motion` pattern/performance assets | Packages already-known rules into reusable cards. |\n127: | 6 | `md-generator` authoring boundary and prompt skeleton | Adds forward authoring while protecting cardinal fidelity. |\n128: \n129: ## 5. Do-Not-Add List\n130: \n131: - Do not reopen parent taxonomy or architecture.\n132: - Do not create net-new sub-skills.\n133: - Do not import the full `designer-skills-main` process lifecycle.\n134: - Do not import slides/canvas/poster workflows into the five current modes unless a later scope ruling approves presentation work.\n135: - Do not add generic anti-truncation output guidance; prior analysis classifies `output-skill` as out-of-family [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md:36].\n136: - Do not add GSAP-heavy or motion-rich defaults to all interface/motion work.\n137: - Do not expand `md-generator` by inventing values or weakening `tokens.json` fidelity.\n138: - Do not add large references without an associated mode owner and a concrete operator action.\n139: \n140: ## 6. Residual Risks\n141: \n142: - Exact effort estimates are inferred from document size and current skill patterns; implementation should calibrate them against template and validation work.\n143: - Some external corpus advice is aggressive and landing-page-specific. Implementation must label those references as conditional rather than default.\n144: - `md-generator` forward authoring is the highest-risk addition because it can blur measured vs inferred truth. It needs explicit source labels and validation language before use.\n145: \n146: ## 7. References\n147: \n148: ### Prior research\n149: \n150: - `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/research.md`\n151: - `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md`\n152: - `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/spec.md`\n153: \n154: ### Live skill state\n155: \n156: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md`\n157: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md`\n158: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md`\n159: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md`\n160: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md`\n161: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/anti_slop_principles.md`\n162: \n163: ### External corpus\n164: \n165: - `external/taste-skill.md`\n166: - `external/gpt-tasteskill.md`\n167: - `external/colorize.md`\n168: - `external/layout.md`\n169: - `external/adapt.md`\n170: - `external/interaction-design.md`\n171: - `external/animate.md`\n172: - `external/mastering-animate-presence.md`\n173: - `external/fixing-motion-performance.md`\n174: - `external/make-interfaces-feel-better.md`\n175: - `external/audit.md`\n176: - `external/critique.md`\n177: - `external/fixing-accessibility.md`\n178: - `external/harden.md`\n179: - `external/stitch-skill.md`\n\n(End of file - total 179 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"| P1 | Asset | `assets/animate_presence_checklist.md` | Exit wrapper, exit prop, key, symmetry, presence hook, safeToRemove, mode, and nested-exit checks. | AnimatePresence priority categories and rules [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/mastering-animate-presence.md:21]. | 0.5d |\n| P1 | Asset | `assets/motion_performance_failure_card.md` | Failure-mode card for layout thrash, scroll polling, endless rAF, mixed systems, layer promotion, paint-heavy effects, and blur. | `fixing-motion-performance` quick reference [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/fixing-motion-performance.md:52]. | 0.5d |\n| P2 | Reference subsection | Add `polish_details` to `micro_interactions.md` | Concentric radii, optical alignment, tabular numbers, image outlines, scale-on-press, and transition-property rules. | `make-interfaces-feel-better` core principles [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/make-interfaces-feel-better.md:19]. | 0.5d |\n\nDo not add:\n\n- Overdrive/advanced rendering as core motion behavior. Prior gap analysis classifies advanced rendering as nice-to-have [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md:30].\n- A default rule that all interfaces must be motion-rich. Current success criteria require motion not to exhaust the user [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:306].\n\n### 3.5 `design-audit`\n\n| Priority | Type | Proposed file | What it adds | Sources | Effort |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| P1 | Reference | `references/evidence_capture.md` | Evidence model for file/source target resolution, browser evidence, deterministic scans, screenshot/overlay notes, and fallback labels. | `critique` requires independent assessment and detector/browser evidence [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/critique.md:12]. | 1.0d |\n| P1 | Asset | `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md` | Snippet-level fixes for accessible names, keyboard, focus/dialogs, semantics, forms/errors, announcements, contrast, and motion. | `fixing-accessibility` priority categories and quick fixes [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/fixing-accessibility.md:33]. | 0.75d |\n| P1 | Reference | `references/hardening_edge_cases.md` | Production-readiness matrix for extreme inputs, API/network errors, permissions, rate limits, concurrency, i18n, RTL, text expansion, and CJK/emoji. | `harden` edge-case assessment [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/harden.md:14]. | 0.75d |\n| P1 | Reference | `references/transform_remediation.md` | Maps bolder/quieter/distill/redesign verbs to findings, owner mode, and accepted remediation path. | Prior gap analysis flags transform verbs and redesign/remediation as should-adds [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md:17]. | 0.75d |\n| P2 | Asset | `assets/audit_report_template.md` | Findings-first report skeleton with score, anti-pattern verdict, positive findings, priority issues, owner mapping, and evidence caveats. | `audit` five-dimension score and severity contract [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/audit.md:12]. | 0.5d |\n\nDo not add:","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/lineages/gpt55fast/research.md","text":"| P1 | Asset | `assets/animate_presence_checklist.md` | Exit wrapper, exit prop, key, symmetry, presence hook, safeToRemove, mode, and nested-exit checks. | AnimatePresence priority categories and rules [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/mastering-animate-presence.md:21]. | 0.5d |\n| P1 | Asset | `assets/motion_performance_failure_card.md` | Failure-mode card for layout thrash, scroll polling, endless rAF, mixed systems, layer promotion, paint-heavy effects, and blur. | `fixing-motion-performance` quick reference [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/fixing-motion-performance.md:52]. | 0.5d |\n| P2 | Reference subsection | Add `polish_details` to `micro_interactions.md` | Concentric radii, optical alignment, tabular numbers, image outlines, scale-on-press, and transition-property rules. | `make-interfaces-feel-better` core principles [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/make-interfaces-feel-better.md:19]. | 0.5d |\n\nDo not add:\n\n- Overdrive/advanced rendering as core motion behavior. Prior gap analysis classifies advanced rendering as nice-to-have [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md:30].\n- A default rule that all interfaces must be motion-rich. Current success criteria require motion not to exhaust the user [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:306].\n\n### 3.5 `design-audit`\n\n| Priority | Type | Proposed file | What it adds | Sources | Effort |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| P1 | Reference | `references/evidence_capture.md` | Evidence model for file/source target resolution, browser evidence, deterministic scans, screenshot/overlay notes, and fallback labels. | `critique` requires independent assessment and detector/browser evidence [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/critique.md:12]. | 1.0d |\n| P1 | Asset | `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md` | Snippet-level fixes for accessible names, keyboard, focus/dialogs, semantics, forms/errors, announcements, contrast, and motion. | `fixing-accessibility` priority categories and quick fixes [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/fixing-accessibility.md:33]. | 0.75d |\n| P1 | Reference | `references/hardening_edge_cases.md` | Production-readiness matrix for extreme inputs, API/network errors, permissions, rate limits, concurrency, i18n, RTL, text expansion, and CJK/emoji. | `harden` edge-case assessment [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/harden.md:14]. | 0.75d |\n| P1 | Reference | `references/transform_remediation.md` | Maps bolder/quieter/distill/redesign verbs to findings, owner mode, and accepted remediation path. | Prior gap analysis flags transform verbs and redesign/remediation as should-adds [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md:17]. | 0.75d |\n| P2 | Asset | `assets/audit_report_template.md` | Findings-first report skeleton with score, anti-pattern verdict, positive findings, priority issues, owner mapping, and evidence caveats. | `audit` five-dimension score and severity contract [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/audit.md:12]. | 0.5d |\n\nDo not add:\n\n- Fix implementation into audit. Current audit integration delegates direction to interface, color/type/layout to foundations, motion to motion, and implementation to sk-code [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:337].\n- Full two-sub-agent critique orchestration from `critique.md`; keep only evidence principles unless a later workflow packet owns orchestration.\n\n### 3.6 `design-md-generator`\n\n| Priority | Type | Proposed file | What it adds | Sources | Effort |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| P1 | Reference | `references/authoring_boundary.md` | Distinguishes measured extraction, brief-authored Style Reference, and hybrid extension; defines source-of-truth labels and fidelity constraints. | Current cardinal fidelity rule [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:248]; `stitch-skill` forward authoring goal [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/stitch-skill.md:17]. | 1.0d |\n| P1 | Asset | `assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md` | Quick card that asks: measured tokens, brief-provided values, inferred style direction, or missing backing data? Prevents fabricated values. | v3 format cardinal rules [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/design_md_format.md:27]. | 0.5d |\n| P1 | Asset | `assets/brief_to_style_reference_prompt.md` | Prompt skeleton for non-extraction authoring that requires explicit labels for measured, brief-provided, inferred, and absent sections. | `stitch-skill` output structure [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/stitch-skill.md:115]; writing guide voice rules [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/writing_style_guide.md:29]. | 0.75d |\n| P2 | Reference subsection | Add component decision examples to `component_taxonomy.md` | Enriches component selection guide with examples for dialog/toast/banner, card/list/table, dropdown/radio/segmented control where needed. | Current component taxonomy already defines Use lines and decision logic [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/component_taxonomy.md:347]. | 0.25d |\n\nDo not add:\n\n- A second extraction backend or crawler path. Current pipeline already extracts, writes, validates, and reports [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:206].\n- A rename or new `design-spec` child in this phase. The phase scope excludes taxonomy changes [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/spec.md:53].\n\n## 4. Implementation Sequence\n\n| Step | Scope | Why first |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | `shared/register.md` and `shared/assets/register_card.md` | Gates multiple mode decisions and prior gap analysis marks it must-add. |\n| 2 | `design-interface/assets/interface_preflight_card.md` plus `brief_to_dials.md` | Highest operator leverage; converts taste corpus into repeatable checks. |\n| 3 | `design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md` and `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md` | Makes review/fix guidance evidence-backed before new content expands. |\n| 4 | `foundations` register/data-viz/adaptation references | Completes static visual-system gaps without duplicating basics. |\n| 5 | `motion` pattern/performance assets | Packages already-known rules into reusable cards. |\n| 6 | `md-generator` authoring boundary and prompt skeleton | Adds forward authoring while protecting cardinal fidelity. |\n\n## 5. Do-Not-Add List\n\n- Do not reopen parent taxonomy or architecture.\n- Do not create net-new sub-skills.\n- Do not import the full `designer-skills-main` process lifecycle.\n- Do not import slides/canvas/poster workflows into the five current modes unless a later scope ruling approves presentation work.\n- Do not add generic anti-truncation output guidance; prior analysis classifies `output-skill` as out-of-family [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md:36].\n- Do not add GSAP-heavy or motion-rich defaults to all interface/motion work.\n- Do not expand `md-generator` by inventing values or weakening `tokens.json` fidelity.\n- Do not add large references without an associated mode owner and a concrete operator action.\n\n## 6. Residual Risks\n\n- Exact effort estimates are inferred from document size and current skill patterns; implementation should calibrate them against template and validation work.\n- Some external corpus advice is aggressive and landing-page-specific. Implementation must label those references as conditional rather than default.\n- `md-generator` forward authoring is the highest-risk addition because it can blur measured vs inferred truth. It needs explicit source labels and validation language before use.\n\n## 7. References\n\n### Prior research\n\n- `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/research.md`\n- `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md`\n- `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/spec.md`\n\n### Live skill state\n\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/anti_slop_principles.md`\n\n### External corpus\n\n- `external/taste-skill.md`\n- `external/gpt-tasteskill.md`\n- `external/colorize.md`\n- `external/layout.md`\n- `external/adapt.md`\n- `external/interaction-design.md`\n- `external/animate.md`\n- `external/mastering-animate-presence.md`\n- `external/fixing-motion-performance.md`\n- `external/make-interfaces-feel-better.md`\n- `external/audit.md`\n- `external/critique.md`\n- `external/fixing-accessibility.md`\n- `external/harden.md`\n- `external/stitch-skill.md`","lineStart":80,"lineEnd":179,"totalLines":179,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/lineages/gpt55fast/research.md","time":{"start":1782532293521,"end":1782532293551}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07a1153d994a9141016a3f48c572088191be8aa0fce5ce17c0"}},"id":"prt_f0734438b001WC8mZmSOEU5BzN","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c98ffe3IWN2NyShq3kW9","messageID":"msg_f0733e001001u7RASZufmf6CNx"}}
